<h2>Meet the Panelists</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

From: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York<br>
Date: Mon July 22 11:28:40 1996<br>
Subject: MEET THE PANELISTS<p>

Last Append: Wed July 31 09:56:22 1996<p>

TED CURTIS (Seminar Moderator) is a sports attorney and writer in Boca Raton, Florida. He is an attorney with the University of South Florida, General Counsel to the Ft. Lauderdale-based Sport Theory Center, and the co-moderator of the Counsel Connect's Sports Law forum. He also is the news editor of The Sports Lawyer -- the bimonthly publication of the Sports Lawyers Association -- and has written on issues in sports law, business and finance for national and regional publications for seven years.<p>   

MARIA DENNIS (Seminar Moderator) is co-moderator of the Sports Law forum. Maria is an associate with Jones, Day, Reavis & Pogue in Los Angeles, and a graduate of Georgetown University Law Center and Yale University. Her involvement with sports law mainly derives from Maria's involvement on the Board of Directors of USA Hockey (the governing body of all amateur ice hockey in the United States) and her position on the Athletes' Advisory Council to the United States Olympic Committee. (And of course a natural interest in sports which predates law school.) Her involvement in these organizations is based upon her participation on the women's national ice hockey team in the first women's World Tournament in 1990 where her team captured a silver medal. The tournament paved the way for women's ice hockey to become an Olympic sport in the 1998 Nagano Winter Games.<p>    

JOHN S. BLACK is a partner with the Kansas City law firm of Swanson, Midgley, Gangwere, Kitchin & McLarney, LLC, where he practices in the fields of business law and sports law.  John earned a degree in economics from Colorado College and a law degree from Duke University.  He taught business law for four years at Rockhurst College in Kansas City, and has worked as an arbitrator for the American Arbitration Association.  John is a former president of the 20,000 lawyer-strong Missouri Bar.  He has served a term as President of the Lawyers Association of Kansas City and two terms as Chair of the Sports and Entertainment Law Committee of the Kansas City Metropolitan Bar Association.<p>  

CHRIS CAMPBELL is a former Olympic wrestler. He is a member of the Athlete's Advisory Council of the USOC and is appointed to the International Court of Arbitration. Chris is very involved in spearheading the athlete movement to protect individual athletes' marketing rights.<p> 

LISA DELPY, Ph.D., has been a professor of Sport and Event Management at the George Washington University for the past five years.  Lisa is also the faculty advisor for the Forum for Sport and Event Management and Marketing and coordinator of student internships and cooperative education experiences.  Currently, Lisa is planning a conference on Sport Tourism to be held Spring, 1997.  Lisa is the co-author of "The Ultimate Guide to Sport Event Management and Marketing" published by Irwin Professional Publishing, Chicago, IL: 1995.  Lisa has led student study tours to the 1992 and 1996 Summer Olympic Games, the 1993 World University Games, the 1994 Winter Olympic Games, and the 1994 Goodwill Games.  Overall, she has attended eight Olympic Games.<p>   

JEFFREY GEWIRTZ is an associate at the New York City law firm of Dunnington, Bartholow & Miller, LLP, where he works on various sports related legal matters.  Jeffrey is also a staff member of THE SPORTS EXECUTIVE REPORT and an Adjunct Professor of Sports Law at New York Law School.<p>   

PETER GOPLERUD is a graduate of the University of Kansas School of Law. Following graduation he clerked for the Honorable David Prager of the Supreme Court of Kansas. He began his career in legal education at the University of Akron in 1977.  He moved to Southern Illinois University in 1981 and later the University of Oklahoma College of Law in 1993.  He has served as dean at both Southern Illinois and Oklahoma and is currently Professor of Law at Oklahoma.  He has taught and written in the sports law area since 1983.  He is co-author of one of the leading casebooks in sports law, has written numerous articles, appeared on numerous panels, and has a treatise in progress.  He is a member of the Sports Lawyers Association and past chair of the Sports Law Section of the Association of American Law Schools.  He has also been a consultant in the sports law area and a certified contract advisor with the NFLPA.<p> 

JAY LEVINE is a senior associate with the DC office of Chicago-based Winston & Strawn, and concentrates primarily on antitrust and trade regulation issues.  For the first four years of his career Jay litigated a number of sports cases, mainly dealing with obtaining free agency for professional athletes.  Jay was on the litigation team that handled:  McNeil v. NFL; White v. NFL (class action) and the team that negotiated  the NFL/NFLPA collective bargaining agreement.  Additionally, Jay was on the team that litigated issues dealing with Commissioner authority (NHLPA v. Bettman) and other restraints imposed by leagues (Nasland v. NHL).<p>   

QUIRINO MANCINI is a partner at Sinsi Ceschini Mancini & Partners, with offices in Rome and Milan. Quirino has extensive experience in sports law and entertainment law, being one of the leading Italian lawyers representing basketball, football and track and field athletes.  Mr. Mancini also represents foreign players in contract dealings and disputes with Italian clubs.  Quirino is the Italian editorial consultant for the Sports Law & Finance publication, distributed globally out of London.<p>   

GREG ROSS is a senior business associate at the Charlotte office of Poyner & Spruill.  Greg had the good luck of moving to Charlotte at the beginning of 1993 just as the city's bid for an NFL team kicked into the final stretch.  Poyner & Spruill represented the Carolinas ownership group led by Jerry Richardson, and the firm was involved in the entire selection process, including the development and drafting of the first-ever Permanent Seat License Agreement.  Greg's other work included negotiation of the $140 million franchise agreement and the $100 million stadium construction loan.  Those labors now bear visible fruit, as the brand-new Ericsson Stadium awaits its first game on August 3. Greg is a 1987 graduate of the University of Virginia School of Law and a member of the Sports Lawyers Association.  In addition to the Panthers experience, he has represented an indoor soccer league team and worked on scholastic sports issues.<p>   

WILLIAM H. SCHRODER, JR., a native Atlanta lawyer active in the federal and state courts of Georgia and Florida and a principal in the Schroder Partners LC law firm, has engaged exclusively in the law of dispute resolution since graduation from the University of Virginia Law School in 1966. Although he has spent his entire 30-year career litigating, Bill began early in ADR with a 1971 international patent licensing arbitration, and in the late 1970's he began traveling to Europe and the Middle East representing clients in international construction conciliations and arbitrations. In 1979 Bill added services as an ADR neutral when he was invited by the American Arbitration Association to serve on its national panels of mediators and arbitrators, and he has continued that service for the past 17 years, including on the AAA's international, commercial, computer, construction, insurance, securities and telecommunications panels. He additionally has served since 1991 on panels of the Administrative Conference of the United States, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the U.S. Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, the Resolution Trust Corporation, and even his own dispute resolution provider company, ADR Executive Verdict, Inc. Bill has served since March, 1995, as the Moderator of the Georgia ADR Forum on Counsel Connect. A highlight of Bill's career is his current service on the special arbitrator panels created for the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games.<p>   

KENNETH L. SHROPSHRE is a tenured associate professor of Legal Studies at the Wharton School of Business at the University of Pennsylvania and a practicing attorney.  He joined the faculty in 1986.  Ken's research and teaching focuses on the legal and business aspects of sports, race and the law, business law and real estate transactions.  Ken was formerly in private law practice in Los Angeles and prior to that was an assistant vice president with the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee.  While with the Organizing Committee he marketed the Games to Olympic sponsors and licensees and negotiated many of the contracts.  He was also in charge of the Olympic Boxing competition and facility during the 1984 Games.<p>  

Ken has written several articles on sports, entertainment and business issues.  The articles have focused on international sports leagues, sports franchise relocation, problems within the NCAA and business law.  Kenneth's award winning book, "Agents of Opportunity:  Sports Agents and Corruption in Collegiate Sports," was published by the University of Pennsylvania Press in 1990 and won the Choice magazine "Outstanding Book Award."  Additional books authored by Ken include, "The Sports Franchise Game:  Cities in Pursuit of Sports Franchises, Events, Stadiums, and Arenas" (published by the University of Pennsylvania Press in 1995) and "In Black and White: Race and Sports in America" (to be published by New York University Press in 1996).<p>  

AARON N. WISE is a partner of the New York City law firm, Klepner & Cayea.  His practice includes all areas of sports law, domestic (USA) and international.  His practice ranges from professional and amateur league and individual sports, and also includes areas like sports broadcasting, sports marketing and nearly all other areas incidental to sports.  Aaron has earned an LLB from Boston College Law School, an LLM from New York University Law School and a Certificate of Doctorat de l'Universite from the University of Paris Law School.  He is the author of a 3-4 volume book, "International Sports Law and Business," due to be published in August, 1996 by Kluwer International.  The book has five major parts including a section on the Law and Business of Sports in 18 international jurisdictions.  Currently, Aaron has been engaged as a legal expert in the Wilander/Novacek doping legislation against the International Tennis Federation presently pending in an English court.<p>  

ELLEN ZAVIAN is an attorney and professional athlete and entertainer representative. She is legal counsel for the U.S. Women's Olympic Soccer and U.S. Women's Olympic Softball team members. Her work includes negotiating employment, promotional, personal and licensing agreements for athletes and talent, coordinating sponsorship and media events, providing advice on tax and investment matters. Her practice focuses on NFL players, coaches and broadcasters. In addition, she teaches Entertainment Law at American University and Sports Law at University of Baltimore Law School.<p>

