<h2>Banned Drugs</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

From: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br>
Date: Mon July 22 07:25:32 1996<br>
Subject: Banned drugs<p>

Last Append: Fri July 26 14:30:40 1996<p>

A number of athletes already have been banned from the Olympic Games for reportedly testing positive for performance-enhancing drugs, such as steroids.  And the appearance at the Olympic Games of Butch Reynolds -- who previously had lost a lengthy battle with the IOC over a failed drug test -- once again has raised familiar questions.<p> 

To what extent should athletes be tested for drugs at the Olympic Games?<p> 

And to what extent should athletes at other sporting events be tested for various drugs?<p> 

Ted Curtis<br>
Assistant Attorney, University of South Florida; Co-Moderator, Counsel<br> Connect Sports Law forum<p>

<hr><p> 

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Mon July 22 09:30:14 1996<br> 
Subject: Quip<p> 

Mike Lupica on ESPN's Sports Reporters:  "It's been said that the only banned substance in this Olympics is Pepsi."<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles<br> 
Date: Mon July 22 18:55:09 1996<br> 
Subject: Drug Testing-Arbitration<p> 

The new, tougher drug testing policy supported by the USOC and implemented at these Olympic Games was a topic of great discussion at one of our Athletes' Advisory Council meetings a few months ago.  The Athletes' Advisory Council of the USOC strongly supports a new "get tough" position on drugs.  In an interview the other day, Janet Evans expressed her support for tougher drug testing of athletes.  Everyone knows the suspicions surrounding the Chinese swimmers..... So to address Ted's first question, I think you will find a majority of the athletes support a strong drug testing policy.<p>  

However, a British doctor quoted in a documentary on the BBC has said that athletes can still use performance-enhancing drugs to train and had only to stop within a certain time period before the Olympic Games so as to guard against detection.  He implied that 70% of the athletes (from Britain) had taken performance-enhancing drugs during training.   Needless to say, the British delegation is upset at this accusation, but it raises the issue of how drugs are treated in different countries.  Is there a difference in drug testing policies in different countries?  Different sports?   What is the consensus on out-of-competition testing (not just at the Games) and how many countries address this issue?<p> 

The second part of the drug-testing issue, however, is what happens if there is a "false" positive?  How is an athlete's rights protected?  How is the sport protected?   What if someone mixed up your sample and what if someone spiked your drink?<p> 

Maria Dennis, Co-Moderator of Sports Law Forum, Counsel Connect<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jack Rabinowich -- Teacher Stern - London<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 05:33:08 1996<br> 
Subject: Drug Testing-Arbitration<p> 

In a recent Court decision in England (Lightman, J. reported in the Times 15/7/96 delivered on 13/6/96) the Court held that following the ECJ decision in Bosman [1996] 1 CMLR 645 (relating to restrictions on soccer professionals) the rules relating to doping of the International Tennis Federation may be in breach of the European Convention (particularly Articles 48 and 59) as to appeals, testing and formal procedures.<p> 

In another case in England relating to Diane Modahl, the British athlete, an attempt by the BAAF to strike out her claim for damages on the lines of the Butch Reynolds case failed and the case will proceed to a full trial.  She is claiming £500,000 following the reversal of her ban for drugs.<p> 

The English Courts seem more prepared at the moment to look critically at the way Sports Organizations run their affairs than previously.<p> 

Jack Rabinowicz<br>
Teacher Stern Selby<p> 

<hr><p>


Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 15:15:18 1996<br> 
Subject: "Strict Liability" Drug Rules<p> 

What follows is directed in part to Maris Dennis' comments of July 22, to Jack Rabinowich's of July 23 and to Quirino Mancini's of July 23. The IOC and sports federations' war on drugs and "get tough" position may be all well and good. However, the rights of the athlete must not be submerged in the process. The IOC and many international and national sports federations (sports governing bodies="SGBs") have in the last few years adopted "strict liability" drug rules. Such rules do not allow for exculpation where there is no fault: proof of lack of knowledge how the prohibited substance entered the accused athlete's body; absence of culpable intent; sabotage; accident etc. Test positive, and if the sample is that of the accused and no chain of custody or other material "technical" error can be proven, a doping violation has been committed. One then goes to the SGB's corresponding rule on penalties, and applies it. In some cases, SGB rules are not entirely clear as to whether they are of the "strict liability" variety or not. However, SGBs bent on pursuing their agenda--the war on drugs, their public image and public perception, the "best interests" of the sport, may in such situations be inclined to disregard evidence of lack of "fault" and to impose a sanction under their rules. Likewise with their internal (domestic) tribunals. Strict liability SGB drug rules are, it is submitted, incompatible with basic tenets of justice and are unenforceable. A number of arbitral and court decisions in different countries confirm this view, e.g.,<p>  

l. the recent Jessica Foschi decision of a panel of AAA arbitrators (see Summer in Atlanta Library for text);<p> 

2. the l987 Sandra Gasser decision of a Swiss court;<p> 

3. the recent series of German decisions in the Katrin   Krabbe case;<p> 

4. decisions and pronouncements of the Court of Arbitration for Sport in Switzerland.<p>

This is among the main issues presented to the London High Court in the pending litigation, Matts Wilander and Karel Novacek v. International Tennis Federation, in which the undersigned is engaged as an expert witness on behalf of the players. This entire issue is discussed in a very recent article by the undersigned, "Strict Liability" Drug Rules Of Sports Governing Bodies: Are They Legal?" contained in the "Summer in Atlanta" Library. As mentioned, the Jessica Foschi AAA panel decision is also contained in that Library.<p> 

Aaron N. Wise (Panelist)<br>
Klepner & Cayea, LLP<br>      
New York City<br>        
July 24, l996<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 20:01:14 1996<br> 
Subject: Wilander-Novacek v. ITF<p> 

Further to the July 23 comments of my London colleague, Jack Rabinowich. The European Court of Justice (the European Union's=EU) highest court, decided in December, l995, in the landmark Bosman case, that l. post-contractual transfer fees (required payment by a player's new team to his old one when a player moves to a new team, after his contract with the old one has expired), when at least 2 EU countries are involved, and 2. restrictions on the number of nationals from other EU countries a sports team can field, violate Articles 48 and 59, Rome (EC) Treaty. Those provisions deal with the freedom of movement of remunerated workers and employees within the EU. In the litigation presently pending in the London High Court, pro tennis players Mats Wilander and Karel Novacek are challenging the International Tennis Federation's (ITF) drug Rule 53 as being an illegal common law restraint of trade and/or violative of "natural justice" (an English law terms of art for something akin to violative of "due process" and "arbitrary and capricious"). Two of the arguments in this regard turn on the ITF Rule being of the "strict liability" variety; and on the burden of proof being imposed on the players. In late May-early June, l996, the players sought leave to amend their statement of claim (complaint) to launch a new line of argument. ITF Rule 53 provides a tennis player with no right to a hearing or to adduce evidence or make representations before the ITF's first instance, the "review board", upon the player's "A" and "B" urine samples both testing positive. If the review board decides a doping violation has occurred, the player can then appeal to the ITF's "appeals committee". The ITF rules do not provide for any further appeal such as to an independent arbitrator or arbitral body. The U.K., France and a number of other European countries are parties to the Council of Europe's Anti-Doping Convention of November l6, l989 ("A-D Conv"). Article 7, A-D Conv, provides that the parties (contracting States) will encourage their sports organizations to harmonize their doping disciplinary procedures, applying internationally recognized principles of natural justice and guaranteeing respect for the fundamental rights of sportsmen (and women) accused of doping, including, inter alia, the right to a fair hearing; and the right to interject an appeal. Mr. Justice Lightman of the London High Court, in his June l3, l996 decision, granted Wilander/Novacek leave to re-amend their statement of claim (complaint) to plead that ITF Rule 53 violates Articles 48 and 59 of the EC (Rome) Treaty, in that the Rule possibly denies respect for their fundamental rights to a fair, first instance hearing and to an appeal against any judgment made. Mr. Justice Lightman relied heavily on the ECJ's December, l995 Bosman decision. He noted that the modern law on Articles 48 and 59, Rome (EC) Treaty was to be found in the advisory opinion of the Advocate General in Bosman and in the ECJ's Bosman decision itself. The relevant principles are (quoting from the Times Law Report): "l. Those articles (49 and 58) were to the same substantive effect, save that activities            covered by 48 were within, and by 59 outside, the ties of a contract of employment;<p> 

2. Both prohibited any restriction on the fundamental rights to freedom of movement and freedom to provide services;<p>

3. Sport was subject to Community law in so far as it constituted an economic activity within article 2;<p>      

4. Both professional sportsmen and the rules of sports;<p>    

5. Such associations could not lawfully adopt rules which restricted individual rights conferred or protected by the Treaty;<p>

6. Articles 49 and 59 extended to such associations' rules aimed at regulating gainful employment and any limitation on the rights to gainful employment or to  provide services had to be justified on grounds of public policy, public security, or public health."<p> 
This was not a decision on the merits, but, to repeat, only allows plaintiffs Wilander and Novacek to re-amend their statement of claim to assert the above arguments.  Mr. Rabinowich tells me that the ITF has appealed this ruling to the Court of Appeal.  The trial of the main action is pending at this writing and, unless settled prior thereto, a decision on the merits is expected some time around mid l997.  Panelist Jack Rabinowich's firm is handling the case for the players (as sollitors); and Philip Engleman, Q.C., also, I believe, a panelist in this seminar, is one of the barristers arguing the case for the players.  This commentator is engaged as an expert witness for the players on certain legal issues.<p> 

Aaron N.Wise<br>
Klepner & Cayea, LLP<br>   
New York City<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Susan Nogan -- CC Law Editor - Washington<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 11:38:04 1996<br> 
Subject: Background, please<p> 

For those members who may be interested in sports law as spectators only, could one of you experts give a brief summary of which substances are banned, and why.  For example, I heard a yachtsman was having trouble with the IOC because he must take testosterone supplements due to removal of cancerous testicles, and that between shots, his testosterone level drops to below that of a woman.  And we're all familiar with the problems asthmatics face due to the ephedrine (?) in their inhalers.<p> 

Is there any purpose served by such rigid enforcement of the rules?<p> 

<hr><p>


Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 18:18:32 1996<br> 
Subject: Banned drugs<p> 

As one who knows very little about this, I would like some basic information from some of our experts.   

(1) Exactly what are the "performance enhancing drugs?"  Are they just anabolic steroids, or are there more of them?  Are new ones being made all the time?<br> 

(2)  How good are the drug tests used in the Olympics?  Can they detect all performance enhancing drugs out there, or only the more common ones?<br> 

(3) How can you beat a drug test?  I understand some countries (Old East Germany & maybe China) put their national resources behind drugging athletes, so they can do sophisticated tests & those who are positive don't compete.  But, how can a single athlete, free-lancing, so to speak, beat the tests?<br> 

(4) How long does one have to be on the drugs to get an effect?  Likewise, how long can you be off & not lose the effect?  And, how long do they stay in your body?<br> 

(5) The Irish Swimmer.  Does anyone care to comment on her?  (This was a BIG debate at lunch today).  Can someone take 10 or 11 drug tests in a year (all negative) & still be on drugs?  Is it possible to shave off that much time legitimately?<br>    

<br><p>

Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 14:30:40 1996<br> 
Subject: Re D.George's Questions<p> 

The answers to many of David George's questions depend on what experts one consults. Opinions differ on many of the points. Here is what one commentator states in a very recent article, Hoxha, T.M., "Atlanta '96 and Athletes' Rights"--An Update on Drug Testing and the International Olympic Committee", Entertainment and Sports Lawyer, vol. l4, no. l, Spring l996, pp.7-l0 at 7-8: (Referring to the Ben Johnson case) A second test given to Johnson in February l994 resulted in Johnson's life-time suspension. According to Terrence O'Sullivan, a Toronto lawyer and advocate for athletes' rights who represented Johnson during his second test, "The best evidence in his case was Athletics Canada's own tests." After a race in Hamilton, Ontario, on Friday, January l993, Johnson submitted to an unannounced random test that proved negative. Two days later at a Grand Prize meet in Montreal, Johnson again acquiesced to a second drug test that he had known would be administered. He  tested negative for any steroid metabolites, but his  testosterone-epitestosterone (T-E) ratio in the A sample was l0.3.l. For doctors at the IOC and the International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF), this  proved that Johnson was guilty of an infraction. This  ratio was slightly different in the B sample. Yet, according to Dr. Mauro Di Pasquale, author of ll books about steroids, "Testosterone offers long-term benefits with no immediate results. It's not a drug of the moment such as an amphetamine. If you took 5.000 milligrams of testosterone several days before a race, it wouldn't do a thing." In other words, steroids are used as training aids not as race accelerants. If this is  the case, what other factor or factors might have altered Johnson's T-E ratios?<p> 

The body produces two substances called testosterone  and epitestosterone, each with a different molecular configuration. The doctors at the IOC and the IAAF claim that a person's natural testosterone to epitestosterone ratio is l:l. If a person uses exogenous  steroids, that ratio will alter. To accommodate any physiological and pathological conditions that could also alter this ratio, the IOC has gauged that a ratio of 6:l to l0:l is suspect of drug use and that a ratio of l0:l or greater is certifiable proof of drug use.  The biochemists implementing this test for the IOC have an unshakable faith in the test.<p> 

Other scientists, however, do not believe these tests are sensitive and specific. "Regardless of the significant analytical advances made in the last decade," asserts Di Pasquale, "testing is far from perfect." In his view, "Little is known about epitestosterone. Individuals can have varying levels of epitestosterone and their T-E ratios can vary greatly fromthe norms es- tablished by the IOC, without any malady or steroid use. Di Pasquale believes that the 6:l ratio should not be used as a decision point. <p>

In addition, Di Pasquale argues that there can be a  false positive as a result of the analytical process  and a positive test can arise secondary to the ingestion of foods containing banned substances. Di Pasquale cites a recent study by doctors in Budapest who found that residues of anabolic steroids such as testosterone, nortestosterone, methyltestosterone and  trenbolone 2,3,4,5,6, in food created false positives. He concludes that even the consumption of meat from animals that have been treated with hormones can result in a false positive anabolic steroid doping test. Interestingly, this conclusion was corroborated by a paper offered by doctors involved in IOC testing.<p> 

Not only can the reliability of drug testing be questioned, but, according to Terrence O'Sullivan, the  whole system is faulty. "Athletics Canada's own test," O'Sullivan claims, "would strengthen Johnson's case of innocence." Four days after Johnson's alleged positive test, Athletics Canada surprised Johnson with yet another random test on January 2l, l993. Not only did they find no metabolites of steroids, they found an acceptable T-E ratio. However, it is unusual for one's T-E ratio to quickly drop to an acceptable  level. The evidence seems to suggest that Johnson was not guilty of a steroid infraction.<p> 

I have not included the footnotes in the above passages. The article contains much more and is well worth reading. While the article's author does not specifically cite "strict liability" IOC and other sports governing body drug rules, he points to a number of major obstacles to athlete's receiving a fair, impartial hearing, in particular, before the International Council of Arbitration for Sport (ICAS). That is an IOC created arbitral body headquartered in Switzerland which, inter alia, hears and decides disputes involving Olympic athletes (including drug cases). ICAS arbitrators are present in Atlanta during the Games. Regarding "strict liability" drug  rules, see my (A. Wise's) earlier appended comments.<p> 

Aaron N. Wise<br>
Klepner & Cayea, LLP<br> 
New York City<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Quirino Mancini -- Sinisi, Cesschini - Milan<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 11:44:40 1996<br> 
Subject: Banned drugs<p> 

Hello there Aaron.  Regrettably, I could not find the time earlier to check out any follow up messages to my remarks concerning anti-doping issues, hence I will address your queries now.<p> 

As a disclaimer, please note that rulings made by the domestic tribunals of Italian sports federations are published with notable delay in the sports law reviews.  This makes it extremely difficult for Italian sports law practitioners to maintain updated records, that is, unless they were actually involved, at a representational or expertise level, in the relevant case.<p> 

As to your first question, in obeyance with the recently-enforced exacting liability principles, a decision was published late last year, issued by the judging council of the Italian Rugby Federation (IRF), whereby it was ruled that a player's failure to report for a doping test resulted as though the player had tested positive to the test and, accordingly, the heaviest disciplinary sanctions must be levied.  In the case at hand, following the implementation in 1994 of the "surprise" anti-doping test programme by the Italian Olympic Committee's (IOC) anti-doping commission, a rugby player who had been directed by the IRF to undergo a drug test during the course of a training session (i.e. far and away from being an official test match) did not show up on the due date, it being two days since having received the notice, alleging university commitments.  He did make himself available, however, for test purposes on a date which was 7 days distant from that set by the IRF:<p> 

From the player's failure to report for the drug test on the set date and from his seeking a postponement without submitting any material evidence to the extent that the alleged commitments actually required a 7-day rescheduling of the test, the IRF found that the player could not plead any cause of force majeure and thereby found him guilty, that is, as though he had tested positive.  As a result, the player was banned from playing any official competitions for a period of 2-years and his club was fined ITL 5,000,000 (nearly USD$3,000).  Eventually, the Federal Justice Committee, the body in charge of hearing the appeal case,  reversed the IRF's decision and thereby acquitted both the player and his club, sustaining two arguments submitted by the player in defense.  The latter had in fact argue that: (I) there were no official records reflecting that the IRF had indeed adopted, by implementing the relevant secondary legislation, the IOC's surprise anti-doping test programme thereby introducing the exacting liability rules, and (ii) once implemented, the new drug test rules had not been duly and formally notified to the IRF fellow members (both clubs and players).<p> 

In conclusion, although the IRF's decision was indisputable from a significant standpoint, as it entailed the enforcement of the exacting liability principles in matters of drug tests, the fact that the player had strongly objected to their legality insofar as they had not been duly notified to all IFR members, resulted in the above acquittal.<p> 

I guess the quoted case also answers your second query concerning the burden of proof as, due to the fact that the new rules on drug tests are tougher, the prosecuting bodies are required to fully substantiate their findings and subsequent disciplinary action.<p> 

I am afraid I could find no precedents to properly address your third question.  Nonetheless, I would like to share the following with you, which is based on a case I am currently handling.  You will forgive me if I do not disclose the full details of this story as the relevant litigation is still pending and I do not want to run the risk of jeopardizing or influencing, in any way, the final outcome.<p> 

Late last year I was retained by a foreign pro-player engaged by an Italian team who was no longer acting under the terms of the engagement arrangements.  No only had the club failed to pay the player's most recent monthly salary installments, but eventually had applied strong psychological pressure by insisting, on various occasions and with no apparent reason, that he undergo drug testing. However, as the club had repeatedly defaulted the engagement agreement by not making the payments due to the player, despite him having regularly and fully performed his obligations, I put the club on notice of default regarding the outstanding payments and threatened to terminate the agreement if the breaches were not cured by a certain date.  Then, I advised my client not to report for the drug test until such time as the club had met its obligations in full.  At the same time, I also instructed by client to retain the services of an independent analyst and thereby undergo a voluntary drug test as a backup measure.  Needless to say, my client tested negative.<p> 

Eventually, the agreement was terminated by the club's failure to act as required and I served the club with an injunction of payment.  The club challenged the player's injunction and, amongst other things, counter-claimed that the agreement had initially been terminated by my client due to him having failed to report (on very short notice I might add) for the doping test.  The club also submitted that such behaviour by the player was not consistent with the national federation rules in drug matters and it therefore entailed a serious contractual breach.<p> 

To cut a long story shorter than it might  result in being, we ended up in an ordinary court (and not before a federation arbitration panel) with the club alleging, without having entered any substantiating evidence, that my client had not undergone the test as he would have doubtless proved positive.  Regrettably, the case has not as yet been heard by the court, and I dare say that when we do finally appear, it should prove diverting to learn how the club attempts to substantiate a doping claim in a situation where the allegedly drugged player holds material evidence to the contrary.<p> 

Returning to your third question, note how weird this case would appear to be: the club could virtually apply to the player (and not vice versa) to obtain a urine sample in order to conduct an independent test, in a desperate effort to assert a claim.  Is this not the most peculiar case of burden of proof in reverse?  I shall keep you posted on the final outcome of the trial.<p> 

<hr><p>

