<h2>Dream Teams v. Amateurs</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3>


<P>From: Jessica Londin -- Counsel Connect - New Yor<BR>
Date: Tue Jul 23 14:42:05 1996<BR>
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<BR>



<P>Last Append: Tue Jul 23 14:42:05 1996</P>


<P>What's are the rules on professionals in the Games?   </P>

<P>I love the Olympics but I miss "amateur" competition. </P>

<P>It's exciting to see the big guys in Atlanta (and Barcelona), all those
superstar multi-millionaire mega-athletes who are way too  rich and famous
to even stay in the Olympic Village with  the other competitors.    </P>

<P>And sure, our elite Dream Team will save the U.S. from the  embarrassment
of losing again to the Russians (last time they  beat us they were
*Soviets*) at our beloved basketball.  (Even Brazil has whipped our non-pro
b-ball team at the Pan Am games.) But weren't the Olympics originally an
amateur sporting exhibition?   </P>

<P>Obviously, other countries send their pros to the Games. It  would be
unfair (not to mention downright foolish-looking)  if we failed to enter
our best players too. </P>

<P>I hate to be a spoil sport, but where's that 'ol Olympic  spirit in Games
dazzled by the presence of all-stars like  Barkley, Malone, Pippen,
Olajuwon, Seles, Agassi, Lewis, Johnson?  It's not just because they can
afford first class hotels and  don't have to eat the same Village food as
everyone else. </P>

<P>What makes the Olympics the OLYMPICS, anymore?  We already have Wimbeldon
and the NBA.   </P>

<P>And if the Games are to be a pro show, then let's give gold medals to all
the major league  players on the planet.  Where are the Dream Teams in
hockey, baseball, soccer?   Let's really give Coca-Cola its money's  worth.
 We have pro sports all year 'round. What's so special about a mere two
weeks every four years?  Every day can be an Olympic day.  Ask Charles
Barkley. </P>

<P>Jesse</P>






<P><HR></P>

<P>Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<BR> Date: Tue Jul 23
13:13:30 1996<BR> Subject: The Rules </P>

<P>According to Section 373 of the Amateur Sports Act of 1978: </P>

<P>"As used in this Act, the term--</P>

<P>(1) 'amateur athlete' means any athlete who meets the eligibility standards
established by the national governing body for the sport in which the
athlete competes . . . " </P>

<P>So, the common perception of what an amateur is (a non-professional
athlete) has very little to do with who is eligible to compete in the
Olympic Games. It is solely up to the NGBs of each sport. So, USA
Basketball decided that they would not exclude professional athletes from
the eligibility standards which they defined. NGBs for other countries and
other sports have declined to do the same, which is why some pros
participate in the Olympics and some don't. </P>



<P><HR></P>

<P>Appended by: Adam Shapiro -- GA Counsel Connect - Atlanta<BR> Date: Tue Jul 23
14:25:53 1996 <BR>Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs </P>

<P>Jesse, what if the Dream Team wasn't so good against international
competition?  Would you care that they weren't amateurs?    I don't think
so.   </P>





