Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br>
Date: Tue Jul 23 14:51:15 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

It is my understanding that originally amateurism was used to keep working class people out of athletics.  The less privileged had to work to support themselves, so they weren't as good as the rich.  The only way working class people could excel was by being professionals.<p> 

On McNeil/Lehrer last night they told the story of a Hungarian skier in the 1950s who lost his medal because he had previously given skiing lessons.  Likewise, in this week's New Yorker there is a story on rowing.  In the early part of the century Englishmen who had ever engaged in manual labor or the trades were prohibited from rowing in certain highly prestigious events.  In light of that background, I think allowing professionals is more egalitarian.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Susan Nogan -- CC Law Editor - Washington<br> 
Date: Tue Jul 23 15:00:39 1996<br> 
Subject: What's An Amateur<p> 

And Jess, let's not forget  that those "amateur" Soviets that beat our boys didn't have to work full-time to support their hobby - their government made sure they could devote their time to sport.<p> 

That said, I'm far more impressed with the Olympians who *do* have day jobs.  Like the short stop on our softball team.  In her spare time she's an orthopedic surgeon.<p> 

