Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br> 
Date: Tue Jul 23 17:12:37 1996<br> 
Subject: The Pro Olympics<p> 

I too miss the day when TRUE amateurs only competed in the Olympics. But remember that we are now dealing with something that is far and away out of control. The Olympics are no longer amateur sport, played only for the good of sport. Now, we are talking about major corporate sponsorship and big money. So it should really surprise no one that the Olympics now include indidivuals who earn millions of dollars a year.<p> 

But even as I write this, I am reminded of two things from the Olympics. First is that TRUE amateurs still do exist in the Games in events including shooting, fencing and similar sports. So I suppose that at least those sports still maintain the purest of Olympic spirits.<p> 

Second and conversely, I recall one international athlete once defending the use of pros in the Games by simply arguing (paraphrazing here): "I want to come where the best are competing. That's what the Olympcis are about. If that means pros will play, so be it."<p> 

Ted Curtis<br>
Assistant Attorney, University of South Florida<br> 
Co-Moderator, Counsel Connect Sports Law forum<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jessica Londin -- Counsel Connect - New York<br> 
Date: Tue Jul 23 19:03:13 1996<br> 
Subject: Rich v. Poor<p> 

I agree there's no way around the class issue.  The rich can afford to buy Olympic gold.  It's clear what kind of resources go into turning kids into Olympians.  How much time and money can most people devote to competitive sports, anyway? (I mean participating in them, not watching them on ESPN.)<p> 

Amateur competitive sports are for the leisure set, or those so monstrously talented they win scholarships, sponsors, and the free services of coaches like Bela Karolyi (Comaneci, Retton, Moceanu) or Nick Boleteri (Agassi, Seles).<p> 

And when that time comes, they're amateurs no longer.<p> 

Jesse<p>

