Appended by: David Mandell -- Attorney at Law - Norwich<br> 
Date: Tue Jul 23 22:42:59 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

The Olympics lost their amateur status decades ago. They always pretended that the athletes were amatuers but everyone knew that you can't do things like pole vault 17 to 20 feet unless you are in training full time. Tennis used to pretend that its stars at Wimbledon were amateurs but they were known as "shamateurs". The olympics might as well come out and admit they are a professional outfit designed to make as much money as possible, just like the NBA, Major League Baseball et. al. The Olympics also are over rated as an economic boost to a community. Montreal is still paying for the 1976 games.<p>   

<hr><p>

Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York<br> 
Date: Wed Jul 24 12:20:23 1996<br> 
Subject: 0lympic Baseball<p> 

What follows relates in part to Adam Shapiro's comments of July 23 on Olympic baseball. Adam says that the 2000 Sydney Games will be held in February-- does he or anyone else know if February is definite? My information indicates late September as the tentative date for the 2000 Sydney Olympics. Here's some data on Olympic baseball, and particularly, on pro players competing therein. Baseball became a full fledged Olympic sport some time prior to the l992 Barcelona Games, and was treated as such for the first time in those Games. However, pro players did not participate. Nor are pros participating in the ongoing Atlanta Games. So far as I know, professional players' participation in future Olympics is an unresolved issue. The IOC wants to see Major League and other pro baseball players (e.g., Japanese League players) in the Games. For pros to compete in the Olympics, the approval of the international governing body, the International Baseball Association (IBA) is required. An IBA rule prohibits pros from doing so. A 2/3 vote of IBA member federations is needed to change it. In June, l994, a measure to change the rule was defeated (3 votes shy). The US federation (with MLB backing) voted in favor of the change. Since then, on several occasions, the IOC's President has threatened to expel baseball from the Olympics if the IBA does not change its rule to allow top pros to compete in the 2000 Sydney Games and subsequent Olympics. In November, l995, the IBA'S President made similar public statements. While MLB would have to work out scheduling and other problems with the MLBPA, that would seem possible. The PA seems willing. As stated initially, my reports indicate tentative late September dates for the 2000 Sydney Games. Those dates would enable MLB to permit teams out of the pennant race to send players. Future summer Olympics played in Southern Hemisphere cities could be scheduled after MLB's World Series. Until a MLB collective bargaining agreement is worked out, probably this issue will not be tackled in a definitive way as between the League and the PA. While the issue could be dealt with in a new CBA, more likely a separate agreement would be reached after a new CBA is concluded (best guess). Meanwhile, however, the question remains whether through IOC and other pressure/persuasion, enough member federation votes can be mustered to change the IBA rule to allow pros to play. If not, the possibility exists of a breakaway movement--a new international baseball federation being formed by the majority of IBA members favoring the rule change, and its recognition by the IOC. Top MLB players in the Olympics could greatly help baseball's popularity worldwide (TV coverage, more foreign government money into the sport, etc.). It could even help MLB to regain some of its lost luster and fans. It could hasten a "super World Series" or similar event between MLB and the Japanese Leagues; and might well shorten the time frame for eventual MLB overseas expansion (e.g., franchises outside of the US & Canada, MLB sponsored overseas leagues etc.). The IBA issue is likely to come to a head in the relatively short term. Does anyone have very recent information on the IBA.<p> 

Aaron N. Wise (Panelist)<br>
Klepner & Cayea, LLP<br>
New York City<p>

(The above issues are discussed in Wise, A., and Meyer, B., "International Sports Law and Business", Part II (Kluwer Law International, Cambridge, Mass)--a 4 volume work scheduled for publication in September, l996).<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Wed Jul 24 17:27:18 1996<br> 
Subject: Original Dream Team<p> 

Someone please correct me if I am wrong, but as I recall, the international governing body for basketball approved the use of professionals over the "no" vote of USA Basketball.  It seemed that the rest of the world wanted to play against the very best.<p> 

As mentioned above re Carl Lewis or the Soviets, etc., it had simply become too difficult to distinguish who were pros or amateurs in almost any sport.  Let's let this "ideal" die and concentrate on the opportunity to watch those who are the absolute best athletes in the world.  And let's be happy for them that they do not have to beg for financial support to allow them to train as they should.<p> 

