Appended by: John Libretti -- Attorney at Law - Hackensack<br> 
Date: Wed Jul 24 18:54:14 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

Jesse,<p>

Since your piece on amateur v. professional athletes in the Olympics centered on the Dream Team, I thought you ( and perhaps others) would be interested in a notion that was floating around the airwaves in New  York today, on WFAN, the SportsRadio station. A couple of  listeners called in and opined that perhaps USA basketball could do what that United States Soccer Federation did for the mens' soccer team. That is, select  a team of  All-Stars who are under a specific age (in the case of soccer it is 23) and have 3 "wild-card" selections. In other words, you could have three NBA hoopers play with a team of  college kids.  Of course, in light of the fact that most of the best collegiate hoopers leave school when they are 19-20, you may still end up with a team of pros even if you impose an age requirement.<p> 

Furthermore, I think it bears keeping in mind that the United States was one of the few (if  not the only) countries that sent an amateur basketball team, prior to 1992. Now, in terms of status, we have an even playing field: our best pros versus the best pros from other countries. While I appreciate the empty feeling you seem to be experiencing at the "death of amateur athletics", I must  add that  the concept of amateurism has been dead for a long time. I'm sorry if  it took  you a while to notice.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: David Baker -- Arnzen Parry Wentz - Covington<br> 
Date: Thu Jul 25 14:05:32 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

I don't know about the rest of you, but I have to admit that, although I have no doubt that the USA, where basketball was invented and where the best in the world play, is entitled to send its best (meaning the pros) to the Olympics, I am pretty underwhelmed by the attitude exhibited by Barkley and Co.  Playing on the Dream Team is most assuredly not THEIR dream, it's ours.  They look and act as if they could care less.  The drama, and hence the appeal, of the Olympics comes from the athletes who have sacrificed and struggled to get to the Olympics -- and who show some genuine emotion when they win or lose.  I'm thinking of the American wrestler who cried unashamedly when, having given his best, came up short against the Russian.   Barkley and Co. aren't exactly sacrificing anything to go to the Olympics -- except maybe a couple of rounds of golf.<p> 

There are journalists here who have written columns expressing the hope that the DT loses (which is, of course, their 1st Amd. right . . .).<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: David Baker -- Arnzen Parry Wentz - Covington<br> 
Date: Thu Jul 25 16:04:00 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

The following private reply was sent to me.  I'll post it here without attribution, since the sentiment may be shared by others:<p> 

subject:Dream Teams v. Amateurs<br>
David, I could not agree with you more!  As soon as the basketball comes on, I change the station.  It's pretty disgusting to see these athletes display such an utter lack of sportsmanship.  My fervent hope for these Olympics is for the Dream Team to lose, preferably in the medal round. =============<p> 

