Appended by: James Clark -- Baker & Daniels - Indianapolis<br> 
Date: Thu Jul 25 16:11:27 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

I don't understand the anguish over the loss of  "true" amateurs in the Olympics.  As I understand it,  the athletes in the original Greek  Olympics were quite well compensated for their efforts, and the notion that only "amateurs" could compete was introduced in the 19th century to keep the working class from spoiling the aristocrats' fun.  More recently, only the United States has paid even lip service to the amateur ideal, offering up collegians to compete against the well-supported athletes from other countries.  As to Dream Team III, I understand that basketball's international governing body was all in favor of NBA participation, and the other players seem equally in support of the idea.  I think what we are lamenting is not the demise of amateur competition in the Olympics, but the demise of a peculiarly American myth.<p> 

Jim Clark<p>   

<hr><p>  

Appended by: Al Pola -- Bond Schoeneck King - Syracuse<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 08:39:45 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

I believe Susan first pointed out way back in the deep recesses of this thread that the United States was the last major country to hold out against bringing professionals to the Olympics.  Other countries had been doing it for years.  Case in point, other than the easy Soviet and Bloc countries:  in the Scandinavian countries, athletes would "work" for a state corp., where their job was essentially to train for competition.  Their reward was a "job" that compensated them for training, while the employer received the benefits of a great p.r./marketing tool (let's play golf with the Olympic champion).<p> 

There are a number of great points made as to whether the Olympics were ever truly amateur.  In some cases, they still are:  people who have real jobs and train in their spare time, yet are the best their country has to offer in their sport.  Generally, it seems as though the sport is one that has little to no marketing attached to it.<p> 

In New York, we have a competition called the Empire State Games, akin to the Olympics but truly amateur.  Its exciting to watch these athletes compete, as one never knows what the outcome will be (isn't that part of the excitement of sports, notwithstanding our desire for "our" team to win?).  Unfortunately, that is what  amateur sport has been reduced to:  little coverage and notice as opposed to where the pros play.  So be it.  At times, I'd rather watch high school or college sports than a pro game, given the outlandish prices attached to attending as well as the equally outlandish attitude of some pro players.  Jesse, I think this is where you'll find the last bastion of true amateur sport (aside from the fencing/shooting/etc competitions).<p>

As for the upcoming pro involvement in hockey, I have this comment: I enjoyed the 1980 Miracle on Ice more than I think I would enjoy watching a pro team attempt to call itself amateurs and win a medal.   Don't get me wrong; it will be exciting to watch the best of the best play, but its not amateur sport.  There are two completely different styles of play, and consequently two completely different attitudes in watching the sport.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Quirino Mancini -- Sinisi, Cesschini - Milan<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 14:46:41 1996<br> 
Subject: Dream Teams v. Amateurs<p> 

I am really most intrigued by this discussion on Dream Teams and its implications on the various  sports.  Here is a story which concerns the Italian soccer team which has just been played out of the first round of the Olympic tournament.<p> 

Prior to being sent to Atlanta, our soccer players were generally considered to be one of the three Italian Dream Teams, along with the water-polo players and the volleyballers.  Indeed, the Italian soccer team had just won the Under 23 European Championship for the third time in a row and was bound for further glory in Atlanta.  Instead, the major flop!<p> 

The above outcome obviously triggered harsh criticism in Italy, not only from the specialized press but also from the nearly 56 million soccer "coaches" (it appears the entire population views for this post).  Prior to the Olympics, Mr. Maldini (the team's coach) was tipped to take over the leadership of the senior national team from Mr. Sacchi, brutally ousted from the Euro England series last June.  Following the Olympics. however, it appears that Mr. Maldini is destined to accompany Mr. Sacchi in his long lonesome strolls along an alpine road, while two fresh-blooded sacrificial lambs willingly step up to substitute.<p> 

So the crucial question we are now faced with is: are our young champions still to be considered a Dream Team, or should they instead be downgraded to a "Creamed" Team which readily melted under the scorching Georgian sun?<p> 

The serious side of this story is that the very sad outcome of just this small part of the Olympics has spurred a debate as to whether pros such as our Under 23 soccer players should still be allowed to compete in the Olympics.  It is a situation where it is abundantly clear that the players were quite put out at being forced to skip their summer vacation and instead, were required to spend in excess of four weeks in compliance with monasterial regulations.  In this regard, many wondered whether our boys were motivated to the degree necessary to play in the Olympic Games, also in view of the fact that the bonus granted by the national federation in the event of a medal was not outrageously high.<p> 

Obviously, there is very little rationality in this issue, yet, insofar as soccer is concerned (football for our British participants), a real problem would seem to exist:  how can we possibly and satisfactorily combine the different needs, behaviors and mostly business-driven mentalities of pro-players with the amateurish rules by which the Olympic Games are still governed?  Returning again to the Italian team's disastrous performance in Atlanta (do we have to?), is it reasonable to expect that a bunch of amateur, however well trained, soccer players could have done better than the pro Dream Team?  Many Italians are currently posing this question: is there anybody else willing to volunteer a response?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York<br>
Date: Fri July 26 15:40:30 1996<br> 
Subject: Q.Mancini DTs&Amats  Drugs<p> 

Hi Quirino (there in Italy).<br>
l. Your remarks on the Italian soccer "Dream Team" are very interesting. Since, however, our Olympic soccer team got knocked out (again) in the preliminary round, we Americans must be quite humble when it comes to Olympic soccer....maybe water polo too.<p>

2. A question for you, Quirino. It properly goes under the subfile "Drugs", but you might not tune in to it so I'm putting it here.  Please take a look at my article in the Library of this seminar; and my comments under Drug Use. Question: Have there, to your knowledge, been any cases decided by the Italian courts or by arbitrators or by domestic tribunals of Italian sports federations, whereby an athlete has<p> 

	A. challenged the legality of a sports federation's "strict liability" drug rule (and/or 	the penalty imposed based thereon) under Italian or EU law?<p>

            B. raised the issue of who, the federation or the athlete, has the burden of proof 	of a drug violation and by what standard?<p> 

	C. claimed that he or she, the athlete, has a right to receive a portion of his or her 	urine sample in order to do an independent test (and, if the athlete so chooses, to 	submit the results in evidence to support his or her innocence)? Apart from the 	l987 Gasser case (Switzerland), the series of l993-96 Katrin Krabbe cases 	(Germany), and Court of Arbitration for Sport decisions, are you aware of any 	decisions in any European country apart from Italy and the UK where A., B. and/or 	C. above have come up?<p>       

Regards, Quirino-Aaron N. Wise Klepner & Cayea, LLP New York City<p>              

<hr><p>

Appended by: Parry Aftab -- Aftab & Savitt - Paramus<br> 
