<hr><p>

Appended by: James Hirschhorn -- Sills Cummis - Newark<br> 
Date: Mon Jul 29 18:58:29 1996<br> 
Subject: DT and Amateurs<p> 

1.  As a number of people here have pointed out, the amateur ideal was a 19th century class concept.  It had a variety of rationales: i) that the performance of strenuous manual labor gave the laboring poor an unfair physical advantage over gentlemen, ii) that the purpose of amateur sport was to encourage physical fitness and competition among upper class young men so that they would be more fit to command their social inferiors (OW Holmes Sr., for example, wrote along those lines), iii) that common folks and mercenaries were too concerned with winning and couldn't grasp the ideals of sportsmanship and chivalry that sport was supposed to promote, and iv) that sport was essentially a social event at which outsiders didn't belong.  The result was the kind of snobbery that barred from the Henley Regatta any oarsman who had ever performed manual labor for a living; the story is well known that John Kelly, Sr. (Grace Kelly's father) was not allowed to compete in the Henley single sculls because he had once been a bricklayer, and that after he made a fortune as a contractor he had the satisfaction of seeing his son win the event.  All of that is, mercifully, behind us.  While I hugely enjoy seeing athletes who compete for the love of the sport, with no hope of remuneration, I think any restriction that keeps the best from competing against one another is arbitrary and unwarranted.<p> 

2.  I have no problem with the members of the Dream Team.  As the New Yorker pointed out last week, they hardly need the money themselves and come as close as anyone to playing for the love of what they do.  The scores are lopsided, but it was the FIBA that wanted US professionals to play in order to ultimately raise the level of the game world wide.  It would be patronizing for the DT players to get out there and dog it.<p> 

3.  What does bother me is the fans' indecent zest at these one sided victories.  I sometimes think that a lot of Americans have no more stomach for a fair fight.  The desire for blowouts is to me a symptom of  insecurity; it reminds me of the public reaction to Desert Storm. 
<BR><BR>
<hr><BR><BR>



