<h2>Too Young To Compete</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

Last Append: Wed July 31 07:09:05 1996<p>

Last Sunday, 60 Minutes did a disturbing segment on American women's
gymnastics.  The segment focused on the immense psychological and physical
strain these young women have to go through in order to excel and, perhaps,
become champions.  Several gymnasts interviewed stated they were
psychologically abused, by both coaches and parents, when they couldn't
keep their weight down during training.<p>  

Adding fuel to the fire, 60 Minutes revealed that at the 1976 Games, the
average American female gymnast weighed 106 lbs., was 17 1/2 yrs. old, and
stood 5' 3".  In 1992, the average American female gymnast weighed 83 lbs.,
was 16 yrs. old, and stood 4' 9".  Quite a big difference.<p> 

Although I usually find 60 Minutes to be a somewhat credible news-program,
I must say that I felt this segment went a bit over the top.  Obviously,
forcing young girls to starve themselves in order to achieve Olympic
greatness is morally reprehensible.  The differences in age and weight
between the 1976 and 1992 team is quite alarming.  Yet, isn't it also true
that these lighter, younger, more diminutive women are superior gymnasts
because of these very attributes?  Is allowing Dominique Moceanu the
ability to represent the U.S. in these 1996 games such a bad thing?  At 13,
Moceanu became the youngest senior U.S. champion (she's now 14).  Should
someone like Moceanu be prevented from competing at the highest levels of
competition simply due to her age and weight?  Wasn't Nadia Comaneci of
similar age and stature?<p>   

The USOC has drawn at least one line here.  In the 2000 Olympic Games, the
USOC has set a minimum age for female gymnasts - 16.  Yet, should this step
be taken at all?  Will an age requirement prevent young gymnasts from
starving themselves in order to better perform?  Will it prevent their
parents from obsessing over their child-star's career?<p> 

What steps should be taken to protect these young women, without
compromising their potential to medal at higher competitions?<p>
<hr><p>


Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 14:40:19 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

Such has been the topic of discussion in women's gymnastics (or really
shouldn't it be GIRL'S gymnastics now?) for a number of years. For a great
review of this topic, check out a recent book, I think called "Little Girls
in Pretty Boxes" for a discussion on this topic.<p> 

Ted Curtis<p>


<hr><p>


Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 13:43:50 1996<br> 
Subject: Golden Injuries<p> 

On the same subject --<p> 


Did anybody besides me find it absolutely chilling that the young woman on the US gymnastics team competed despite, as I understood the reports, a severely sprained ankle.  Her pain on dismount was palpable.<p>   

The book referred to in the prior post is by Joan Ryan, a San Francisco reporter, who  was interviewed on Sunday ( a repeat, I think) on 60 Minutes, about the unbelievable abuses, both physical and psychological, to the young girls who compete in gymnastics.  One of the routine issues, she said, was that the young women are pushed to compete when injured, which, said Ryan, would NEVER happen in football.  Ryan has recently published a book on the subject.<p>  

The coach, Bella  (?) is apparently notorious for pushing the girls -- and refused to be interviewed by the 60 minutes reporter.<p> 

Posted by Monica Bay, Sr. Law Editor<br>
(415) 749 5511<br> 
monica.bay@counsel.com<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 14:20:44 1996<br> 
Subject: Never Happen in Football???<p> 

Clearly Strug was injured when she did her last vault.  But, did she vault because she was under Bela's control, or because she had a dream of winning the gold & knew this was the only way to make that happen.  She is an 18 year old woman capable of making choices.<p> 

Also, what are the real downsides to aggravating the sprain?  Unless I'm mistaken, it wasn't going to kill her or cripple her.  Perhaps it will affect her ability to compete in the future, but this is probably her final Olympics (she'll be 22 in Sydney).  What would she be saving herself for?  This, as they say, is come to Jesus time.  If the vault would not be likely (or possible) to do her permanent physical harm that would affect her doing normal activities, then maybe she should go for it.<p> 

You must admit, for a moment she was on top of the world.  People everywhere were hailing her as a hero & inspired by her courageous act.  In one of the most dramatic sports moments I've ever seen, she came through.  I've never been anywhere near doing anything remotely like that, but, I must imagine that a sprained ankle is a small price to pay for such an experience.<p> 

One other point, if she hadn't vaulted she would not have gone to the allaround competition (Dominique M. was ahead of her).  So her only hope for best allaround was to risk injury.  A tough choice, but one that had to be made.<p> 

Finally, I'm not sure about Ryan's comment that football players would never be pushed to compete when injured.  That may be true, but it flies in the face of everything I've ever heard about football (from high school through pros).  Playing with pain is part of the game.  When men do it they're heroes.  When a similarly aged woman does it we worry she's being manipulated.  Maybe we shouldn't be so paternalistic & sexist.  (Monica, this is not a comment to your post, but rather to an attitude I've heard expressed by others, including Ms. Ryan).<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 14:33:03 1996<br> 
Subject: Never in Football?<p> 

I've got to go with Dave on this one. I was friendly with a lot of the football players when I was in college at Duke, NOT a great football school. I remember friends of mine getting injections (of Novocain or cortisone, I think) in the middle of a game to numb the pain caused by an on the field injury, so they could keep playing. When the game ended, they were worse off than they would have been had they sat out when injured.<p>  

<hr><p>

Appended by: Mary Zwick -- The Chemical Co. - Midland<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 15:21:41 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

A couple thoughts after watching last night's women's (girls'??) team finals:<p> 

It is apparent why smaller is better, especially after seeing Dominique Moceanu's mastery of the balance beam, an apparatus at which the US has met its Olympic Waterloo more than once.  Obviously, the smaller you are, the less of a challenge it is to land on a surface four inches wide.<p> 

At the same time, it is also painfully apparent that younger is not always better.  How else to explain Moceanu's sitting down two vaults in a row -- vaults which did not even carry a potential for a "10" score?  Even the NBC commentators were at a loss.<p>  

Although I did not see the 60 Minutes segment referred to above, I am in agreement with the position that the gymnasts are pushed much too hard and hounded mercilessly about their weight and appearance.  To wit, recall the case a couple of years ago of Christy Hentrich, a US gymnast who died of anorexia.<p>  


I think that as long as the US fans and TV networks milk the stories and endorse the "little pixie" image, it will continue.  To a large extent, parents will want to enjoy vicariously the glory that is Olympic Gold, and they will always find a coach willing to go along for the ride.<p>   

As far as the "playing with pain" -- what we saw Carrie Strugg do last night was definitely THE story of the Games.  I don't think anything can top that.  Obviously, she did not compete the entire night with the sprained ankle; it was only after she knew that the US would lose the gold medal that she tried the second vault.  This was an act of tremendous intestinal fortitude, IMHO.  I would also venture to guess that various other athletes in other sports would have done the same thing.  As pointed out previously, Carrie was not risking debilitation or worse, this was probably her last competition, and she was not eligible at the time for the individual all-around.<p> 

All it took was one look at her face on the medal stand to know it was well worth it!<p>

<hr><p>  

Appended by: Ken Shropshire -- Wharton School - Philadelphia<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 15:50:56 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

I think in this discussion it is also important to keep in mind age restrictions in other sports.  Tennis and hockey are two notable examples.  In tennis the action regarding age restriction developed more as a result of the emotional problems of the young athletes rather than any physical issues as in gymnastics.<p> 

Further, we can' t leave out early entry into the NBA.<p>   

<hr><p>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 16:55:21 1996<br> 
Subject: Moral Dilemma<p> 

Are their some individuals whose talent is so rare that the world is better off if their childhood is sacrificed so that we all can benefit from that talent?<p> 

Furthermore, aren't their some individuals, even young girls (Mary Lou Retton comes to mind), who are well-grounded enough to make the commitment to endure this type of training, given the potential benefit of being one of the best at the world at what you do?<p> 

It seems to me that the abuses alleged in the 60 minutes piece are standard-issue coaching manipulation techniques.  Not that they don't seem somewhat shocking when applied to little girls, but they are part of the stick and carrot approach which all top coaches employ (including the very top high school coaches of male athletes).  There is no doubt that the top students of these coaches have an incredible amount of affection and loyalty to them.<p> 

I found the most condemning part of the 60 minutes piece to be the abuse inflicted by the parents of each of the girls.  This has also been shown in tennis, with the fathers of Mary Pierce and Jennifer Capriati, for example.  Parents can either provide proper perspective, support and love, and thereby temper the worst parts of this training, or they may exacerbate the situation to a terrible extreme.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 17:58:46 1996<br> 
Subject: Good points<p>  

what a thoughtful discussion!<p>

I do resonate to the "come to Jesus" component -- and think that's a very valid point. and I think it's a very significant point that she is a young adult, and not a pre-teen, and capable of making that choice. And finally, if in fact the ankle injury was not that severe before the event, but was aggravated by the event, then I don't find that so problematic.  

but Joan Ryan's points -- and the 60 minutes interview -- were indeed very very chilling, especially listening to the young athletes articulate how they were belittled, called cows, etc., and ultimately felt their lives were over because they hit puberty.  And yes, the point about the parents is very well taken.  I thought the one mother was very very moving who said that she would go to her grave with guilt over allowing her daughter to be manipulated and humiliated by overbearing coaches.<p>  

Did I read somewhere that with the next Olympics, there will be an age 16 limit put on the gymnasts?<p>  

Posted by Monica Bay, Sr. Law Editor<br>
(415) 749 5511<br> 
monica.bay@counsel.com<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Deirdre Terry -- Counsel Connect - New York<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 18:11:21 1996<br> 
Subject: Good points<p> 

I understand from the commentary (I can't believe I actually learned something from that vapid commentary) that, beginning in the 2000 Olympics athletes will have to be sixteen in an Olympic year to compete.<p>  

I was surprised to find out, however, that there is already a rule saying that the athletes have to be at least 15 in an Olympic year to compete. The reason 14 year-olds (like Dominique M.) compete is that they expect to turn 15 later in the year that the Olympics are held. So this is not as big of a change as I thought when I initially heard of the rule change.<p> 

I also heard that the average age of the American women's gymnastics team is 18 this time around, up from 16.5 four years ago, despite the much-discussed youth of the youngest member of the team.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Catherine Ross -- Ross Law Office - Lawrenceville<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 20:21:06 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

I found myself caught up in the drama of the Strug final vault last night, watching on the edge of the sofa with my eight year old daughter who stayed up late specially to watch the US women's gymnastic team.   As lawyers we tend to be very competitive by and large and relate to risk and winning.  When I speculate whether I would have taken that last vault given the overall circumstances at her age, I think I would have made the same decision.   I found myself admiring her for her courage to move beyond pain and injury and persevere on behalf of her team.<p> 

Yet,  as I looked at the crowd reaction and the values that my own daughter was absorbing I couldn't help but wonder how healthy it is to reward our youth for persevering in pain and through injury to win a contest (albeit a major contest).  This young woman didn't struggle across a battle field to save a life, yet a reporter referred to her as a hero.<p> 

We pay our professional sports players to play well into serious permanent injury in their careers.  Is it a value we wish to instill in our youth, to ignore their pain or injuries in order to win?<p>   

The newspaper report I read indicated Strug had no feeling in her injured leg prior to the second vault and that her ankle was dislocated.  Perhaps she won't be or wasn't permanently injured.  I failed to observe much analysis given to the potential for serious injury to Strug prior to the second vault, but observed instead a coach urging her to go on, yelling "You can do it".  I can only hope that as a professional coach he was adept at assessing her physical situation and did so with her best interest at heart.  It didn't seem that way, however.<p>  

All and all, as an adult woman guiding children into the future, I seriously question  the values this event teaches our next generation.  I'm happy the US team won, but  I worry what the next generation will sacrifice in order to win again, in the Olympics and other aspects of life.  From an adult perspective, I don't think I would have  taken the second vault as tempting as it may have been.<p> 

Catherine Ross<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 08:21:21 1996<br> 
Subject: Bad Lessons?<p> 

You can put many spins on this, but consider that Strug courageously overcame personal difficulties for the good of her team.  Is this a bad lesson?<p> 

As was noted earlier, there seems to be a real gender split on the perceptions involved here.  As women's sports become bigger, are we being forced to confront issues that we have ignored with young men?  How many Olympic boxers started taking their licks in the ring in their early teen years?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 11:24:11 1996<br> 
Subject: Good Lesson<p> 

Catherine, I have to disagree with you.  I think Strug did teach a good lesson.  Life is (often) pain.  The ability to put that behind you and concentrate on the goal is an important one.  I imagine you teach your daughter that the good & important things are difficult, that things don't come easy.  She knows that to succeed in school she has to put in many hours studying, even though it's not fun.  Strug taught us that when adversity comes you persevere through it & prevail.  That young woman gave us an object lesson.<p> 

A complaint about the current generation (of which I am a member) is that we're lazy & don't want to put in the effort to succeed.  The athletes show us what is possible if you work hard (the amount of training they go through is unreal).<p>   

I also contend that Strug is a hero.  She may not have saved a life, but she did commit a selfless act (which is a hallmark of heroism).  Faced with pain, she continued, for the greater good of the team (& country).  That is heroism.<p>  

<hr><p>

Appended by: Melanie Morgan -- Frito-Lay - Plano<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 12:32:58 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

I must comment on the statement that the techniques used by Bela Karoly (sp?) are the same as those used by coaches on young male athletes, with resulting success and loyalty.  I think we as a society ought to take a hard look at what effect that sort of military, "blame-and-shame" treatment has upon a person's personality, his or her self image, and relationships later in life.  I think it's tremendously damaging, and I won't let any teacher or coach treat either my son or my daughter that way.  I hope they both have the chance to feel the satisfaction, pride and camaraderie that go along with participating in sports, but I hope they never feel that their worth as persons rides on what they do on a playing field or gym floor.<p> 

On the other hand, in our society, you are not outcast and shamed if you don't come home with a medal, which is what the NBC commentary led me to believe will happen to the poor Chinese gymnasts.<p> 

Also, the look on Kerri Strug's face didn't convince me--she looked none too sure about what was going on.  All Bela's girls seem to look at him with faces of dogs who have been beaten into submission--grateful for the current affection, but uncertain about when the next abuse will occur.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: William H. Schroder Jr -- Schroder Partners LC - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 12:27:47 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Abused To Compete?<p> 

I think that Catherine has a point on the Strug matter.  I was watching too, and likewise with the rest of you I was caught up in the competition, rooting for the good old US of A.  But my own daughter has competed in gymnastics, and for this reason I was particularly alerted to the circumstances immediately following Strug's first vault, the one in which she suffered a foot injury.  She obviously was in severe pain, and the eyes in her pain-expressing and frightened face were searching among her coaches as to what to do.  What a pregnant pause!  As an aside here, I should mention that Bella later said that Strug was the last one on the team whom he would have expected to have the courage to vault while in pain.  So the response from Bella to her frightened, painful look this time was "Come on, you can do it!  You can do it!  We need it one more time!"  Now not once did anyone there, not a single coach, not even Bella, run up to Strug and check out the injury.  We, on hindsight, accept that it was "only" an ankle sprain; but no one *knew* that at the time!  She was yelled at to go and vault again, without any knowledge as to the extent of her injury.  30,000 strong in the packed arena are chanting "USA!  USA!"  What was this little girl to do?  I'm sorry, but I don't see that she made a free choice.  Talk about duress!<p> 

As a matter of fact, she did not even have to make the second vault in order for the USA to win the gold medal.  There were two remaining Russian gymnasts on floor exercises.  NBC reported at the time that they would have had to have scored a 10.00 and a 9.95 in order for the USA to get silver instead of gold, two scores that those judges had given no one all night long!  And, as it turned out, they only got 9.75 apiece, which was about average.<p> 

So assume under these circumstances that Strug's foot, which has more bones in it than any other part of the body, had one or more broken bones and/or torn tendons and ligaments, all from having planted the foot wrong on her first vault landing.  Under many such circumstances she still could have walked to the second vault.  But a second vault would have caused another landing, and on that same foot, now injured!  Also a push off with that foot, and its Achilles tendon, which possibly also was injured.  No one knew!  The risk of a more severe injury to the already injured foot, by repeating the very same activity that injured the foot the first time, was patent.  The only question was how bad the more severe injury would be!  Given the circumstances in this paragraph, it was possible that Strug would cause *permanent* injury to her foot in a second vault, at least one requiring one or more surgeries.  And for what?  As if that should matter.  The gold was as good as in our pocket already!<p> 

And this gets us back to the question in this thread of abuse of a child.  If a child is involved in gymnastics of this international hype and national glory, there ought to be some sort of "Amicus" of the child ("Amicus Parvulae"), whether at the behest of the IOC or the USOC, who can step in at any point and enjoin immediately any activity s/he rules to be abusive.  The child deserves that kind of protection from any excessive glory-seekers around him/her and the chanting crowd.  If there is any kind of injury, such as Strug's, it would be the responsibility of the Amicus Parvulae at least to stop the proceedings and to check it out, including calling for a medical examination of the child.  Additionally, Strug was representing the USA, you and me.  We at least ought to set up a procedure designed to protect her from abuse, physical as well as psychological, under circumstances where she is representing us.  If no Amicus Parvulae, then at least some sort of independent on-site arbitrator skilled in such matters and whose decision would be binding.<p> 

We Olympics arbitrators already are in place for "disputes" where there is time to hear them.  Why not add Referees for Child Abuse? The cost would be minimal, and I believe worth it!<p> 

Bill<p>

