Appended by: David Baker -- Arnzen Parry Wentz - Covington<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 13:47:50 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

After reading the various posts in this thread, several thoughts come to mind:<p> 

1.  We all tend to see what we want to see in this situation.  I, for one, didn't see the "dog fear" look in the eyes of the gymnasts, but then, I hadn't followed all the "Bela Is Bad" publicity.  In retrospect, I still don't see it.  And I certainly didn't see it in the eyes of the young women as they received their gold medals.  Kerry S. didn't look particularly overjoyed, but then, she was in pain.<p> 

2.  Was there duress on Kerry to do the last vault?  Maybe.  But I'm not sure it was as severe as was described by one of the respondents above -- that sounded to me like a closing argument to a jury (and a darn good one, too).  Remember that even though we saw it on TV, we weren't THERE and cannot possibly know everything that went on.  At any rate, Kerry made the choice to do the vault, and years from now, I suspect she'll be glad she did.  I note that it was reported today that Amanda Borden, one of the U.S. women gymnasts, has decided to postpone college and embark on an "exhibition tour" with some of the other team members.   Cashing in?  Perhaps.  And why not?<p>  

3.  You've got to admit, that moment was priceless in terms of drama.  And if we parents put the proper spin on it, it serves as a powerful lesson to our own children.  Sacrifice, deferred gratification, the value of the team -- these are values that are often noticeably absent in the children of us Baby Boomers (we weren't exactly too hot on those values ourselves in the 60s and 70s).  Seeing Kerry's heroic (yes) performance certainly seemed to inspire my 14-year old daughter!<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 13:58:38 1996<br> 
Subject: Under Bela's Control?<p> 

I disagree with the comments that Strug is cowering in fear of Bela.  I find it instructive that after the last Olympics Strug left Bela (he retired for a while from coaching elite gymnasts).  She bounced around from coach to coach for a while, but finally came back to Bela.  Perhaps she's like the abuse victim who keeps returning to the abuser, but I don't think so.  After 4 years away from Bela (especially the 14 to 18 year old years), I doubt she'd go back if he was emotionally abusing her.<p> 

I'm sure many coaches do go too far.  But, the fact that they're not all sweetness & light at all times doesn't make it abusive.  Many coaches do use strong techniques to bring out the maximum performance in their athletes.  I know in school I had professors who were quite demanding &, at the time I thought, abusive.  But, they used those techniques to show us what we could achieve.  Schools such as VMI & the Citadel use the so-called "aversive" method of instruction.  Perhaps it's just abuse, but it seems to work.   Mary Lou worked under Bela for many years & she seems to still hold affection for him 12 years later.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: James Clark -- Baker & Daniels - Indianapolis<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 16:38:13 1996<br> 
Subject: Playing with Pain<p> 

According to the reports I've seen, Strug is a 19 year old woman, not a helpless child.  I think she was completely capable of deciding whether the gain was worth the pain.  Nor do I find her choice particularly surprising.  Both amateur and professional athletes routinely compete despite pain and injury.  For example, I've watched basketball players lace up and play despite a sprained ankle or even a separated shoulder, and I've watched football players compete despite broken bones.  Although it always amazes me, it never surprises me.   As for Strug, she toughed it out , gave it her all, and won the gold medal.  I'm impressed.<p>   

I have to wonder whether there would have been this much controversy if Strug had been a 19 year old male gymnast.  Why do we presume that a woman gymnast must have been dominated by her male coach?  Why can't we just accept that all Olympians -- both male and female -- are tough competitors?<p> 

Jim Clark<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 17:06:37 1996<br> 
Subject: What about a stress fracture?<p> 

Let's not all gang up on Kerri Strug. She is not a helpless minor -- she is an adult Olympic athlete who puts up with pain as a matter of course. No one should be able to tell this 18 year old woman what she can and cannot do.<p> 

But what about 14-year old Dominique Moceanu competing with a stress fracture in her leg? I think that should be of much greater concern to us from a legal standpoint. Strugg should be able to decide whether or not to compete because she is old enough to make the decision for herself. But what about 14-year old Moceanu? Did she compete with a stress fracture because she didn't want let her family down? Or her friends? Or -- worst of all -- her coach?<p> 

The argument does not only apply to gymnastics. Consider what would happen if 15 year old swimmer Amanda Beard suffered a similar injury. Or a 15 year old tennis player.<p>  

I think it is of much greater concern when a minor is pushed towards greatness rather than an adult who is similarly pushed but who is legally held to have the ability to push back and refuse to compete.<p> 

Ted Curtis<br>
Co-Moderator, Sports Law forum<p>

