Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 17:56:42 1996<br> 
Subject: Anorexia & Suicides<p> 

It is tragic that gymnasts have died of anorexia & attempted suicide, just as it is tragic when any girl (or anyone) dies of anorexia or suicide.  However, does anyone know the rates of these occurrences in gymnasts (of figure skaters) vs. the rest of the teenage girl population?  Adolescence is a difficult time for everyone & many girls become anorexic & many attempt suicide.  I don't know if we can say that the sport led them to these things.<p>  


Clearly gymnastics puts pressure on young girls.  But, a girl who attempts suicide apparently because she has hit puberty & can't compete anymore, might not have really done so for that reason.  If a girl tries to kill herself because her boyfriend breaks up with her we usually look for a deeper reason (e.g., clinical depression).<p>   

Additionally, I thought sports were a great thing for girls?  I've read many stories saying that girls involved in sports have much higher self esteem & much lower teen pregnancy rates.  All of the attention on women's gymnastics this time is good for women's sports & women in general.  I'm normally not a big fan of women's sports (don't enjoy women's basketball).  But, I was mesmerized Tuesday night.  Strugg's second vault was one of the most exciting sports moments I've seen./1/  It really lifted women's sports.<p>  


/1/  I think Strugg's vault did more for women's sports than, say, Nadia's 10 because it was not beauty & grace being demonstrated, but sheer courage & will.  So, men could really identify with this.  If you'll note the comparisons being made are between Strugg & male athletes.  So, I think many men now look at what women gymnasts (& also other athletes do) as being "real."  I'm not saying I condone an attitude that thought less of women's sports before this, but I think one must admit the attitude was there.<p> 

