Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br> 
Date: Thu July 25 19:47:55 1996<br> 
Subject: Games Your Mother Never Taught<p>  

David,<p> 

I think you raise some very strong points.<p>  

I completely agree with you that in most cases, sports -- for either boys or girls -- can be terrific ways to teach leadership, teamwork, health, etc. etc.    My nieces both excel at soccer  and I am delighted to see how their self-esteem and confidence has been built up.<p>   

A woman named Betty Harrigan wrote a pivotal book years ago, called "Games Your Mother Never Taught You."  Her premise then was that boys had a terrific advantage over girls because they learned - through organized sports -- how to interact and be a team. I read the book in my 20s and it had a profound affect on me (and a LOT of other women).   The book helped many of us compete and prosper in work environments.<p> 


The problems begin, I think, when winning -- at any cost -- becomes the primary goal. And  after  Ryan's & 60 Minutes'  reports  I remain concerned about the Bellas of the world.   A charismatic controlling adult can easily have incredible influence over a young person -- be they male or female.  Esp. when the child's parents are reinforcing that reality.  It can often be good  (I think back on an incredibly nurturing high school teacher who encouraged me to pursue my writing) or bad.<p>  

When a young girl becomes so obsessed with gymnastics that when she hits puberty she thinks  her life is OVER, then something is wrong. That's an obsession, not a healthy outlet.  And call me Californian, but in my book, it's inexcusable to call any young person a "cow"  when you are in a position of power and influence.<p> 


Maybe that's the bottom line: These coaches, like teachers, have a responsibility to treat the children with compassion, care and respect. Not like dogs. Otherwise, society pays the price.<p>   


Posted by Monica Bay, Sr. Law Editor<br>
(415) 749 5511<br> 
monica.bay@counsel.com<p>

