Appended by: Melanie Morgan -- Frito-Lay - Plano<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 17:24:32 1996<br> 
Subject: Too Young To Compete?<p> 

As the person who made the "dog" analogy, I should point out that I think what Keri did was very gutsy and admirable in many ways.  I just find that the interaction between her and her coach is  unsettling.<p> 

Watching gymnastics again last night, I was very disturbed to see the coaches' reactions to both Shannon Miller's and Dominique Dawes' tears (after they each stepped off the mat during the floor exercise).  Shannon's coach kept saying "Stop crying!"  Both of them were left by themselves on the bench, told to quit having emotional reactions to what must have been a devastating experience.  As a parent and a wife, I have discovered that people feel a lot better, and get past negative emotions much more quickly, when you validate the feelings instead of denying them.  Why didn't anyone comfort these girls?  Why didn't anyone acknowledge their pain?  This isn't the army--it's sports!<p> 

Finally, I don't think the parents have much real ability to control decisions made during events--and I'm not sure they should.  Imagine the chaos if every time a coach made a decision, an angry parent could come down from the stands and overrule it!  No, I think that if coaches knew there was some sort of objective, organized oversight into their treatment of their team members, they would temper their behavior.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 17:55:20 1996<br>
 Subject: Crying<p> 

I heard Miller's coach tell her to stop crying.  I didn't find his comments as harsh as Melanie did.   First, he didn't seem to be shouting a command, but rather making a suggestion (I would exclude the exclamation mark from my transcript).  Second, it is arguable that he's looking out for Miller's interests.  He said "Stop crying, everyone's watching."  Which is true.  Her face was on the Jumbotron & millions (billions) of people were watching her.  Perhaps she will be glad that she held back the tears until later, rather than having such a (justifiably) emotional moment in front of the world.  Clearly you can validate feelings without expressing them to the world.  I don't think a person who is informed at work of a tragic event would be accused of repressing feelings by remaining composed until in private, & then crying.<p> 

OTOH, the weepiest group I've seen is the wrestlers.  (See Dick Enberg's piece on Wednesday night).  Everyone of them was bawling after their matches.  In a kind of reverse of the norm, that was considered great, while the gymnasts crying was seen as weakness.  I guess a tough wrestler has proved his manhood enough to be able to cry in public, while a gymnast crying is just proving she's a little girl.  Cf. Pat Schroeder's crying when leaving the race in '88 (?) with all the male candidates who turn on the tears like faucets (Clinton, Dole etc.).<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Beth Corvino -- General Instrument - Chicago<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 18:31:54 1996<br> 
Subject: I agree, David.<p> 

I saw compassion and trying to look out for the best interests of both Miller and Dawes.  Miller's coach hugged her, asked several times whether she was okay, and then tried to calm her down, talking her through the routine and then telling her to stop crying, that everyone was watching, that she had to pull herself together -- she still had to vault.  Dawes' coach did the same.<p>   

These women have worked most of their lives to get to this point.  What people seem to forget is that their coaches have, too.  They have sweated and worked and agonized for years as well.  I thought the coaches of all the U.S. women have been much more empathetic than I would have imagined them to be.  No screaming.  No yelling. No "how could you screw up like that?"  Nothing.  Nothing but encouraging them, telling them they did their best (Karolyi hugging Morcheau after her floor routine).<p> 

I don't know that any of us can really understand what these girls/women go through, or sit here in front of our computers and determine what's right or wrong with this picture.  Personally, I believe that Olympic athletes are driven and motivated beyond what we can imagine.  That is their personality.  There's a fire inside them.  While I suppose there can be Svengali stories or horror stories of pushy parents, I think we're more likely to find those stories in Little Leagues and high school sports than in the Olympic arena.  To get to this level, you have to have more than just talent and people pushing you.  You have to have a fire burning in your gut.  You have to really really want it.<p> 

Kerri wanted it.  I'm sure that if she had it to do over again in the same situation, i.e.  where she didn't know that she didn't have to take the second vault, she'd do the same thing.  Who knows, perhaps she'd do the same thing even if she somehow could have known the team had locked the gold, because she knew she wouldn't qualify for the all-around or for the vault finals if she didn't try.<p>   

I'm sure there are abuses in every sport.  (I'm sure there are abuses outside of sports.  What about the young children whose parents stick flash cards in their faces when they're infants and push them academically and on five different musical instruments and twelve different extracurricular activities instead of just letting them be kids?  Is there any difference?)  But I don't think that that fact alone is reason to condemn this woman, her coaches, her parents, or the Olympic Games.  The potential for serious trouble -- whether it is a dominating coach, parents who want their child to live their dreams for them, eating disorders, societal notions of what's good and beautiful -- must always be acknowledged and watched for and guarded against and dealt with when it exists.  In the meantime, let's acknowledge that it is possible that Kerri Struggs is a young woman who had the inner courage and fortitude and drive to do something that will inspire men and women alike for years to come.<p> 

