Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles<BR> Date: Thu Aug  1 14:27:02 1996 <BR>Subject: The Olympic Charter 
<BR><BR>
The Olympic Charter of the IOC states in Rule 47 that : 
<BR><BR>
"There may be no age limit for competitors in the Olympic Games other than as prescribed for health reasons in the competition rules of an IF [International Federation]." 
<BR><BR>
Has the IF of Gymnastics shown scientific evidence that proves gymnastics is not healthy for younger gymnasts?  Then why do little boys and girls start at the age of 4? 
<BR><BR>
I believe that the IF has taken over the parents' role and is dictating how a family should treat its children.  If the parent wants to put his or her child through the rigors of competitive gymnastics, then that is his or her decision along with the child's.  Who is to say that the 14-year-old does not want to put herself through such rigors?  When I was 14 years old and playing ice hockey, I played through all sorts of obstacles because I knew myself and my limits and my parents recognized my awareness for my body and my drive for perfection.  Why are we treating these gymnasts any different?  Because they are sweet little girls?  While I do recognize that there is a pervasive problem with anorexia and bulimia in gymnastics (as with many other sports), this is not an age problem, but a problem to be addressed by the sport as a whole. 
<BR><BR>
I believe that the IF has taken a patronistic role in this age issue.  They should take a scientific role and provide evidence from a scientific background.  Basically, I think this is age discrimination. 
<BR><BR>
-Maria Dennis, Co-Moderator

<BR><BR> 

<hr><BR><BR>

 

Appended by: Mary Zwick -- The Chemical Co. - Midland <BR>Date: Fri Aug  2 15:52:36 1996 <BR>Subject: dying for approval 

I fall somewhere between Dave G. and Monica on this issue.  On the one hand, I think that the coaching methods used in women's gymnastics at the world class level are pretty reprehensible, and I don't think it's quite fair to paint Bela Karolyi as the lone villain of the piece.  Steve Nunno et al. are probably just as bad.  The problem with using "aversive" coaching methods, as Dave suggests, is that with gymansts you're dealing with preadolescent girls who, as countless studies have shown, have very fragile self-images to begin with, and telling them things ("you're a cow," "you're too big," etc. etc.) that play off this fragility and create this almost maniacal desire to please the coach and do whatever it takes to be the best (whatever that means). 
<BR><BR>
However, I do think that once a girl reaches a certain age, she indeed has the capacity to make decisions in her own best interests (without the "help" of any sort of Amicus Parvulae or other paternalistic watchdog) and decide for herself whether, for instance, to take that second vault.  We have to give girls/women the same credit we give boys in this situation and not ask ourselves whether we need to "protect" these athletes from themselves/their parents/their coaches. 
<BR><BR>
I think that even a forty year old woman who found herself in Kerry Strug's position the other night would have done exactly the same thing, and we wouldn't even have thought twice about it, or questioned whether the impetus for the act had really been hers or had come from her Svengali, Karolyi. 
<BR><BR>
On a related topic, why isn't anyone up in arms about all these 14 and 15 year old American female swimmers who are tearing up the pool?  Why doesn't anyone question their youth and call for age restrictions on competition?     


<BR><BR> 

