<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
<h2>Olympic Sponsorship</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

From: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br>
Date: Mon July 29 23:16:29 1996 <br>
Subject: Olympic sponsorship<p>

Last Append: Tue July 23 07:16:01<p>

Story around Atlanta is that if you want a Pepsi, drive across the border
to Florida and make a left at Jacksonville. You see, Coca-Cola is an
Olympic sponsor, so only the products of the Atlanta-based company may be
found in the Olympic city. Coke paid millions for the right to be the
exclusive soda of the Games. From document reproduction machines to
automobiles to game shows, there are hundreds of official Olympic
sponsors.<p> 

Some have criticized these Games as TOO corporate. Others have justified
the deals as American capitalism at its best. Which is it? How far is too
far for Olympic sponsorship?<p> 

Ted Curtis<br>
Assistant Attorney, University of South Florida; Co-Moderator,<br> Counsel
Connect Sports Law forum<p> 

<hr><p>
 
Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 07:16:01 1996<br> 
Subject: Cadillac, NBC and Janet Evans<p> 

Perhaps two examples of corporate sponsorship clouding NBC's ability to
properly do its job:<p> 

In between the telecast of the women's 400 meter freestyle (in which Janet
Evans did not compete after failing to make it through her qualifying heat)
and NBC's Jim Gray's interview with Evans (at which she told of her
disappointment in not making the finals), NBC reportedly aired a Cadillac
commercial featuring no one other than...Janet Evans.<p> 

Later, at a similarly inappropriate moment, NBC aired a commercial for AT&T
also featuring Evans.<p> 

Ted Curtis<br>
Assistant Attorney, University of South Florida; Co-Moderator,<br> Counsel
Connect Sports Law Forum<p> 

<hr><p>
Appended by: Jay Levine -- Winston & Strawn - Washington<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 16:37:32 1996<br> 
Subject: Olympic sponsorship<p> 

Ted, query whether the tremendous Olympic sponsorships actually  effectuate
the Olympic ideal in some perverse way.  If the Olympic ideal includes
freedom and the ability to achieve, aren't the huge Olympic sponsorships
one manifestation of that ideal?  Aren't they merely the operation of the
free market?<p>   

Food for thought.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Steven Nauman -- Best Koeppel - Houston<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 19:39:59 1996<br> 
Subject: Olympic sponsorship<p> 

National Public Radio reported yesterday that cans of coke were being sold
at a set price of  $4 per can, which is probably how Coke was going to make
back the dough it spent on becoming the official soft drink.   NPR reported
however that the price soon dropped to $2 per can because non-official
vendors were selling Pepsi at $1 per can.  I am delighted at this proof
that the free enterprise system can function in the face of officialdom.<p>
  

<hr><p>

Appended by: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 21:28:31 1996<br> 
Subject: Reebock vs. Nike<p> 

Perhaps the Games will teach some corporate sponsors that it's better to
stay home and save some cash.<p>   

Reebock reportedly paid over $20 million for the right to proclaim itself
the "official Olympic footwear supplier," and the right to air ads during
network Olympic coverage.  A wise investment?  Perhaps not.<p> 

Nike, In response to Reebock's official Olympic status, has thrown a
stinging counter-punch by indirectly associating themselves with the Summer
Games even though they're not an official sponsor. Nike is airing several
Olympic-like ads (without saying "Olympic" of course) outside network
Olympic coverage showcasing several Olympic athletes who have endorsement
deals with Nike (e.g., Carl Lewis).  In addition, it's almost impossible
not to notice the Nike logo prominently displayed on the shoes and shirts
of hundreds, if not thousands of Olympic athletes competing in the
games.<p> 

It seems that by spending big money on athlete endorsements, Nike has
ironically saved themselves some cash.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jay Levine -- Winston & Strawn - Washington<br> 
Date: Tue July 23 21:52:39 1996<br> 
Subject: Amex<p> 

Todd, wasn't this exactly American Express' strategy four and eight years
ago?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 14:12:33 1996<br> 
Subject: The bottom line<p> 

That's correct, Jay.  Although I believe Visa has done better as of late.  American Express cards still aren't accepted by Olympic ticket agents.<p> 

Interestingly, some companies who pay for Olympic sponsorship privileges aren't as concerned with the bottom line.  International Paper Co., says it's hoping their Olympic tie-in will generate "pride and excitement" among its own employees.  NationsBank, which recently went through a series of mergers, is using its Olympic status to build brand-name recognition over several states.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Wed July 24 17:30:48 1996<br> 
Subject: Olympic Spirit<p> 

So who has the purer motivations and is more supportive of the Olympic goals--"Official Sponsors" Reebok and Visa, whose fees have helped pay for the incredible costs involved in this event, or the "Ambushers" Nike and AmEx?,p> 

<hr><p>


Appended by: Ellen Zavian -- Ellen Zavian - Columbia<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 17:19:49 1996<br> 
Subject: Ambush Marketing<p> 

Once again, Nike is considered an Olympic Sponsor without paying the millions to the USOC.  Instead, they spend their money on representing the athletes.<p> 

Right or wrong....the general public would not know that Nike was not in the park with the rest of the $40 million dollar Olympic Sponsors.<p> 

First Amendment?  The freedom of advertisement has been restricted within the state of Georgia.  How can one infringe on such a right for a restricted period of time?<p> 

<hr><p>


Appended by: John S. Black -- Swanson, Midgley - Kansas City<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 23:16:29 1996<br> 
Subject: Olympic sponsorship<p> 

In the lead-up to the Olympics, the ACOG  talked a tough game about its aggressive plans to punish ambushers.  I have seen some ACOG advertisements and press releases that urged the public to support the "good guys," but only one item that named the names of the "bad guys."  That one had to do with a Florida tourism board promotion.   Have I missed something, or is the ACOG taking a softer than threatened stance?  If it were to name names, what would be its risk of catching a defamation lawsuit?<p> 

John Black<br>
Swanson Midgley--Kansas City, MO<p>

<hr><p>

