<blockquote>
<h2>Trademark protection</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

<P>From: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<BR>
Date: Mon Jul 22 07:18:47 1996<BR>
Subject: Trademark protection</P>




<P>Last Append: Mon Jul 22 12:37:42 1996</P>

<P>Anyone who has been following the Olympics knows of the zealousness with
which the United States Olympic Committee has protected its trademarks. By
federal statute, no commercial entity may use the names Olympics, Olympic
Games, and similar terms without the approval of the USOC. </P>

<P>Does the USOC need this high level of protection? What would happen if this
trademark protection were removed? </P>

<P>Ted Curtis<BR>
Assstant Attorney, University of South Florida; Co-moderator, Counsel
Connect Sports Law forum </P>




<P><P><HR><P></P>

<P>Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<BR> Date: Mon Jul 22
09:37:57 1996<BR> Subject: Examples </P>

<P>For a couple of examples of ACOG's and USOC's work in this area, see: </P>

<P>(1) the decision in USFC O-M Bread v. USOC, 1995 U.S.App. LEXIS 25188 (Fed.
Cir. 1995), in which the Circuit Court agreed with the USOC that a
breadmaker could not use the name "Olympic Kids", even though the baker had
the right to use the name "Olympic" because such use predated the 1950
federal statutes (the predecessor statute to the Amateur Sports Act) </P>

<P>and</P>

<P>(2) Complaint in Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games v. The Event
Group, in which ACOG seeks to prevent The Event Group from selling ticket
and travel packages. </P>

<P>Both of these are available in LIBRARY on Counsel Connect. </P>




<P><P><HR><P></P>

<P>Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta <BR>Date: Mon Jul 22
11:05:23 1996 <BR>Subject: Examples </P>

<P>Thanks, Greg, for mentioning these. I'll copy them into the Summer in
Atlanta Library, so y'all can find them easily. </P>

<P>The section of the Amateur Act of 1978 that deals with trademark protection
is 36 USC 380. The full text of the Amateur Act is online in the Summer in
Atlanta library, if you want to take a look. </P>



<P><P><HR><P>
Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta <BR>Date: Mon Jul 22
12:37:42 1996 <BR>Subject: Examples </P>

<P>If you want to read the full text of USFC O-M Bread v. USOC (decision) and
ACOG v. The Event Group (complaint), they're now in the Summer in Atlanta
library. </P>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Thu Jul 25 13:20:17 1996<br> 
Subject: Our own dilemma<p> 

During the weeks and months that we planned this seminar, we at CC referred to it as the Olympics seminar. When it came time for us to write advertising copy to publicize the seminar, we ran into a real problem -- what to call the seminar that wouldn't get us in trouble with the USOC for trademark infringement. Anything using Olympic(s) was out, as was Atlanta '96, Summer Games, and a host of others. Living in Atlanta, I knew that enforcement was no idle threat. <P>
<HR><P>




