<h2>Legislation</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

<P>From: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<BR>
Date: Mon Jul 22 10:19:28 1996<BR>
Subject: Legislation</P>




<P>Last Append: Mon Jul 22 12:11:24 1996</P>

<P>Along with many others in Atlanta, the Georgia Legislature has been busy
preparing for the Olympics.  Among other things, they: </P>

<P>Passed an Olympic Price-Gouging Act (O.C.G.A. 43-21-16), which restricts
charges at hotels to rates in effect in 1994, plus some cost of living
increases.  The Act does not apply to private homes.  The Georgia Attorney
General has issued an Opinion (No. 95-23) finding that the State Office of
Consumer Affairs has limited authority to enforce the Act.  Private civil
action is also authorized. </P>

<P>Allowed limited exemptions from licensure and certification laws for
"credentialed persons", particularly medical personnel, for the Olympics
and the Paralympics.  O.C.G.A. 43-1-26.  This statute also provides that
the official "Chef de Mission" for the Olympic teams may give consent for
medical and surgical care given to minors on their team. </P>

<P>Authorized the creation of a commemorative license plate, available through
this year.  O.C.G.A. 40-2-46. </P>

<P>Authorized the governor to use volunteer National Guardsmen for logistic
and personnel support to Olympics activities, including public safety and
security assistance to law enforcement.  However, the Guard cannot be used
to quell riots unless a state of emergency is declared.  O.C.G.A. 38-2-6.2.</P>


<P>Extended Workers Compensation coverage to *volunteer* workers at the
Olympics.  O.C.G.A. 34-9-2.4.  This will entitle those workers to medical
care if they are injured "on the job", and protect the "employers" of those
workers.  Income benefits are not provided, since the workers are
volunteers. </P>

<P>Created the Metropolitan Atlanta Olympic Games Authority, which is a
political subdivision of the State of Georgia.  In essence, MAOGA oversees
the construction spending by ACOG.  MAOGA had the authority to issue
revenue bonds; however, its obligations are its own and not backed by the
state or the City of Atlanta.  The Georgia State Financing Commission owns
the Olympic dormitories, which will be turned over to Georgia State
University after the games.  The Centennial Olympic Park is owned by a
private entity. T he Attorney General has also issued an opinion allowing
school systems to lease school buses to ACOG.  No. 95-41. </P>

<P>Showing attention to detail, the legislature also exempted Olympic
competing boats from certain requirements to maintain flotation devices
onboard.  O.C.G.A. 52-7-8. </P>



<P><P><HR><P></P>

<P>Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston <BR>Date: Mon Jul 22 
12:11:24 1996<BR>  Subject: Price Gouging </P>

<P>Apparantly the price gouging laws don't apply to food prices (or they're
being ignored).  I saw on CNN that a pizza place was selling a pizza that
previously cost $12.50 for $40.  WOW!!!  The owner said "Hey, it's the
Olympics." </P>

<P>
<hr><p>


