<html><head><title>Counsel Connect Seminar - Summer in Atlanta</title></head><BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" ALINK="#000080" VLINK="#FF0000">

 <a href="/inside/about.html"><img align=left border=0 width=400 height=60 src="/images/spotlight/gameshead.gif"></a>
<img align=right border=0 width=99 height=140 src="/images/spotlight/games2.gif">
<img align=right border=0 width=99 height=140 src="/images/spotlight/games.gif"> 
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
<h2>Permanent Site</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

Last Append: Mon Jul 29 11:07:05 1996<p>

There is much hand-wringing and cynical thrashing over the commercialization of the Games; however, there are immense costs involved in staging this affair (estimates of $1.3 billion and up for Atlanta).  Is it time for a permanent site to be selected and constructed?<p> 

Where should that site be?  Or should there be more than one?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York<br> 
Date: Thu Jul 25 12:43:46 1996<br> 
Subject: Atlanta Wins<p> 

Greg, after the Montreal '76 disaster (I think they lost about 1 billion on the Games) the IOC probably considered this very idea.  Up 'till then, the bulk of the tab for hosting the Olympics was picked up by federal, state, and local governments who looked at the Olympics as a way to showcase their local economy.  Yet, in the end, financial losses for the host city were usually staggering.<p>  

Now, however, I'm not so sure if a permanent site is the way to go.  Financially speaking, everything changed at the 1984 Games in Los Angeles (actually, LA was the only city to bid for the 1984 Games).   Peter Uberroth switched gears and actually made a profit on the Games, by thinking of them as a private enterprise.  Los Angeles' costs were almost entirely paid through corporate sponsors, the sale of broadcast rights and tickets to the games themselves.  They actually made a profit.  Since 1984, Uberroth's "private enterprise" theory has been adopted by each Olympic host and the Games have been revived.<p>  

Will Atlanta lose money on the '96 Games?  Probably not.  NBC paid the ACOG $456 million for the broadcasting rights, and ticket sales have accounted for over $400 million.  Of course, lets not forget those corporate sponsorships.  Atlanta is laying out about $300 million themselves (mostly for public improvements), and Washington is chipping in around $200 million.  Still, after the dust clears, Atlanta will most likely break even, with all the new construction paid for.  The new facilities  (e.g., the stadium, swimming facilities, athletic fields, gymnasiums, housing and parks) will all be given away after the games.  They'll go to local colleges and the city of Atlanta.  Even the Atlanta Braves will get a new home (the Olympic Stadium).<p>   

Not a bad deal.<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 11:07:05 1996<br> 
Subject: Agreed<p> 

Todd, I agree that we seem to be "over the hump" on this issue.  After Montreal's disaster and Moscow's US-boycotted games, I believe that Los Angeles was the only bidder for 1984.  Now it seems that at least 3 cities realistically vie for each award.<p> 


<hr><p>


Appended by: Quirino Mancini -- Sinisi, Cesschini - Milan<br> 
Date: Wed July 31 08:51:25 1996<br> 
Subject: Permanent Site?<p> 

This one's for Greg and Todd.<p>

Based on the number of cities throughout the world bidding for the 2004 Olympics, and the furor surrounding this matter, it would appear that overall, the Olympics don't prove, in any way, shape or form, to be a bad deal.  Take a look at Rome's application.  The last thing many Romans would like to see is that the eternal city had secured the 2004 Olympic Games.  It's not that Romans are not sports fans, they certainly are, it's just that many of us still recall the months preceding the 1990 Soccer World Cup as being a veritable nightmare, during which the city resembled London in 1940: a city under siege.  Men at work, traffic jams around the clock , organizers of events always running behind  schedule and noise and dust pervading the commoners' daily existence.<p> 

Nonetheless, Mr. Rutelli, the Mayor of Rome, spent several days in Atlanta to lobby the IOC members, as well as to sightsee the Olympic Village and the adjoining stadiums in search of good ideas to take back to Italy.  While Mr. Rutelli was away, however, the spokesman for the Green Party (of which Mr. Rutelli himself is a prominent member) expressed heated criticism at the prospect of Rome hosting the Olympics just 4 years after the 2000 Jubilee, another epic event bound to create dramatic organizational and logistic problems for our capital.  When Mr. Rutelli learned of the above comments, he immediately reassured all and sundry that, if indeed Rome won the bidding and hosts the Olympics in 2004, there will be no negative repercussions for the environment.  Needless to say the Mayor was very disappointed at the stand taken by the Green's spokesman and now many expect the latter to be forced to step down from his post sooner than later.<p> 

The bottom line is that one would never have expected to see the Italian Greens acting as the major sponsors of a mostly business-driven event such as the modern Olympic Games, which amongst other things, will ultimately result in much environmental pollution, tons of fresh cement and tar disseminating throughout the eternal city, in an effort to refurbish the athletic competition venues and the modes of access thereto.  After all, Rome needs not the Olympics to attract tourists and I wonder whether many would  perhaps choose to put off a desired trip to our city purely due to the fact  that the Olympics  were scheduled to take place at that very same time.  There are certain places in this world that many would like to see remain as they have always been, and in the case of our eternal city, as timeless and unchanged as progress, and the years, allow.<p> 

<hr><p>

<H3><a href="/spotlight/games/"><I>Back</I></a></H3>


