<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
<h2>Restraint of Trade</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>
 
Last Append: Tue Jul 30 11:00:16 1996<p>
 
This question comes from Joseph Galanes, esq., at Kristensen, Cummings
et. al., in Vermont.<p> 

"I am a former member of the '88 Olympic Team (Skiing) and currently an
attorney in Vermont. Query: Has anyone considered whether NGB  Amateur
rules restricting participation of so-called  professionals is an unfair
restraint of trade?  In the ski-world it is usually the case that the
amateur athletes are in fact earning more money than their professional
counterparts."<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 15:10:52 1996<br> 
Subject: NGB Rules Barring Pros Galanes<p> 

Regarding the question of Joseph Galanes, Esq. of Kristenson Cummings
(Vermont), I'm not aware any court decisions or lawsuits brought in the
USA against a NGB due to its rules or policy bar- ring pros from Olympic
competition. My general reaction is that a restraint of trade antitrust
theory (Sherman Act l) would not work because you need two or more
parties. It would probably be difficult to show a NGB contact or
conspiracy with a third party to keep out pros. It is likely that a SGB
would be viewed as a "single entity" for Sherman Act purposes, as
distinguished from pro sports leagues where nearly all recent decisions
have treated them as capable of violating Sherman l because their
respective teams compete with one another. If it could be shown that the
NGB held a monopoly over the sport for Olympic participation purposes(I
presume it could) perhaps a Sherman Act 2 claim of monopolization would
be possible.  In Europe, sports federations have on several occasions
been held to violate antitrust (competition) law based on the counter-
part to Sherman 2 monopolization, abuse of dominant position. This has
occurred under European Community law as well as the national antitrust
laws of European Union("EU") and non-EU countries. I'm not aware of any
antitrust suits or proceedings outside of the  USA involving the
particular issue Mr. Galanes raises.<p> 

Aaron N. Wise<br>
Klepner & Cayea, LLP<br>
New York City<p>

<hr><p>


Appended by: Ellen Zavian -- Ellen Zavian - Columbia<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 17:10:08 1996<br> 
Subject: What is an Amateur<p> 

This questions has haunted me for the past few months.  I currently
represent the soccer players and the softball players in this year's
Olympics (women).  The soccer women have a strange situation with their
NGB.  Only 12 players are professional athletes (under contract and paid
a monthly salary) and the remaining athletes are paid per diem and/or
under NCAA rules.<p> 

The softball women are associated with the Amateur Softball Association
and their  IF defines amateur as "paid to play" and "receiving any type
of benefits from playing/fame of such sport". Well, according to the
Softball Association (ASA), the softball women have already violated the
definition of Amateur because they have endorsement contracts and
receive some small amount from the ASA.<p> 

So, this brings me to my point: What is an Amateur?  Does each IF have a
working definition that they keep changing to suit their needs?<p> 

To the general public, and Amateur means "an athlete that is not paid to
 play".  But this gets confusing with my soccer players, the softball
players, the dream teams, etc...<p> 

The ancient Olympic Games were strictly amateur...so said the IOC. But,
after great research, author David Young published in his 1984 book "the
Olympic Myth of Greek Amateur Athletes"...was that the Greek athletes
were not.<p> 

Athletes in the ancient Olympics were professions who competed for prize
money.  It was written that the Greek language did not even have a word
for Amateurism.    Now, the IOC puts the definition on the backs of the
individual International Sports Federations (ISF).    The first
professional athletes in the Olympics was the hockey players in
1984....and other IFs have followed.  In fact, the USOC charter removed
the word "amateur" and put in "finest athletes".<p> 

This new movement away from amateur restrictions allows an athlete to
train longer, be better, and dedicate his/her full time to the sport. 
It does take away some of the control the NGB's have over their
athletes.  They are no longer dependent upon thier NGB's fully.  To me,
this is better.  The NGB's seem to have a greater respect  and tend to
work better with the professional athletes...this is my opinion from my
personal experiences.<p> 

The USOC does pay each athlete for a medal won under their Olympic Gold
Award program: 20,000 for gold, $10,000 for silver, and $5,000 for
bronze to each athlete.  Then, each NGB MAY set up a bonus structure
too.  Many do...but not enough.  The NGB's that still maintain the
amateur status can save themselves money by keeping such amateur
definition.  This is not fair!<p> 

It is time for the USOC to take back the control over such a decision. 
With the Dream Team and other professionals playing...it is time to make
every sport equal...and not leave it in the hands of ISF's to
control.<p> 

We will have the best athletes...not the one's that can only afford to
stay in the game.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jay Levine -- Winston & Strawn - Washington<br>
Date: Mon July 29 22:39:25 1996<br> 
Subject: Restraint of Trade?<p> 

I agree that a single national governing board ("NGB") may not be
considered to be separate legal entities capable of conspiring for
Sherman Act 1 purposes.   If athletes are required to sign contracts
with the NGB, however, that may be a different story.<p> 

With respect to Sherman Act 2, monopolization, the NGB may be considered
to have monopolized the relevant market for the "sport" over which it
governs.  Moreover, its exclusion of certain athletes may be considered
an unlawful refusal to deal.  But query -- what is the anticompetitive
effect, especially since there is no competitor who has been denied
access to an essential facility? Of course, the cases involving
professional athletes and sports leagues have never articulated a
traditional anticompetitive theory either.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York<br> 
Date: Tue July 30 11:00:16 1996<br> 
Subject: Restraint of Trade?<p> 

This append is from Joseph Galanes, esq., at Kristensen, Cummings et.
al., in Vermont.<p>   

"Thank you Mr. Wise for your response to my "restraint of trade" 
inquiry.  With regard to your point that restraint of trade -  antitrust
- requires third party;  Is it possible to argue that  the international
governing body for skiing, FIS, acted in  conspiracy with the NBG to
prevent professional participation.   Ultimately, it is the FIS that is
in competition with the  professional ski tour.  The FIS sanctions all
premier skiing  events (known as World Cup events), controls the number
of  participants and the amateur qualifications of the participants.  
It seems to me the NGB merely echoes FIS amateur rules in order  to
ensure that its athletes are eligible to compete in the  international
competitions, including the Olympics."<p> 

"Thank you for your time and consideration. Joseph Galanes"<BR><BR>

<hr><BR><BR>




Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York <BR>Date: Wed
Jul 31 13:02:58 1996 <BR>Subject: To J. Galanes  RestTrade 
<BR><BR>
If, as you say, the FIS and the U.S. national ski federation (NGB) did
conspire or combine (or contract, if a contract could be shown) to
restrain trade, then, if the requisite anticompetitive effects could be
shown, there may well be a Sherman I claim.  If skiers try to sue not
only NGB but FIS (international federation as well for federal antitrust
violation, they may have significant jurisdictional arguments to
overcome. I assume FIS is located outside of the USA.  See, e.g.,
Karsten Mfg. Corp. v. United States Golf Assn, 728 F. Supp. l429 (D.C.
Ariz. l990). Though not an antitrust case, see also Reynolds v.
International Amateur Athletic Federation, 23 F.3d lll0, l994 WL l86594
(6th Cir. l994), cert. denied, l30 L.Ed.2d 338 (l994). That does not
necessarily mean one could not sue the US NGB alone based on a
conspiracy, combination or contract to restrain trade (Sherman l) or
monopolization (Sherman II). Pls. also note Mr. Levine's comments of
July 29 on the Sherman l issue. Aaron N. Wise Klepner & Cayea, LLP New
York City 


<BR><BR>

