<blockquote>
<h2>Atlanta's Worst Nightmare</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 



Last Append: Mon Jul 29 19:40:01 1996 <p>

I know this isn't exactly Sports Law, but a bomb went off at Centennial Olympic Park at about 1:15 this morning. Mayor Bill Campbell reports that at least 50 people have been taken to local hospitals.<p> 

Police had begun to clear people from the area after a "suspicious package" was noticed. The police and fire departments had also received bomb threats.<p> 

What does this mean for what was supposed to be the largest international peacetime gathering?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: William H. Schroder Jr -- Schroder Partners LC - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Sun Jul 28 12:16:38 1996<br> 
Subject: Nuts!<p> 

And it means nothing more other than confirmation of the already well-known reality that humanity has its share of nuts!  Whether it's church or rock concert, nuts will set off bombs.  And especially when they can go home afterwards and read about it and see it on TV ad nauseam.  But it means nothing to the peacemakers, other than inspiration to "keep on keeping on!"  For the nuts of the world are the peacemakers' raison d'etre.  There should be *more* Olympics, to spread the message of peace.<p> 

Bill<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles<br>
Date: Mon July 29 19:30:44 1996<br> 
Subject: the Olympic spirit<p> 

Gail Devers said after she won her gold medal that she sends her condolences to the families of those injured and killed by the pipe bomb, but that the Olympic spirit must prevail.  It is that kind of Olympic will that will not allow any nut/terrorist/crazed villain to interrupt these Games.  But I think that although the Olympic spirit is even stronger in Atlanta and across the world, whoever set the bomb off doesn't care!  He/she/they just wanted the attention, to say "we did that!"  The bomber/s don't care if the news story lasted 30 minutes or 3 days--the bomber/s got what they wanted---publicity. This world does produce some very sick people....<p> 

-Maria Dennis<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 19:40:01 1996<br> 
Subject: What Atlanta is doing<p> 

PAPER: <I>Fulton County Daily Report</I><p>

DATE: July 30, 1996<p>

HEADLINE: Bombing Puts U.S. Team in Action<p> 

BY ANN WOOLNER<p>

Associate Editor<p>

AND EMILY HELLER<p>

Staff Reporter<p>

The bomb that exploded at Centennial Olympic Park early Saturday morning sent into action a non-sports team USAa group of prosecutors from the U.S. attorney's office here assigned to work with federal agents in the search for the culprit.<p> 

Formed in August 1995, the team is led by U.S. Attorney Kent B. Alexander. First Assistant U.S. Attorney Janet F. King is the designated team leader. It also includes Senior Litigation Counsel William L. McKinnon Jr. and Assistant U.S. Attorneys Randy S. Chartash, David C. Nutter and Janis Gordon, according to a government description of the team in April.<p> 

The lawyers in the Olympic Critical Incident Team have attended field training exercises and conferences to prepare them for a variety of crises, according to the U.S. attorney's office. They worked alongside the FBI to decide courses of action to be taken in a number of hypothetical terrorist actions, from hostage- taking at Lake Lanier to the release of toxic gas into the subway system, among those was one related to "explosions at an Olympic Venue."<p> 

In what has become a feature of major federal cases, prosecutors join at the investigative stage to try to ensure that evidence and arrests stand up in court. For the prosecutors, the training exercises raised legal questions such as those concerning electronic intercepts and proper searches and seizures.<p> 

The Olympic team of lawyers also attended conferences and briefings on "post-blast incident/crisis response training," terrorism and diplomatic issues, the government says.<p> 

In investigations such as these, prosecutors work hand in glove with investigative agents, according to Henry dePippo, who, as senior trial counsel in the Southern District of New York, helped prosecute the World Trade Center bombers. He is now a white-collar criminal-defense lawyer in Rochester, N.Y.<p> 

Neither Alexander nor Gordon will discuss details, but Alexander says, "We are working around the clock."<p> 

Government lawyers and government agents worked closely together locally in another notorious case when Louis J. Freeh, then associate U.S. attorney from the Southern District of New York, was brought to Atlanta in 1990 to run the multi-state, multi- agency investigation into the mail-bomb deaths of 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals Judge Robert S. Vance and Savannah lawyer Robert E. Robinson. That investigation, which had been mired in multi-jurisdictional issues in the months between the mail-bomb deaths and Freeh's appointment, eventually brought the conviction of Walter Leroy Moody Jr. of Rex.<p> 

Freeh now heads the Federal Bureau of Investigation. An assistant U.S. attorney he brought with him from New York to Atlanta to help in the mail- bomb case, Howard M. Shapiro, now works as the FBI's general counsel.<p> 

Moody's lead defender, Edward D. Tolley, says Freeh's experience and success in the Moody case will make the eventual prosecution of the Olympic bomber hard for defense lawyers.<p> 

Freeh "knows bombs better than most folks," says Tolley, a partner at Cook, Noell, Tolley & Wiggins in Athens. And that is "a great challenge for the defense," Tolley says.<p> 

The Moody investigation was "really comprehensive," says Atlanta lawyer Michael R. Hauptman, who represented Moody for a time. "The federal government left no stone unturned," says Hauptman. "I would expect a similar type of thoroughness."<p> 

The Atlanta-based prosecutors report to Justice Department officials normally based in Washington. Deputy Attorney General Jamie S. Gorelick has been overseeing security matters for the Justice Department, according to a spokesman, and is the person to whom Alexander reports.<p> 

The Moody case "probably gives people a good road map" for the investigation and prosecution, says Joe D. Whitley, who became U.S. attorney after the Moody case was under way.<p> 

Whitley, now in private practice at Kilpatrick & Cody, says he would not be surprised if the Justice Department appoints a special prosecutor to head the team.<p> 

Although Atlanta prosecutors are qualified to handle the case and the bomb's apparent lack of sophistication might not call for a specialized prosecutor, Whitley says, control by Washington is possible because of the "heightened degree of attention" given the Olympics- week bombing.<p> 

The e-mail addresses of Ann Woolner and Emily Heller are, respectively,<br> awoolner@counsel.com and eheller@counsel.com.<p>

<hr><p>
 


Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta <BR>Date: Sat Aug  3 11:41:03 1996 <BR>Subject: Atlanta's worst nightmare <BR><BR>

<P>Here's a story from the Daily Report on the obscure lawyer representing the accused Centennial Park bomber. It's amazing how he fell into the case.  </P>

<P>DATE: Aug. 2, 1996</P>

<P>HEADLINE:'I Have Been Hit by Lightning'</P>

<P>DECK:Bomb Case Puts Obscure Lawyer Who Knows Suspect into Limelight  </P>

<P>BY EMILY HELLER, Staff Reporter</P>

<P>G. Watson Bryant Jr., an Atlanta lawyer with a quiet transactional practice, has been thrust into the international limelight by representing Richard Jewell, a suspect in the bombing of Centennial Olympic Park.  </P>

<P>Bryant says he and Jewell met when they worked at the Small Business Administration in the 1980s. Jewell was a clerk in a supply room. Bryant closed loans.  </P>

<P>"Jewell is a friendly, outgoing guy," Bryant says. "We laughed a lot."  </P>

<P>Even though Bryant and his client are famous to watchers of television news shows, Bryant is virtually unknown in the city's legal community.  </P>

<P>It is buzzing with talk of how Bryant, a practitioner with a business law practice, has become part of what could become one of Georgia's most high- profile criminal prosecutions.  </P>

<P>In a telephone interview Thursday, Bryant, who calls himself a private person, seemed equally stunned.  </P>

<P>"I have been hit by lightning," he says. "I cannot believe that odds are I would know someone who would be accused of bombing the park."  </P>

<P>Federal investigators have been trying to determine whether Jewell, a private agency security guard on duty at Centennial Olympic Park, played a role in the July 27 pipe-bomb explosion that killed one woman and injured more than 100.  </P>

<P>On Wednesday the Federal Bureau of Investigation searched Jewell's apartment on Buford Highway and a shed in Habersham County. The search warrant and its affidavits were sealed.  </P>

<P>Having received 500 phone calls in two days, including offers of help, Bryant says, he is assembling a defense team, should Jewell be arrested.  </P>

<P>"I got all kinds of people offering to help that are well- schooled [in criminal-defense law] and I intend to take advantage of it for Richard," Bryant says.  </P>

<P>He refuses to say whom he has contacted, but says he hopes no defense team will be needed. Bryant says he thinks the investigation is moving away from his client.  </P>

<P>"I am only involved in this to try to control the situation until such time,  until I can get a specialist to handle" the case, Bryant says. "I am not pretending to be a criminal trial lawyer. I am smarter than that."  </P>

<P>Bryant says he was appointed defense counsel in some Fulton County cases but does not recall how many or what kind of cases.  </P>

<P>Jewell does not have the financial resources to "retain some hotshot right now," Bryant says.  </P>

<P>Bryant says he has not represented Jewell in any previous legal matters, either criminal or civil.  </P>

<P>"Richard doesn't have any property that's even worthy of a will," Bryant says.  </P>

<P>Meanwhile, however, Bryant is furious at investigators' "leaking" of information about the case to the news media and says Jewell might bring a suit.  </P>

<P>"I'd sure like to know who the hell it is that's talking to the newspaper," Bryant says. "It's not a three-ring circus. It's a 100-ring circus. It's ridiculous.  </P>

<P>"We want them to be accountable for their misbehavior," Bryant says, speaking of investigators who he says divulged information improperly. "There are laws and regulations and guidelines that prohibit this. I think it's probably a criminal act to disclose information from an ongoing criminal investigation."  </P>

<P>He expresses frustration about getting no information from the FBI. He says he does not know what evidence the government used to get search warrants, because the documents are under seal.  </P>

<P>"What the hell is probable cause for busting up Jewell?" Bryant says.  </P>

<P>He said the FBI told him the search would take an hour or two, but it took 10. "To take 10 hours to search a two-bedroom apartment seems to be a little bit excessive," he says. "I don't mean a little bit. I mean a lot."  </P>

<P>He also took umbrage at the large number of investigators in "color-coded" shirts conducting the searches: "It's like I'm walking around Six Flags or something."  </P>

<P>And he fumes about the FBI's towing Jewell's truck to Washington or New York to be picked over while Jewell is still making payments on it. "I think they've legally stolen it," he says.  </P>

<P>FBI spokesman Jay Spadafore declines to comment.  </P>

<P>'A Lot of Good Clients'</P>

<P>Bryant, a 45-year-old 1977 University of South Carolina law graduate, will not say who his clients are and defines his practice only as transactional.  </P>

<P>After graduating from law school in 1977, Bryant went to work for the Small Business Administration, where he closed disaster loans. </P>


<P>He launched a private practice but had no luck obtaining clients.  </P>

<P>Bryant next worked as a prosecutor in Atlanta Municipal Court for 18 months, then returned to private practice at Freeman & Hawkins for one year.  </P>

<P>He went back out on his own and by then had obtained a master's degree in tax law at Emory University. Still unsuccessful at developing a client base, he returned to the SBA in 1982 and stayed five years.  </P>

<P>After his second stint at the SBA, during which Bryant met Jewell, Bryant returned in 1987 to a private practice, as an associate at the former Schwall, Ruff & Goodman, a small, general civil practice firm.  </P>

<P>He worked there for about two years in the late 1980s, doing mostly SBA loan closings, recalls Emory A. Schwall, whose Atlanta firm is now called Schwall & Schwall.  </P>

<P>Bryant "wasn't much into trial work," Schwall says.  </P>

<P>Bryant left voluntarily, Schwall says, to work solo from an office his father owned, then becoming of counsel to Fishman & Heaton, which ultimately dissolved.  </P>

<P>He has worked from second-floor office space in Nickolas P. Chilivis' Buckhead building the past four or five.  </P>

<P>Chilivis, a prominent trial lawyer, says he sees Bryant coming and going, using the library and meeting with clients in the conference rooms.  </P>

<P>"I do know he is a competent lawyer," says Chilivis. "He seems to be a busy lawyer with a lot of good clients. A lot of them look distinguished and prominent." But Chilivis says he does not know who they are.  </P>

<P>"I never have asked him what kind of cases" Bryant takes, he says. </P>


<P>Sued over SBA Loan</P>

<P>Court records provide a few details of Bryant's practice.  </P>

<P>His work at the Schwall firm was the subject of a suit by a former client, ITT Small Business Finance Corp.  </P>

<P>Bryant closed a $720,000 SBA- backed loan to Club Rio on Luckie Street in downtown Atlanta. SBA paid its $640,000 guarantee when the club was liquidated in bankruptcy. However, the SBA found tax liens of $113,000.  </P>

<P>The existence of the liens violated an agency rule against backing loans for borrowers who owe back taxes. When the SBA threatened to sue ITT and suspend it from lending nationwide, ITT refunded the money.  </P>

<P>ITT then turned to Bryant, who it argued concealed the liens from the lender at closing, thus committing fraud and malpractice.  </P>

<P>Bryant said he had disclosed the liens to an ITT loan officer and inquired how the matter should be handled.  </P>

<P>At the time, Bryant said 80 percent of his practice related to loan closings, a stream of business he intended to maintain (Daily Report, July 12, 1994).  </P>

<P>But the case was bad for business. In 1992, Bryant entered a consent order, not admitting guilt, that suspended him from government practice.  </P>

<P>Bryant won summary judgment on the fraud claim in 1994. He said at the time he was "backstabbed" by ITT and vowed he would not settle.  </P>

<P>Bryant has participated in some civil litigation, records in federal District Court show.  </P>

<P>He represented a co-owner of seven Little Caesar pizza franchises in the Atlanta area. The plaintiffs, a father and son and their company, sued Little Caesar to rescind franchise contracts, claiming the company defrauded them by inflating sales figures for stores, six of which were company-owned.  </P>

<P>Although Bryant represented a plaintiff, lead counsel in the case was John P. MacNaughton of Morris, Manning & Martin.  </P>

<P>After a bench trial, Judge Willis B. Hunt Jr. found for Little Caesar in the amount of $219,326, ruling that some Little Caesar's figures were unintentionally erroneous but that the plaintiffs' accountants could have discovered the miscalculations. The matter is on appeal.  </P>

<P>Neither MacNaughton nor his co- counsel, Frank W. DeBorde, could be reached for comment.  </P>

<P>Criminal-defense attorneys, buzzing about the case, say they have never heard of Bryant and express curiosity about the legal counsel Jewell is receiving.  </P>

<P>"Who the hell is Watson Bryant?" quips Atlanta attorney Donald F. Samuel, past president of the Georgia Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. Samuel was co- counsel in the notorious mail- bomb case of Walter Leroy Moody Jr., the Rex man convicted of murdering a federal appeals court judge and a Savannah lawyer.  </P>

<P>GACDL President Aimee R. Maxwell says she does not know Bryant and hopes he is consulting with a defender.  </P>

<P>"What is happening at this stage is going to be critical to the case if they actually can make a case against" Jewell, she says.  </P>

<P>Told of Bryant's background in loan closings and commercial transactions, the defense lawyer says pointedly, "I would never walk into a closing without a specialist in real estate."  r  </P>

<P>Emily Heller's e-mail address is eheller@counsel.com.  </P>






<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Sanford J. Asman -- Hopkins & Thomas - Atlanta<BR> Date: Sat Aug  3 09:52:41 1996 <BR>Subject: Atlanta's worst nightmare  
<BR><BR>
"Who the hell is Watson Bryant?" asked Atlanta attorney Donald F. Samuel, past president of the Georgia Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, whose client, Walter Leroy Moody Jr., was convicted of murdering a federal appeals court judge and a Savannah lawyer.   
<BR><BR>
I guess he's a lawyer who has not yet had a client convicted of murdering anyone in a bombing.  Sandy  







<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Ernest Baynard -- Baynard Law Firm - McLean <BR>Date: Sun Aug  4 13:19:33 1996 <BR>Subject: what arrogance! 
<BR><BR>
Who is Bryant indeed.  What unbridled arrogance.  Bryant appears to be a guy who has survived in a tough market, knows how to try a law suit, and is representing Jewell.  I have successfully defended numerous people accused of crime and have yet to discover any mystical, unattainable quality required in a defense attorney. Hard work, knowledge of the rules of evidence, and a touch of panache are all thatis required.  Bryant will do just fine. 





<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Jennifer Fox -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<BR> Date: Mon Aug  5 09:05:54 1996 <BR>Subject: Atlanta's worst nightmare 
<BR><BR>
From Paul M. Lavelle -- Attorney at Law -- New Orleans: 
<BR><BR>
I cannot believe that this article was published by the Daily Report. I find it to be an incredible violation of Mr. Bryant's privacy.  What relevance or interest does his conflict with ITT bear to his representation of Jewell.  This, in my opinion, represents the worst kind of journalism. 





<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: David L Haron -- Frank and Stefani - Troy <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 15:11:02 1996 <BR>Subject: privacy 
<BR><BR>
"I cannot believe that this article was published by the Daily Report" 
<BR><BR>
While I agree that the Daily Report's article could be considered an unnecessary invasion, but to a certain extent, Mr. Bryant, IMHO, asked for it by appearing on every talk show, etc. that would have him, including Today, CNN and Larry King. Once you seek your 15 minutes of fame, you're like the dog who catches the bus., you get it and don't realize how difficult it is to control it. On that subject, I guess I'm from the old school where attorneys tried their cases in court, not on TV (or perhaps in my case, the radio <G>). I realize it's not necessarily unethical but why do it? 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


