<blockquote>
<h2>Live From Atlanta -- NOT</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 


Last Append: Tue July 30 10:32:16 1996<p>

Is NBC's coverage of the Olympics--rebroadcasting previously taped
events as if they were live, without an indication that the event was
held earlier in the day, dishonest?<p> 

One broadcast of a woman's bicycle race was particularly annoying. John
Tesh was describing the event in the present tense, but it was clear the
event had been held earlier in the day. That's because during the bike
race it was raining, and the rain had stopped by the evening broadcast.
In fact, just before it showed the bike race, it showed a sunny crowd in
the bleachers of the swimming stadium. The whole think looked rather
sloppy.<p> 

NBC says people don't really care, they are watching the events for
entertainment, not for news. As a viewer, I want to know whether what I
am watching is live or taped. How about you?<p>  

<hr><p>

Appended by: Monica Bay -- Counsel Connect - San Francisco<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 14:53:00 1996<br> 
Subject: Entertainment v. News<p> 

I'm with you, Ellie.<p> 

BTW: There is a long discussion in Cracker-barrel about Tesh.<p> 

Bottom line: pretty negative.<p>


Posted by Monica Bay, Sr. Law Editor<br>
(415) 749 5511<br> 
monica.bay@counsel.com<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 15:03:29 1996<br> 
Subject: Patronizing the Viewer AGAIN<p> 

Yes, I agree with you!   I am insulted that NBC thinks I am an idiot
sitting in my easy chair watching TV at 9pm and believing that it is
sunny in Atlanta as I watch beach volleyball.  What I would like to know
is---when was this game?  Yesterday, today?  It is ridiculous.  Besides
the fact that NBC does it for entertainment purposes, I think that NBC
thinks if we knew the truth (and probably the outcome), then we wouldn't
watch it!!!<p> 

Since when was following the Olympics only learning the results of
events?  I want to see the action, the heartbreak, the elation involved
with the whole event...and the truth.  Moreover, I want to see the truth
even if it is boring to TV producers.  And I feel manipulated by NBC.<p>


I feel like I am watching "Hard Copy" (or shall we say, "Entertainment
Tonight"?), not the greatest sports event in the world.<p> 

-Maria Dennis, Co-Moderator<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Deirdre Terry -- Counsel Connect - New York<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 15:21:57 1996<br> 
Subject: Live from Atlanta--NOT<p> 

NBC reportedly did lots of focus groups and found that people didn't
care if they were seeing the events live. And there is a lot of need for
taped coverage in an event like the Olympics, where several competitions
are going on in different locations at one time, and some events (such
as gymnastics) have several things going on at once. You couldn't
possibly cover all that satisfactorily in real time.<p> 

In concluding that people also didn't care about being misled about it,
however, I think that NBC made a mistake.<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston<br> 
Date: Fri July 26 15:18:30 1996<br> 
Subject: Live from Atlanta--NOT<p> 

I know it's not live, but I certainly don't want to know the results.  I
tune into the games for more than the scores, but it definitely ruins it
for me to know the outcome.  Last night I made sure to avoid finding out
who won the all-around.  Part of the excitement of watching sports is
not knowing what will happen & the highs & lows as your team's fortunes
change.  The fact that the event is not taking place simultaneously is
not that relevant.<p> 

BTW, how do you expect NBC to televise all of these events, from who
knows how many venues, live.  This is not a football game they're
putting on.  With the notable exception of some announcers (although
Tesh is so sappy he's fun to watch), I think NBC has done a good job. 
Bob Costas has been great (as usual).<p>
 
<hr><p>

Appended by: Eleanor Kerlow -- DC Counsel Connect - Washington<br> 
Date: Tue July 30 10:32:16 1996<br> 
Subject: Doesn't have to be live<p> 

I never said the coverage of all of the events should be live. I said
NBC should be up front about whether an event happened earlier in the
day or is happening during prime time, as I am watching it. Personally,
I don't mind knowing the results before seeing the event. I may learn
that Carl Lewis won his fourth gold medal in the long jump and still
tune in later to watch how he did it.<p> 

Elli<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Suzanne Schiller -- Pepper Hamilton & Scheetz -
Philadelphia<br> 
Date: Wed July 31 00:53:04 1996<br> 
Subject: Live - Prerecorded<p> 

On the West  Coast, it is commonplace to see "live" events like the
Oscars or the Emmys tape delayed (even when the event occurs in the same
time zone).  Almost always these shows have an announcement at the start
of, and a caption during, the program alerting viewers to the fact that
the show was "prerecorded for rebroadcast in this time zone."   Yet
people in California still manage to participate in the excitement of
seeing a winner being announced despite the fact that it actually
happened three hours earlier.  So, I can't imagine that NBC would be
doing itself much harm if it advised its viewers that the events took
place earlier in the day.<p> 

But the missing caption is only part of the deceit that NBC appears to
be engaging in and it is not, in my opinion, the worst. It is my
understanding that in addition to the events not being broadcast live,
much of the "running" commentary, at least in gymnastics, has been
dubbed in after the event in an effort to heighten the drama.  So when
John Tesh says in an ominous tone, "he needs a 9.878 to stay in the
medal hunt," Tesh and the rest of the NBC team already know whether that
score was achieved.  Thus, NBC is actually manipulating how those events
are perceived by the viewing audience.  This, to me, is a far worse
insult to the intelligence of the viewers than the mere omission of an
announcement as to whether or not the event is being broadcast live.<p> 


---Shosh<p>   

<hr><p>

Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br>
Date: Wed July 31 07:14:00 1996<br> 
Subject: Voice-overs<p> 

Does anyone know for a fact whether Tesh's commentary was a
voice-over?<p> 

I know that Al Trautwig's reports on the cycling and mountain biking
events were -- they were cut and edited and turned more into a story
than a traditional sports broadcast (and, by the way, I thought they
were GREAT. A nice change of pace, making an otherwise lengthy and
potentially tedious event into something really exciting)<p> 

Anyone know for sure what is voiced-over and what is not?<p> 

And, yes, I think that NBC would be doing everyone a great service if it
just put a "LIVE-NBC" in the upper corner when an event IS live.<p> 

Ted Curtis<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Quirino Mancini -- Sinisi, Cesschini - Milan<br> 
Date: Wed July 31 08:34:10 1996<br> 
Subject: Live from Atlanta--NOT<p> 

Please advise the NBC that the Italian viewers have also, by now,
realized that the NBC is playing strange games with respect to the
"live" coverage of the Olympic Games.  The most well read Italian sports
paper today displayed an entire column, criticizing the way the NBC
purports to be broadcasting certain events as though they were live
which, instead, took place hours earlier.  In particular, the anchorman
Bob Costas was noted as promising an update on Kerri Strug's injury
"within the next thirty minutes" (as if the event had just taken place),
ignoring the fact that the issue had already been covered by CNN.<p> 

<hr><p>




Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa <BR>Date: Fri Aug  2 10:59:05 1996 <BR>Subject: NBC <BR><BR>

There I was, watching the Games last night: a GREAT gold medal game going on in women's soccer involving the U.S. team, the closing innings of the Japan-U.S. semi-final baseball game, and the pre-game of the Dream Team game. And we get the Dream Team game preview and its opening minutes? 
<BR><BR>
What is NBC thinking? Or are they?
<BR><BR>
The stories on NBC done by Al Trautwig just keep getting better but NBC's live coverage has been a total broadcasting disaster. 
<BR><BR>
Ted Curtis<BR>
Forum Co-moderator


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


Appended by: Evelyn Storch -- Tompkins McGuire - Newark <BR>Date: Sat Aug  3 08:58:56 1996 <BR>Subject: Voice-Over 
<BR><BR>
I attended the Women's Individual All-Around Gymnastics Finals, and I was sitting directly across from the area in which John Tesh was seated.  Periodically,  we watched him through the binoculars, and it did not appear that he was commentating.  We concluded that he would add his commentary later.  I have not yet viewed my tape of the event, so I don't really know how it was broadcast. 
<BR><BR>
Having now seen the event live, however, I must admit that I do not see an evil in the later dubbing.  When you watch it on TV, you're aware that performances on more than one apparatus are going on at once, but you can't realize how completely impossible it is to follow each and every apparatus for each and every competitor.  Sometimes, all four performances are going on simultaneously; at other times, none.  Frankly, I don't know how they would be able to do it otherwise.  Moreover,  while attending that event was utterly thrilling, the one thing we missed was the commentary letting us know who was in contention and how many points they needed.  The voice-over  pulls it all together, adds drama and maintains the focus.  I'm in favor of doing it in whatever manner it takes to do it well. 

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Mary Zwick -- The Chemical Co. - Midland <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 15:22:01 1996 <BR>Subject: Voice-Over 
<BR><BR>
I can understand doing voice-overs and dubbing in commentary for an event like gymnastics where many athletes are competing simultaneously.  What I think is dishonest is when NBC would show events that clearly have taken place hours previously without stating that they occurred much earlier. 
<BR><BR>
I also noticed that NBC dragged out its coverage of gymnastics, swimming, and track so that, even though these events were taking place during prime time, the NBC coverage of the events didn't end until several hours after the actual event had concluded.  As I mentioned in another thread, I had my choice in coverage between NBC and CBC (from Windsor).  CBC had to be off the air by 11 PM,  and it almost always managed to get its coverage of all the important events concluded by that time.  The fact that NBC used tape in presenting such "live" events was what I really objected to.  They should at least have had a graphic on the screen delineating the taped events from the live ones, in order to avoid misleading the public (but they probably chose not to because that would tip off people to how much videotape they were actually using). 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<BR> Date: Tue Aug  6 18:21:09 1996 <BR>Subject: Not for Prime Time Athletes 
<BR><BR>
I also found all of the time-shifting interesting because, as I recall, one reason why the Atlanta games generated huge TV money interest was the fact that it was in the US Eastern time zone and thus most sports could be shown live. 



