<h2>Arbitration Confidentiality</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>

Last Append: Mon Jul 29 10:00:53 1996<p>

Many binding arbitrations related to these Olympic Games have been held
already, yet the world is unaware.  The reason is the confidentiality
that historically has been one of the essential features of the
arbitration process.<p>

The athletes were required, at a very late stage in their years of
preparation for these Games, to commit as a condition precedent to their
participation in these Games that all disputes would be decided through
confidential binding arbitration.  This required commitment took such
disputes out of the courts and enshrouded them in a cloak of secrecy.<p>

The Olympic Games are a public event, witnessed worldwide by upwards of
4 billion people.  While it is athletes who compete, they do so under
the flags of and as representatives for their countries, there being 197
nations represented in these Games in Atlanta.  We here are a free and
open society, and our courts provide equal and full access to all, and
in a public forum.<p>

Binding arbitration, IMHO, is by far the preferred method of dispute
resolution in the Olympic Games.  But being that the public is
integrally involved, that the disputants are representatives of the
various nations of the world who are responsible for their being here
and who must live with the glory and tragedy of their results in the
competition, there exists a valid argument that the dispute resolution
process should in these circumstances be open to public view, just as
the competitions themselves are open to public view.  And, accordingly,
that the athletes and the countries whom they represent have given up
too valuable a right in being required to waive a public forum for their
disputes, a right that we in this democracy have honored for 200 years
as integral not only to justice for the individual, but also to the
stability of the country itself.<p>

Would you agree with this argument that Olympics arbitrations should be
open instead of closed?<p>

Bill<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: C. Peter Goplerud -- Oklahoma Univ. Law - Norman<br> Date:
Mon Jul 29 09:45:58 1996<br> Subject: Arbitration Confidentiality<p>

Inasmuch as arbitration is an alternative dispute resolution process, it
seems appropriate that something less than open proceedings should be
utilized.  However, it also seems reasonable that the results should be
made public.<p>

Peter Goplerud<p>

<br><p>

Appended by: William H. Schroder Jr -- Schroder Partners LC -
Atlanta<br> Date: Mon Jul 29 10:00:53 1996<br> Subject: Arbitrator's
Perspective<p>

I'd like to add another perspective to the foregoing discussion:  the
nature of arbitration, and especially its confidentiality, prevents the
construction of a body of precedent that can guide both the public (here
Olympic athletes, coaches, etc.) in its behavior and also we future
arbitrators who are faced with identical, or at least similar, issues. 
This is a large issue in the philosophical debate that goes on regarding
the benefits of arbitration vis-à-vis litigation, and oftentimes the
particular benefits of arbitration override society's need for
precedent.<p>

Here in the Olympics, however, a worldwide public spectacle wherein 197
countries compete for honor and glory in a large number of events and in
a very compressed time frame of but 17 days, with all of the myriad of
disputes being resolved by private, confidential, binding arbitration,
the issue of achieving guidance for the arbitrators, in the interest at
least of consistency of result, takes on added weight.  There are those
who contend that the cloak of secrecy ought to be raised, if only for
the arbitrator panels that have been set up to hear the disputes on a
fast-track basis.  They argue that this morning's arbitrator panel ought
to be aware of how last night's arbitrator panel decided an almost
identical issue, and, for example, what penalty was exacted for a
similar Code of Conduct violation.  Those who argue to the contrary
respond that arbitration by nature is private and confidential,
important elements in making it expeditious and final.  They argue that
to allow chinks in the armor of arbitration confidentiality is to risk
waiving the cloak of secrecy entirely, thereby removing a key benefit of
arbitration and risking further that the matter will end up being tried
in the courts and in the media, making an Olympics as we know it totally
unworkable.  Inconsistency of arbitration result, they posit, is part of
the price that must be paid for the overall good accomplished by the
holding of an Olympics.<p>

Should the Olympics arbitrators have a "right to know" the details of
previous Olympics arbitrations as a guide in the performance of their
duties and in the interest of consistency of result?  Or would this
damage unacceptably the benefits brought by arbitration to the Olympic
Games?<p>

Bill<p>

<hr><p>


Appended by: Patrick J Goggins -- Steel Hector - Miami<br> Date: Tue
July 30 18:02:21 1996<br> Subject: Arbitration Confidentiality<p>

The agreement to arbitrate is enforceable on its terms.  If the athlete
agrees to compete subject to the arbitration provision, that provision
should be enforceable unless the athlete can prove overreaching, etc. 
The above posts raise the interesting question of the rights of third
parties to arbitration information.  How would someone do it?  Argue
public policy?  I'm aware of no policy requiring disclosure of
information relating to a private dispute.<p>

Patrick Goggins<br> pgoggins@counsel.com<p>

<hr><p>
 

Appended by: Barry D. Bayer -- Law Office Tech Rev - Homewood<BR> Date: Sat Aug  3 09:32:50 1996 <BR>Subject: Arbitration Confidentiality <BR><BR>

<P>what you say is sound, patrick, if you assume your premise. </P>

<P>However....isn't that sort of a contract of adhesion? and when we are speaking of the olympics ( with all sort of federal breaks for the olympic committee and so forth) doesn't the public have some interest in knowign what is going on? </P>

<P>HOWEVER.....maybe the olympics committee, which knows how to do things without leaking to the press, ought to run the fbi investigations. </P>


<p>

