<blockquote>
<h2>Atlanta -- The Wrong Choice?</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

Last Append: Tue July 30 14:37:14 1996<BR><BR>

Did the IOC make a mistake in handing the Summer Games over to Atlanta?<p> 

The international community seems to think so.  An article in today's New York Times reports that international delegations are furious over the way Atlanta has hosted the Games.  A few examples: A Georgian weight lifter missed an event because a bus driver did not know his route.  A German swimmer appeared on the scoreboard as a citizen of Ghana.  A kayaker from Antigua was injured when a shuttle bus hit a concrete barrier.  A Ugandan boxer was listed as more than 19 feet tall.  The Italians have complained that their team has nowhere to boil water for a decent pot of pasta.  The list goes on and on (remember the lights going out on the Dream Team?).  The President of the ACOG admits that there have been problems, primarily with transportation and the IBM results system, but still professes that these would be the "greatest games ever."<p>   

Has Atlanta blown it?  One can argue that Atlanta is doing quite well, considering the scope and production of the Summer Games.  Perhaps a larger questions here is whether or not turning the games over to American private enterprise has resulted in a far too big of a production, causing Atlanta to crack at the seams.<p> 



<P><HR><P>

Appended by: Mary Jane Saunders -- Arter & Hadden - Washington <BR>Date: Fri July 26 17:48:18 1996 <BR>Subject: In Defense of Atlanta <BR><BR>

I just returned from the Summer Games.  I think the transportation glitches have been blown way out of proportion.  Sure MARTA is crowed, but so is DC's Metro.  Don't condemn the entire operation for one or two mishaps.  By and large, the crowds are hot but happy.  Southern hospitality at its best.<p> 

BTW, you can get tickets (face value or less) and hotel rooms.<p> 


<P><HR><P>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles <BR>Date: Fri July 26 21:42:20 1996 <BR>Subject: Unhappy Merchants <BR><BR>

Not only are there transportation glitches, but the Atlanta Games are not turning out to be as great as some people thought-especially some of the vendors and storeowners who were promised a big boom in their businesses.  For example, some of the stores around Savannah are extremely upset at the lack of business (isn't that where some of the water events are being held?) and some of the vendors in Centennial Park have actually packed up and gone home!<p>  

Were these people falsely misled to believe an increase in business by ACOG?  Is business so bad because of logistics?  Or bad luck?  Were the merchants privy to any of the plans for their area so that they could make an educated decision about their businesses?  I can see that if they were misled regarding logistical or geographical plans, then they have a reason to complain.  But it is probably just bad luck and I feel sorry for the unfulfilled expectations.<p> 

I know business is sometimes harsh and luck is fickle, but these storeowners and vendors are ANGRY.  Can anything be done and whose fault, if there is any, is it?<p> 


-Maria Dennis, Co-Moderator<p>


<P><HR><P>

Appended by: Jay Barber -- Ogletree Deakins - Atlanta <BR>Date: Sat July 27 12:30:04 1996 <BR>Subject: Atlanta -- The Wrong Choice? <BR><BR>

Nobody was "promised" anything.  Your post indicates that you have no idea what you are talking about.  First, Savannah is host to yachting only (not exactly a big crowd pleaser, but well attended just the same).  There was never  any expected "boom" to Savannah. Moreover, there are no "vendors" in Centennial Park that are also not sponsors, and, of course, none of those have left.  The "vendors" that you speak of  were licensed by the city, not ACOG, and if they have had no business, so be it.  In business, you pay your money and you take your chances, and these "vendors" lost out.  Too bad.  They were an eyesore to begin with (coming under criticism from the IOC for ruining the ambiance of the Games, a sentiment that I share).  Good riddance to them.  They made their choices about locations they wished to lease and they did not pay off. 
<BR><BR>
Jay

<P><HR><P>

Appended by: Richard North -- Nelson Mullins - Atlanta <BR>Date: Sat July 27 23:20:52 1996<BR> Subject: SHUT UP!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! <BR><BR>

I realize that this discussion was initiated before last night's tragic bombing.  I also recognize that Todd probably does not know how idiotic he now sounds.    Perhaps some of you believe that the critical story here is the logistical functioning of the Games.  In that regard, there is no doubt that the bussing of the media was flawed in the initial days of the Games, and that IBM has completely screwed up the event-result system devised for the games.   By the same token, there is also no question that the foreign journalists have been eager to find any fault they could in these Games and that the snobbish New York and Los Angeles media have been readily manipulated to verify "problems" in these Games. It is perhaps most revealing that New York City has (only now) launched a major effort to obtain the Games at a future date. I hope New York is successful.  I also hope the city is successful in preventing every "crazy" from invading any public area and endangering the public.  I hope that the city can also conduct the Games without making people feel the fear that I suspect will now be inevitable.  Most of all, I hope that the rest of this great nation will rally around New York City, at that time, to help in such an endeavor. In the meantime, I am going to be at every event in Atlanta I can.  I hope, although I doubt, that everyone in this country -- unlike Todd -- can support me in that effort! 


<P><HR><P>

Appended by: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta <BR>Date: Sun July 28 14:53:27 1996 <BR>Subject: Asking the Questions <BR><BR>

I realize that the question mark at the end of Todd's subject line doesn't show up til you open the thread, but please remember that it's there. It's legitimate to ask whether Atlanta was the wrong choice, in the context of the criticism being heaped on the city last week.<p> 

Asking the question doesn't equal taking the position, and that's not what Todd intended to do.<p> 

And for the record (admitting my bias as a native Atlantan), I think Atlanta was a great choice. I keep hearing the same incidents brought up when journalists talk about problems with transportation and technology; percentage-wise, these seem to be very small fractions of the overall operation.<p> 

The bombing is an entirely different question of course, having taken place in a public park, not an Olympic venue.

<P><HR><P>

Appended by: James Clark -- Baker & Daniels - Indianapolis <BR>Date: Sun July 28 15:09:45 1996 <BR>Subject: Yikes! <BR><BR>

It's understandable that nerves would be frayed in Atlanta, but I don't agree that  Todd (or Maria or anyone else) sounds "idiotic." Todd correctly noted that an unflattering article had appeared in the New York Times.  Similar articles have appeared in the Indianapolis Star, on national news programs, and everywhere else in the nation.  (Like Maria, I have also heard news reports that at least some Atlanta business people have been disappointed that a hoped-for Olympic boom had not occurred.)  Todd noted that "[o]ne could argue that Atlanta is doing quite well, considering the scope and production of the Summer Games."  Todd then raised for our discussion the very questions that are being posed by every media outlet in the world.<p> 

I have no idea what the truth is.  But I think those who disagree with the media coverage would serve themselves better if they would spread more enlightenment  and cast fewer insults.  I am always skeptical of media coverage and would certainly appreciate hearing another side of the story.  But I am hardly persuaded to discount media reports by demands that we all just "shut up."  
<p>
Jim Clark

<P><HR><P>

Appended by: Richard North -- Nelson Mullins - Atlanta<BR> Date: Sun July 28 16:47:37 1996 <BR>Subject: Mea culpa! <p>

Though no excuse for the unnecessary hyperbole, nerves ARE frayed here!  (My office was evacuated for a bomb threat several hours ago).  Many of the points raised in the press are valid; there is no question that the shuttle transportation planning was inadequate and that IBM's computer system has been a dismal failure!  There is also no question that neither problem should have occurred.  On the other hand, those lapses -- which emanated from the organizing committee and IBM -- have little or nothing to do with how the city of Atlanta is doing.  Until early Saturday morning, the city itself was doing wonderfully.  Public transportation was working well (despite isolated reports to the contrary), people actually attending the games were having a wonderful time, and the streets have been one orderly and spirited party.  As numerous posts throughout CC suggest, the picture portrayed in the press is inconsistent with the experiences of the people in attendance.<p> 

I apologize for the tone and hyperbole, but not for the point.  The story of these games is NOT how the city of Atlanta is doing, or even how the organizing committee is doing.  Instead, the real story -- until Saturday a.m. -- has been the joyful Olympic experience in this city.  Now, however, the story is also of the terror wreaked by a madman.<p> 


<HR><P>

Appended by: James Clark -- Baker & Daniels - Indianapolis <BR> Date: Sun July 28 17:31:27 1996<BR> Subject: Mea Culpa <p>

Richard's gracious post causes me to chime in on his side.  (Who wants to pick on an Atlanta lawyer who's just been chased out of his office by a bomb scare?  Not me.)  His account seems consistent with all the interviews of spectators and participants that I've seen/heard.  For what it's worth, I don't credit the armchair quarterbacking going on in the media about security.  Based on everything I've heard, it sounds like security was extraordinary.  I don't see how the organizers could be expected to seal off every public space in Atlanta.  As long as we live in a free society, we will be vulnerable to the despicable psychos who do this.  I hope we do not overreact to the terrible tragedies of the Centennial Park bombing and the TWA disaster. 
<p>
Jim Clark<p>

<hr><p>  


Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 09:58:03 1996<br> 
Subject: Atlanta as the choice<p> 

Let us please save for another day any discussion of whether the terrorist bomb blast at Centennial Olympic Park necessarily makes Atlanta a poor choice for the Games. In the last year, I have been fortunate enough to be able to get to Jerusalem, Paris, New York and Los Angeles. Terrorism was felt in each of those cities even WHILE I was there. The fact that the Games are in Atlanta or Athens or Madrid or Detroit or Lake Placid does not necessarily make terrorism more or less likely there. Let us please remain sensitive to this tragedy and hold this delicate discussion until after the Games. Perhaps we can bring it up in the Sports Law forum after the Games are through and the evidence as to who and why this was done is released.<p> 

As for whether Atlanta was a poor choice to begin with, I think that it is natural to second guess the IOC and ask if Atlanta was the proper choice for the Games. But let us not lose sight of the fact that this is the sort of thing that we do EVERY Olympics.<p> 

Was Norway really the best choice for the Winter Games a few years ago considering that the snow and weather made travel to venues extremely difficult? Was Los Angeles the proper choice in '84 considering the heat, air quality and traffic?<p> 

Questions will always be asked of the choice of the Games site. It is not a personal attack on Atlanta and should not be taken that way. Atlanta and all of the south throughout Georgia and Florida have been very gracious and have generally run the Games well. Have there been computer glitches? Of course. Will there be more in the next week? Certainly. But it appears that there have been no more than in past Summer Games (remember that there are many more athletes in the Summer rather than Winter Games). Perhaps they are just more publicized.<p> 

Any other comments from anyone who has had the chance to attend any of the Games?<p> 

Ted Curtis<br>
Assistant Attorney, University of South Florida; Forum Co-Moderator<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 10:29:51 1996<br> 
Subject: Several Thoughts<p> 

Upon my return to Charlotte from a weekend at the games:<p> 

--This is a *huge* undertaking.  I can think of nothing comparable.  No one city has the resources to take this on alone.  Evidence of this included police barriers borrowed from New Orleans, and buses (and, I believe, drivers) borrowed from as far away as Long Beach, CA.  It is impossible to believe that all of the logistics involved could be handled flawlessly.  All appearances were that ACOG is doing about as well as anyone could reasonable expect.<p> 

--Atlantans are showing their legendary Southern hospitality.  Without exception, the volunteers, staffers and locals were friendly, helpful and knowledgeable.<p> 

--There can always be more security, but a certain amount of risk is inevitable.  Centennial Park is surrounded by public streets and parking areas which are filled with vendors and crowds.  If the bomber had not been able to enter the Park, he could have left the bomb in the House of Blues across the street.  My party parked in the Underground Atlanta garage on Saturday afternoon.  When we returned, we could not get to our vehicle.  The garage was closed because of a suspicious package at a retail store in Underground Atlanta.  It was a false alarm, but an example of how any downtown is vulnerable.<p> 

--The Turks who sadly lost one of their comrades to a heart attack complained that Atlanta was "too small" to host the games.  Isn't security more difficult in a situation like that at Los Angeles, where sites were sprawled over the region?<p> 

--Atlanta is getting a bad break, largely from our own (as noted earlier, NY and LA-based) media.  Surely past Olympics were not snag-free.  I have heard from someone who was involved in the Barcelona Olympics that their homeless were warehoused out of sight during the 1992 games.  Did Seoul have the "cultural sophistication" so missed by those who attended at Barcelona?<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Adam Shapiro -- GA Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 10:43:42 1996<br> 
Subject: Atlanta as the choice<p> 

Thanks, Ted.<p>

I was in Centennial Olympic Park the Saturday before last, Tuesday, Thursday and even Friday night at 11:30 p.m.  I've attended volleyball at the Omni and Basketball at the Dome, both next to the park.  My wife went to tennis at Stone Mountain, east of the city.<p>  

Samaranch reported yesterday that these are the most visited games by spectators and participants ever.   I've seen 31,000 (sellout) pack the half house Dome without a glitch.     80,000 saw track and field yesterday at Olympic stadium.  A friend reported a sellout and enthusiastic crowd at Lake Lanier yesterday for rowing.<p>   

I've driven downtown and parked for 5 dollars- no traffic getting down there at 9:00 a.m. No problem parking 5 blocks from the park. I've also taken the MARTA rail system during the peak time of 4:30 p.m. from the north line to Peachtree Center.  Sure it was as packed as physically possible, but still no one seemed annoyed from my vantage.<p> 

With each trip to the park, I saw increasingly large crowds. Not elbow to elbow, but still not suitable for say a baby carriage.   Everyone seemed to be enjoying themselves.<p>   

My wife tells me that the bathrooms at the tennis venue stopped working so they brought in port-o-potties.  Until 1:25 a.m. Saturday morning this is was the worst inconvenience I heard form anyone I talked with about how the games were going.<p> 

I recall that in Barcelona, you couldn't find a restroom and they had less people.<p> 

The biggest complaints I've heard are from local festivals and merchants saying that business is slow.  Seems no one did a good demographic study of who was coming.<p>   

My Man On the Street (and in the park) impression is visitors are mostly either young people in their 20s from around the globe or upper middle class families from the US.  The latter group are either only staying long enough to go to the events for which they have tickets and otherwise staying close to their hotel, or they are in town for an extended vacation and staying with friends or family.  Neither group has the interest to come to town to shop for anything other than Olympic stuff, let alone get in a car and drive to my or any other suburb (Roswell) for a festival.  The action is downtown.<p> 

I'll be at volleyball tomorrow.  They are re-opening the park for the first time at 9:30 a.m., though I haven't decided if I will go there.  That I have to even think twice is incredibly depressing.<p> 

Adam<p>

Adam J. Shapiro<br>
Executive Editor & Marketing Director<br>
Counsel Connect - Southern Region<br>
(800) 868-3884<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: William H. Schroder Jr -- Schroder Partners LC - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 10:50:53 1996<br> 
Subject: Whitewater!<p> 

Yes, Ted, but the waters weren't smooth there -- everything else was!  The Ocoee River event is the first time that whitewater slalom kayaking and canoeing competitions have been held on a natural river in the Olympics, and it is magnificent.  The athletes are praising it as the best that they have ever seen in competition anywhere.  And the crowds are loving it.<p> 

We drove to one of the many designated and widely separated parking lots, meeting no congestion whatsoever.  We stepped out of the car and immediately onto one of many buses, and it left right away, and quickly deposited us by the banks of the Ocoee.  The trip was much quicker and easier than ones I have taken previously for whitewater rafting on the Ocoee.  There were many lanes for the spectators, which resulted in short, quickly moving lines.  Security was evident everywhere (I even later found it on top of a dam 2 lakes upstream!).  Bags were politely and efficiently searched (and this was the day *before* the bombing).  The facilities were excellent:  more Port-A-Lets than you could shake a stick at, many vendors doing a bang-up business, bluegrass bands playing every 50 feet on the way in, "snowflake camouflage" strung over all of the public areas to keep out the direct sunlight, and bleachers right on the river bank with an absolutely perfect view of all of the action right down in front of you on the river.  It was a rip-roaring good time, including interaction between the competitors and what was reported to be the largest crowd ever to see a whitewater event in the world!  There were two public address announcers who obviously were former whitewater competitors, and their comments during the runs were excellent and guided us very well in our knowledge and appreciation of the sport and in what the competitors were facing, the strategies they were taking for the various course obstacles, and the degrees of success that they were achieving with each obstacle.<p>   

I admit that the bleachers got a little hard after almost 6 hours, so we left early wondering if we could find a bus to take us back to our parking lot.  There they were!  A quick hop on, a prompt departure, singing in various languages on the way back and much laughing, and we were dropped off right at our car, with the drive out being a breeze.<p> 

Now I ask you, what more could you have asked for?  It was a great experience, made so by an expert and most user-friendly organization and operation.  It was so smooooth!<p> 

Bill<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: John L. Cromartie -- Peachtree Rd United - Atlanta<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 11:57:35 1996<br> 
Subject: Attending events- Cent. Oly.<p> 

I've attended a number of events and have been very impressed with the logistics of moving huge numbers of people.  This is an incredible story which seems to be missed by much of the media but appreciated more and more by the people attending the games.<p> 


Moreover, as a Minister at a large Atlanta church, I've had a great deal of contact with visitors from around the world.  Their impressions have been most favorable, and this has been most apparent in those who have attending Olympics games in other cities.   This is a tremendous event which has not been error free but overall has been remarkable.  Sorry, got to get to another event!<p> 

<hr><p>

Appended by: Scot C Stirling -- Sacks Tierney, P.A. - Phoenix<br> 
Date: Mon July 29 16:57:48 1996<br> 
Subject: I Can't Help But Notice . . .<p> 

that, in the list of "problems" at the head of the list, only one of them was both related to organization of the events *and* amounted to anything of consequence -- that is the weight lifter who missed his event because a bus driver did not know his route.  Assuming the weight lifter didn't contribute to the problem by trying to arrive at the event only three minutes before his deadline for checking in, that really is unfortunate.<p> 

The case of kayaker who was injured in an accident is also very unfortunate, but I don't know why that should reflect on the organizers of the Games.  Some accidents are going to happen when you get so many people together in one city to participate in so many events.<p> 

But as for the other problems listed -- if a German diver appears on a scoreboard as a diver from Ghana, or a boxer is listed as 19 feet tall -- so what?  The Italians can't find a place to cook their own food?  Well, excuse me!  If they are staying in an athletes' dormitory, they're not supposed to be cooking in their rooms -- and if cooking their own food was important to them, they should have made other living arrangements.  As far as I'm concerned, that "problem" is not a problem.<p> 

I think the people who are reporting these "problems" really have to be stretching to make a point if these are the best evidence of inadequate preparation or planning on the part of the organizers or the city of Atlanta.<p> 

I spent many years living in foreign countries where nobody would even think of complaining about little glitches like these.  Anybody who thinks that it is possible to organize something as big as this and have it run without a single misstep is out of touch with reality.  I think the Games are going along very well.<p> 

Scot<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Evelyn Storch -- Tompkins McGuire - Newark<br> 
Date: Tue July 30 14:37:14 1996<br> 
Subject: Atlanta -- The Wrong Choice?<p> 

I just returned from the games yesterday and join in the chorus of attendees praising the games and their organization and operation. Have you noticed that the praise has been coming primarily from those who were there and the criticism principally from those who were not?  The media deserves the criticism, not the games.  Minor problems are to be expected when anything of this enormity is planned and executed--and minor problems are all that there have been.  Without the media digging up (creating?) the complaints, there would be few, indeed.  My husband "scolded" a TV camera crew riding a (very crowded, but nonetheless good humored and cooperative) train for their negative coverage.  They demonstrated a complete indifference  to his comments.<p> 
 
The joyous and wondrous atmosphere of the games pervades everything and serves to overcome the small inconveniences that arise.  The international camaraderie that is ever present makes the bombing an even greater tragedy--before the bombing, it didn't seem as if anything could dampen the spirits of those attending.  And notwithstanding the bombing--how can you stop someone hell-bent on destruction--the security was terrific.  We actually witnessed a purse-snatching, in which the perpetrator was immediately caught in a foot chase by 7-8 policemen, and a bag being searched a few minutes after it was left unattended in Olympic stadium by its owner, both before the bombing and the even tighter security.  Applause to the security forces and their organizers!<p> 
 
Hooray to Atlanta and to ACOG for a job well done and an experience those of us who were fortunate enough to share will never forget.<p>

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Beth Corvino -- General Instrument - Chicago<BR> Date: Wed Jul 31 17:58:28 1996 <BR>Subject: Chiming in. <BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
My eight year old daughter and I just returned this afternoon from four days in Atlanta.  We attended events; we wandered the streets during the day and at 1 and 2 in the morning after the gymnastics events ended; we shopped; we picnicked; we rode Marta; we drove downtown; we spent yesterday in the newly reopened Centennial Park. 
<BR><BR>
I think that Atlanta has done an incredible job organizing and putting on these Games.  The security is tremendous.  The transportation is fine, particularly considering that Atlanta is not a public transportation city.  The crowds are incredible, and while it is hot and difficult to wait in line, I thought they moved people through as efficiently as possible, and with good humor. 
<BR><BR>
Southern hospitality, indeed.  The volunteers were wonderful.  Even the security and law enforcement officials were warm and friendly while doing their jobs.   
<BR><BR>
I'm sure there were glitches.  So what.  It would be impossible to do this without some problems.  The fact is that I can't imagine any city doing a better job. 
<BR><BR>
I wish we could have stayed longer.
<BR><BR>
Three cheers for Atlanta!

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Ronald Chen -- Rutgers Law School - Newark <BR>Date: Wed Jul 31 22:43:34 1996<BR> Subject: Atlanta -- The Wrong Choice? <BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
I have just returned from Atlanta, where I was a jury member for the rowing competition at Lake Lanier.  On the whole, I think Atlanta did a very good job preparing the venues (I visited three or four, and seven different sports), but a lot of the good work was overshadowed by the transportation system for the athletes and the "Olympic family."  Unless you had a T1 credential (and thus were entitled to a private driver) the bus system (for us poor T4s) was a disaster.  The British women's coxed eight literally had to commandeer (they dislike th term hijack) a bus traveling to the field hockey venue and diverted it to the rowing venue by standing in the middle of the road until the bus stopped.  Busses scheduled for specific times showed up maybe 60% of the time.  Our drivers often got lost (so we had to direct them) and I heard that about 50 of them quit due to stress and inadequate training.  As usually happens when respources become scarce, people started engaging in side-deals and some entrepreneurship (including creative appropriation of ACOG vans and private cars).  Combined with the added security (expecially after the bomb) , it put a damper on proceedings. 
<BR><BR>
The other major glitch - with the computer results system - is quite an embarrassment for IBM.  The results system terminals at the venue was down for much of the rowing competition, which wasn't much of an inconvenience for us, but for the media in Atlanta at the MPC I am sure it was a problem. 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Eric Anderson -- Powell Goldstein - Atlanta<BR> Date: Thu Aug  1 14:58:49 1996 <BR>Subject: Atlanta - THE RIGHT CHOICE <BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
I commend to all of you Albert R. Hunt's column in today's Wall Street Journal (p. A15) for an unbiased, positive view of the Atlanta games from a member of the media here on vacation with his family.  "No matter what you may read or hear, and notwithstanding the trauma of last weekend's terrorism, the Atlanta Olympics have been terrific."   
<BR><BR>
As an Atlanta resident (and admittedly an unabashed Olympics lover), I think the IOC made absolutely the right choice.  You couldn't pick a city with more enthusiasm for the games.  Yes, there have been a few glitches in trying to get 11,000 athletes, 15,000 media members and millions of visitors to the venues, but those occur everywhere, and most certainly would have been just as bad or worse in Athens or anywhere else.  Considering the massive scale of this undertaking, Atlanta has been superb, and ACOG has shouldered its burden admirably. 

EWA


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles<BR> Date: Thu Aug  1 15:01:23 1996<BR> Subject: Atlanta <BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
In answer to Jay Barber's earlier response to my posting, which as a moderator of this seminar was intended to spark conversation (it did!) not post my opinion, I must say that Atlanta has done a wonderful job at hosting the Olympics.  The whole point about bringing up problems is to identify the problem so that the next host countries (Nagano and Sydney) can learn from these "glitches".  I agree that the media (as always) exaggerates the issues and always makes a drama out of everything.  My friends who are working in Atlanta for ACOG and the USOC say everything, on the whole, is going well.  And let's face it - as Gail Devers said, The OLYMPIC SPIRIT WILL PREVAIL!  It is the Olympics, after all, and what an honor it would be to be in Atlanta, as a fan or an athlete! 
<BR><BR>
-Maria Dennis, Co-Moderator



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte <BR>Date: Fri Aug  2 09:11:23 1996 <BR>Subject: Media 
<BR><BR>
I agree with Maria's post in all except the "as always" regarding the media approach.  Having grown up in the DC area, where "local" news is quite often really "national" news (or at least they treat it so), but having spent my career so far in smaller cities in the Midwest and the South, I perceive a definite tendency for the media from the coastal population centers to see most everyplace else as too small/unsophisticated to be taken seriously. 
<BR><BR>
The "as always" to me with the media is that, although they ostensibly operate as individuals, they tend to form a story line for major events into which the great majority tends to join.  The story line for L.A. was very "pro-American, look at how Peter Uberroth got this done," while the Barcelona line was "isn't this a charming, old, sophisticated city which is largely unknown to Americans."  I can't remember anything about the Seoul games (time difference problem, I guess). 
<BR><BR>
The story line for Atlanta (for all but NBC): the "Glitch Games." 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


