<blockquote>
<h2>Bromantan</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 

The Russian swimmer who won the bronze medal in 200-meter breaststroke,
and a Russian wrestler who also won a bronze have both been stripped of
their medals after testing positive for Bromantan.  A Lithuanian cyclist
who did not medal also tested positive.<p> 

What is Bromantan?  What does it do, and why is it banned?  Also, do
these athletes intend to appeal?<p> 

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York <BR>Date: Thu Aug  1
13:38:40 1996<BR> Subject: Appeals 
<BR><BR>
According to Prince Alexandre de Merode, chairman of the IOC medical
commission, bromantan is a "psychostimulant" and has the same properties
as amphetamines.  Merode claims that bromantan is manufactured by the
Russian army and has been used for years by athletes of the former
Soviet Union. 
<BR><BR>
The Russian Olympic committee has denied that bromantan is a stimulant
and has appealed the disqualifications of Andrei Korneyev (200-meter
breaststroke) and Zafar Gulyov (Greco-Roman wrestler).  Both athletes
were stripped of their bronze medals after testing positive for
bromantan.  A final verdict is expected today. 
<BR><BR>
The Russian delegation argues that the drug is not on the IOC's list of
banned substances.  Yet, Merode claims that the drug is covered under
the list of "related substances," thus disallowing its usage. 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston <BR>Date: Thu Aug 
1 15:26:39 1996 <BR>Subject: Bromantan 
<BR><BR>
I read in the paper that Bromantan can be used to "mask" other illegal
substances.  Does anyone know if that is true? 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>



Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte<BR> Date: Mon Aug  5 09:10:54 1996 <BR>Subject: Appeals 
<BR>
<P>According to radio reports, two Russians have won their appeal regarding their use of Bromantan, and will have their medals restored. </P>

