<blockquote>
<h2>Defining a sport in the Games</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>


What should define a sport in the Olympic Games? Is it a single
definition? Or is it an ever-changing definition? Is it any sport that
has to do with wartime activity (running, jumping, shooting, etc.) Does
stuff like beach volleyball and team handball belong in the Games?<p> 

What do you think?<p>

Ted Curtis<br>
Assistant Attorney, University of South Florida; Forum Co-Moderator 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles <BR>Date: Thu Aug  1
14:41:48 1996 <BR>Subject: Olympic Charter Definition <BR><BR>

Rule 52 of the Olympic Charter states that to be included as a sport in
the Olympic Games, the sport must conform with the following criteria: 
<BR><BR>
(1) only sports widely practised by men in at least 75 countries and on
4 continents, and by women in at least 40 countries and on 3 continents;

<BR><BR>
(2) only sports widely practised in at least 25 countries and on 3
continents may be included in the Winter Games; 
<BR><BR>
(3) sports are admitted to the programme of the Olympic Games at least 7
years before specific Olympic Games in respect of which no change shall
thereafter be permitted. 
<BR><BR>
In addition, to be included in the programme of the Olympic Games the
sport must not depend essentially on mechanical propulsion.  Of course,
the Charter also states that the IOC can make exceptions. Does anyone
else think that these criteria do not give us much guidance on what is
an Olympic sport?  Ballroom dancing is going to be an Olympic sport in
Sydney, I believe, which sabotages Ted's theory of war-related
activities (of course, an argument can be made that ballroom dancing was
practiced during wartime to relieve soldiers' stress!).  I really do not
have a clue as to how the IOC decides on what sports are "Olympic". 
Based on Rule 52, it seems that popularity is a huge factor! -Maria
Dennis, Co-Moderator 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Jay Levine -- Winston & Strawn - Washington<BR> Date: Thu Aug 
1 16:20:04 1996 <BR>Subject: Whatever is hip 
<BR><BR>
Ballroom dancing aside, I believe Maria is right.  Popularity is quite
obviously a huge factor in the IOC's decision as to what may be included
in the Games as a "sport."  (The IOC regs define when a sport may be
included in the Olympics but do not define what is "sport")  This merely
continues the Olympic tradition of commercializing itself, discussed in
another thread.  If these "sports" are popular among recreational
"athletes," these people will more likely watch and attend more of the
Olympics and buy more Olympic merchandising.   
<BR><BR>
The more relevant question may be this:  If this is what people really
want to see, then is the trend a BAD thing?  It can be argued that the
IOC is merely giving what the consuming public demands. 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


Appended by: Suzanne Schiller -- Pepper Hamilton & Scheetz -
Philadelphia<BR> Date: Thu Aug  1 17:40:59 1996<BR> Subject: Is It A Bad Thing? 
<BR><BR>
I think including "recreational" and even professional (e.g. tennis,
baseball, basketball) sports benefits only two groups:  (1) the host
city/relevant Olympic organizing entities who share in the proceeds of
the ticket sales; and (2) the new sport participants who can claim to be
"Olympians."  On the other hand, I think it seriously devalues the value
of winning and the games as a whole.  On balance, I think we should
stick with some basic sports that epitomize the various aspects (e.g.
speed, strength, agility) of athletics.      
<BR><BR>
This is not to say, of course, that rhythm gymnasts or synchronized
swimmers do not necessarily display the same level of athletic ability
as sprinters or rowers; in fact, if an Olympic sport can be defined as
that which requires speed, strength, agility and grace, ballroom dancing
should be considered the perfect Olympic sport.  But just because a
"sport" exists or is a "crowd-pleaser" like beach volleyball doesn't
mean it should be included in the Olympic line-up.  Sure, it may be
arbitrary that a shot putter gets a chance at an Olympic medal while a
bocce player doesn't (bocce isn't an Olympic sport yet, is it?), but I
think a line needs to be drawn somewhere. 
<BR><BR>
And I think similar lines should be drawn within each sport.  For
example, what is the point of having 2-man, 4-man & 8-man rowing crews? 
Yes, technique, strategy and equipment are different, but it is all
rowing.  And why aren't the gymnastics individual all around and
apparatus medals based on the same routines?   For that matter, why
can't they be based on the routines done during the team competition? 
Finally, do we really need all these races at every conceivable distance
(100 m, 200 m, 400 m, etc.)   Pick one distance for sprinters, one for
middle-distance runners, and one for marathoners/cross-country runners. 
 
<BR><BR>
---Shosh

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


Appended by: Barry D. Bayer -- Law Office Tech Rev - Homewood <BR>Date: Sat Aug  3 23:18:48 1996 <BR>Subject: Defining a sport in the Games 
<BR><BR>
gee shosh...you want to take all the fun away. 
<BR><BR>
but hey...why rhythm gymnatics and not ballet? 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: James Clark -- Baker & Daniels - Indianapolis <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 10:38:07 1996 <BR>Subject: Defining a sport in the Games 
<BR><BR>
It's not a sport if your choice of music is relevant. 
<BR><BR>
Jim Clark


