<h2>Ethnocentrism</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 


From: Eleanor Kerlow -- DC Counsel Connect - Wash<BR>
Date: Wed Jul 31 11:39:30 1996<BR>
Subject: Ethnocentrism
<BR>



Last Append: Fri Aug  2 11:33:59 1996<BR><BR>

Do you think NBC is alienating large segments of the viewing audience,
namely immigrants and foreign residents, by focusing so heavily on the
US led events and atheletes? NBC is apparently receiving many complaints
about this. Frank DeFord said on NPR this morning that all coverage is
skewed: Italy focuses on its athletes and Japan its favorites etc.  
<BR><BR>
For instance, during the men's team gymnastics competition when Russia 
and China were neck and neck, and NBC remained rivetted on the U.S.
team, which was posting fourth or fifth place. Viewers were robbed of
the tense competition and higher caliber gymnastics of these other
teams. 
<BR><BR>
Perhaps there should be two broadcasts, one very US oriented, with
sports that are popular in the U.S., such as swimming, gymnastics,
track, and weight lifting, and one that has more of an international
flare, focusing on the best athletes (even if they are from another
country) and highlighting sports that may be very popular throughout the
world, though not in the U.S., such as the equestrian events, rowing,
and fencing. We live in a global world and there are many
underappreciated sports in the Olympics. 
<BR><BR>
What do you think? 
<BR><BR>
Elli

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: David Baker -- Arnzen Parry Wentz - Covington<BR> Date: Thu Aug 
 1 11:18:31 1996 <BR>Subject: Ethnocentrism <BR><BR>

Sure, the coverage is skewed toward U.S. athletes.  However, that does
not mean that the *best* athletes are being ignored if they come from
another country:  look at the coverage of -- and overall American
fascination with -- the weightlifter known as "Pocket Hercules."  Or the
Ethiopian woman who took the gold medal in the marathon.  I'm sure there
are many other examples as well. 
<BR><BR>
It seems to me that when U.S. athletes are in medal contention, they get
a lot of media attention.  When the Americans are not in contention,
other athletes get the attention.  Any why not?  Has political
correctness / diversity gotten to the point that we chastise ourselves
for being interested in our own athletes? 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Susan Nogan -- CC Law Editor - Washington <BR>Date: Thu Aug  1 
11:56:27 1996 <BR>Subject: An example <BR><BR>

The men's cycling road race.  There were twelve men in the breakaway,
but NBC mentioned only Americans Lance Armstrong and Frankie Andreou. 
I'd have been interested in knowing who else was there. 
<BR><BR>
At least Phil Liggett was providing commentary, and was able to point
out Miguel Indurain, the greatest cyclist ever, and Bjore Riis, winner
of the grueling Tour de France only weeks ago.   



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: David George -- Chambers of Judge - Houston <BR>Date: Thu Aug  
1 12:06:24 1996<BR> Subject: Ethnocentrism <BR><BR>

I've seen a good bit of coverage of other athletes.  In the heavyweight
weightlifting the other night a long story was done on the Russian who
won.  They did a piece following him to Moscow for a drug test & seeing
him at home with his pregnant wife.  A very positive piece.  And this is
an event that had a big American in it (Mark Henry).  In the actual
competition, there was lots of attention given to the Russian & the
other guy (I forget where he was from) battling it out for gold. 
<BR><BR>
Sure the Americans are featured more, but there seems to be coverage of
other athletes (even if it's not totally balanced). 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Mary Zwick -- The Chemical Co. - Midland <BR>Date: Thu Aug  1 
14:49:10 1996 <BR>Subject: Ethnocentrism <BR><BR>

Since I live in Michigan, I am lucky enough to have two viewing options:
 NBC, of course, and CBC (out of Windsor).  I absolutely agree that the
US coverage is extremely biased toward US athletes. I see sports on the
Canadian coverage of the Games which is either relegated to the nether
regions of late night on NBC or ignored altogether.  In addition, the
CBC coverage stays focused on the battles for the medals, not on
Canadian athletes, wherever they happen to be.    It certainly provides
a different perspective, and helps to show that "amateurism" is still
alive in the Olympics. 




<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Susan Nogan -- CC Law Editor - Washington<BR> Date: Fri Aug  2  
11:33:59 1996<BR> Subject: Ethnocentrism 
<BR><BR>
Mary, any idea of how the CBC coverage is doing in the ratings?  
Anything to counter NBC's defense that "we know this is what the people 
want to see because look how many watch." 
<BR><BR>
<hr><BR><BR>


Appended by: Mary Zwick -- The Chemical Co. - Midland <BR>Date: Fri Aug  2 15:55:54 1996 <BR>Subject: Ethnocentrism 
<BR><BR>
I'm not sure how CBC is doing in Canada.  I imagine they're doing pertty well there since, like NBC in the States, they're the only Canadian network broadcasting the Games.  Anecdotally, I know that everyone I know (friends, family, etc.) who has a choice is watching CBC. 

<BR><BR>
