<h2>Basics of International Law</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p> 


From: Christian Krahe -- Faupel, Krahe - Ueberlin<BR>
Date: Thu Aug  1 11:15:31 1996<BR>
Subject: Basics of International Law<BR><BR>



After having followed the discussion in this seminar, I have got the
impression that many problems are caused by the deficiency of a basic
sports law which is wordwidely accepted. Of course, as far as the
Olympic Games are concerned, there are the Olympic Charta and several
regulations to organize the competitions. However, athletes of 197
different countries participate in these Games  and each of these
countries has its own legal system which often does not harmonize with
the sports law at the place of the event. Summer Opympic Games in
Atlanta und Winter Olympic Games in Nagano happen in completely
different legal surroundings and traditions although it is evident that
the principles of Olympic law should be identical wherever the Games
take place. According to the common European legal opinion, Olympic law
is nothing else than general contractual conditions of a private
association (IOC) based on  private Swiss law. But with regard to the
international importance of IOC, Olympic law is much more similar to
public international law (ius gentium) than to national private law. In
order to secure the worldwide validity of Olympic law and its uniform
interpretation, we should agree on an own legal category of
international sports law covering the fundamental rights of sportsmen
and the legal status of the international federations. 
<BR><BR>
What do you think about this in USA?
<BR><BR>
Christian Krahe, Attorney- at - law, Konstanz / Germany 

<BR><BR>
<hr><BR><BR>

Appended by: Aaron N. Wise -- Klepner & Cayea, LLP - New York <BR>Date: Fri Aug  2 14:53:09 1996<BR> Subject: Basics of International Law 
<BR><BR>
In reply to the August l remarks of my German colleague, Christian Kraehe, I am very skeptical about creating or recognizing an international sports law covering the fundamental rights of athletes, the legal status of international federations and similar matters. Reasons for my skepticism: l. National courts of law might thereby be (further) restricted from taking jurisdiction over and deciding disputes involving athletes' rights and their violation, and other matters where the rights of a person or entity is pitted against the establishment. For example, breakaway or new federations etc. Countries like the USA and Germany, and their courts, offer strong protection to personal and private rights, and others do not or not to the same degree. I do not wish to see that weakened, and in fact, would like to see it strengthened. 2. I am not sure I want to see a special,  "international law status" conferred upon or recognized to international (or national) sports federations. Reasons: similar to l. above. 3. I doubt very much that nations could agree on a common international sports law covering the fundamental rights of athletes and legal status of international federations and the like. Moreover, if agreement were reached, the result might be even more sports litigation. Perhaps my skepticism could be overcome after seeing specific proposals for such common "international sports law". Aaron N. Wise Klepner & Cayea, LLP New York City 

<BR><BR>
<hr><BR><BR>

