<blockquote>
<h2>Housing complaints</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5
09:04:27 1996<BR> Subject: Housing complaints



<BR><BR>
Pulled this off of Hot Docs this morning.
<BR><BR>
 Ted

COMMERCIAL LAW AND CONTRACTS

[Editor's Note: TV Globo, a Brazilian television network sued the
proprietor of The Corporate Key, which allegedly offered to arrange
housing for more than fifty TV Globo employees, as well as rental cars,
mobile phones, food service, office and secretarial services, and other
amenities, during the period of the Atlanta Olympic Games. According to
the complaint, services were provided incompletely and chaotically while
additional invoices were still submitted and paid for services which
were not provided. TV Globo charges common law fraud, breach of
contract, and state RICO violations.]


<PRE>
<B>IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF FULTON COUNTY STATE OF GEORGIA


TV GLOBO LTDA.,

Plaintiff,

vs.

MEGGEN M. MILLS, THE ATLANTA CORPORATE KEY COMPANY, and THE CORPORATE
KEY COMPANY,

Defendant.</B>


CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. - E49897


COMPLAINT AND APPLICATION FOR EQUITABLE RELIEF

Comes now TV GLOBO Ltda. ("TV Globo"), plaintiff in the above-styled
civil action and hereby respectfully shows this Honorable Court as
follows:


PARTIES

1.

Plaintiff TV Globo Ltda. is a corporation organized and existing under
the laws of the Federative Republic of Brazil. TV Globo is a Brazilian
television network covering the Centennial Olympic Games in Atlanta,
Georgia.

2.

Defendant Meggen M. Mills is a resident of Dallas, Texas, currently
temporarily residing in Atlanta, Fulton County, Georgia, and doing
business in Fulton County, at an office located at 199 Fourteenth
Street, Suite 1904, Atlanta, Georgia, 30309. Defendant Meggen M. Mills
is subject to the jurisdiction and venue of this Court.

3.

Defendant The Atlanta Corporate Key Company is a Georgia corporation,
incorporated June 5, 1995, currently not in good standing with the
Georgia Secretary of State. The registered agent for service and
registered office of The Atlanta Corporate Key Company is Meggen M.
Mills' 199 Fourteenth Street, Suite 1904, Atlanta, Georgia 30309.
Defendant The Atlanta Corporate Key Company is subject to the
jurisdiction and venue of this Court.

4.

Defendant The Corporate Key Company is a Texas corporation, incorporated
June 5, 1995, with offices at 5801 Presson Oaks Road, Suite 112, Dallas,
Texas 75240 and 4200 South Hulen Street, Ft. Worth, Texas. The agent for
service of process for The Corporate Key Company is Meggen M. Mills.
Defendant The Corporate Key Company is subject to the jurisdiction and
venue of this Court by reason of the allegations hereinafter set forth.


FACTUAL STATEMENT

5.

Commencing in December 1994, Plaintiff TV Globo began dealing with
Defendant Meggen M. Mills and a business she called "The Corporate Key",
then located in Dallas, Texas, concerning accommodations for its
employees in Atlanta for the Centennial Olympic Games. At that time, TV
Globo, a television network in Brazil, was making arrangements for
coverage of the 1996 Games. The Defendant Meggen M. Mills, doing
business as The Corporate Key, held herself out as capable of providing
a wide array of services to TV Globo.

6.

TV Globo indicated at that time that it would need approximately fifty
(50) apartments, condominiums or hotel suites to house network employees
for varying lengths of time during and around the Olympic Games, and
Defendant Mills confirmed that she could provide such accommodations.
Additionally, Defendant Mills claimed that she could also provide rental
cars, mobile phones, food service, office and secretarial services,
concierge services, shuttle services and other amenities and
necessities. Defendant Mills promised in December 1994 to provide
specific options and prices in the near future.

7.

In the Spring of 1995, Defendant Mills, still working through the
business known as "The Corporate Key" in Dallas, Texas, identified a
number of premier Atlanta properties which she claimed were available
for rental by TV Globo, and she provided price ranges for each. In March
1995, Michele Naili, Executive Producer of the Sports Division of TV
Globo, traveled to Atlanta and met with Defendant Mills. Defendant Mills
took Ms. Naili on a tour of the various available properties, and
confirmed her previous assertions that she could provide housing of
plaintiff's choice, rental cars, mobile phones and other amenities.
Defendant Mills also provided up-dated prices for each accommodation. On
May 23, 1995, Michele Naili of TV Globo communicated by facsimile to
Defendant Mills that TV Globo would need eight (8) condominium units at
"The Grand", and ten ( 10) one-bedroom and forty (40) two-bedroom
apartments at the properties known as "The Parc Vue" and "Mayfair". Ms.
Naili also confirmed that she would get back to Defendant Mills shortly
with TV Globo's rental car needs. This communication is attached hereto
as Exhibit "A".

8.

At or about the same time, Defendant Mills sent by facsimile
transmission a "Letter of Confirmation" and "Security Deposit Statement"
attached hereto as Exhibit "B." The Letter of Confirmation states that a
reservation was being made on behalf of TV Globo for ten (10)
one-bedroom and forty (40) two-bedroom apartments at the Parc Vue or
Mayfair, and six (6) one-bedroom and two (2) two-bedroom condominiums at
The Grand. Defendant Mills's communication requested Security Deposits
for those apartments.

9.

In June 1995, TV Globo began payment of invoices to Defendant Mills and
her companies which ultimately totaled $490,398.92. On June 2, 1995, TV
Globo wired the amount of $49,290.00 to Defendant Mills via her Dallas
bank account for "Security Deposits" on the requested apartments.
Attached as Exhibit "C" hereto is Defendant Mills's June 5, 1995 "Letter
of Confirmation" specifying the number, types and specific locations of
the apartments reserved, along with her "Security Deposit Statement
Payment Receipt" acknowledging receipt of $49,290.00 as security
deposits for the specified apartments. Defendant Mills again confirmed
receipt of the security deposit in her communication of June 14, 1995,
attached as Exhibit "D", and promised Lease Agreement Forms within ten
(10) days.

10.

Representatives of TV Globo met with Defendant Mills in Atlanta twice
more following payment of the security deposits, at which time Defendant
Mills showed the representatives the properties where she had allegedly
reserved units for TV Globo with the funds paid to her and her companies
by TV Globo, and she provided options for rental cars and mobile phones
at that time.

11.

On June 5, 1995, Defendant Mills incorporated The Atlanta Corporate Key
Company, a Georgia corporation, and simultaneously incorporated The
Corporate Key Company, a Texas corporation, with herself as
incorporator, CEO, CFO and Secretary.

12.

On March 1, 1996, Defendant Mills, now operating through The Atlanta
Corporate Key Company from an office on Fourteenth Street in Atlanta,
Georgia, submitted three invoices to TV Globo;


A. Invoice #I-TVG/Rental, in the amount of $27,216.50 for the rental of
1 one- bedroom apartment and 2 two bedroom apartments for the period of
time between June 24, 1996 to August 11, 1996;

B. Invoice #II-TVG/Rental, in the amount of $91,866.50 for the rental of
10 two-bedroom apartments for the period of time between June 30, 1996
through August 11, 1996;

and

C. Invoice #III-TVG/Rental, for the rental of 9 one-bedroom and 28
two-bedroom apartments for the period July 7, 1996 through August 6,
1996. See Exhibits "E", "F" and "G" attached.


Those invoices were paid in full in the amount of $326,129.50 by wire
transfer to the Defendants' Texas corporation's bank account upon the
instructions of Mills contained in the foregoing Exhibits.

13.

Representatives of TV Globo arrived in Atlanta on or about June 24,
1996, and Defendants provided the 1 one-bedroom apartment and 2
two-bedroom apartments that had been paid for.

14.

More employees of TV Globo arrived on June 29, 1996, but on June 30th,
the Defendants could not provide the 10 two-bedroom apartments already
paid for and promised. After some chaos, the Defendants provided some
units to Plaintiff.

15.

In the meantime, at a time when Defendant Mills knew that she had not
properly applied the funds previously paid to her by TV Globo, and that
she did not have an adequate number of apartments rented to house the TV
Globo employees who were continuously arriving in Atlanta, Defendant The
Atlanta Corporate Key Company billed $62,010.00 to TV Globo for an
additional 10 premium apartment homes, along with $8,700.00 as a
"refundable mobile phone deposit". See Exhibit "H".

16.

On June 25, 1996, TV Globo paid Defendant The Atlanta Corporate Key
Company $70,180.00 by the check drawn on NationsBank attached hereto as
Exhibit "I", but Defendants co-mingled or converted those funds and
failed to apply them to the apartments and mobile phones as promised.

17.

Additional employees of TV Globo were arriving in Atlanta continuously,
but the Defendants failed to provide the apartments that the Defendants
had allegedly paid for in full and for which Defendants had been paid in
full by TV Globo. Numerous other individuals employed by other clients
of the Defendants arrived in Atlanta and found that their allegedly
prepaid apartments had never been reserved. Defendants, apparently
having commingled, converted or wasted the funds that had been given to
them to reserve and prepay for accommodations, needed additional monies
to replace the converted funds.

18.

On June 28, 1996, the Defendants billed TV Globo an additional
$44,799.92: $25,000.00 was allegedly for "Ancillary Service Deposit
Fully Refundable"; $11,269.92 was for "prepaid rental of 29 mobile
telephones", and; $8,000.00 was for "deposit" on 16 4-door mid-size
vehicles. Plaintiff paid said invoice by check on June 28, 1996. Upon
information and belief, Defendants then converted those funds to attempt
to secure apartments they had previously been paid for. See Exhibits "J"
and "K".

19.

Employees of TV Globo continued to arrive in Atlanta with no place to
stay. Representatives of TV Globo held numerous meetings with Defendant
Mills wherein she claimed that the apartments had all been properly
reserved and fully paid for, but she claimed that she was having
difficulty with furniture deliveries and other technicalities. Defendant
Mills stated that she had properly applied all funds and that all
prepaid apartments and services would be available shortly.

20.

Then, on July 8, 1996, Defendant Mills informed TV Globo by the letter
attached hereto as Exhibit "L", that "The Atlanta Corporate Key will not
be able to provide additional apartment homes for Rede Globo from this
date forward", and promised to refund any money owed. No such refund has
been made.

21.

TV Globo had paid the Defendants a total of $490,398.92. TV Globo had
contracted for, and fully paid for, 60 specific apartments at identified
locations. The Defendants provided only 24 apartments, and many of them
were inferior, one-bedroom units not equating to the comparable
apartments paid for.

22.

Additionally, even though TV Globo had fully paid for mobile phone
service for 29 phones, and had prepaid for 16 automobiles, the
Defendants had also misapplied those funds. Within days, mobile phones
were turned off, and the rental companies were calling back the
automobiles.

23.

With the Olympic Games about to begin and much work to be done, the
executives of TV Globo were forced to find alternative accommodations
for over 45 employees who had no where to stay. Also, arrangements had
to be made to restore critical mobile phone service and rental car
availability.

24.

As a result of Defendants' wrongful actions, TV Globo was forced to
enter into a lease with an unrelated condominium complex at a cost of
over $460,000.00. As a result of the wrongful actions of defendants, TV
Globo was forced to spend an additional $43,711.13 for cellular phone
deposits and service after having already fully paid Defendants to
provide such equipment and service. TV Globo will also be required to
spend additional amounts for rental vehicles in amounts not yet known.

25.

TV Globo paid to Defendants over $490,000.00 for specific accommodations
and services. The funds were not used for the specific purposes for
which they were paid. Upon information and belief, Defendants have
converted for their own personal use a substantial portion of
Plaintiff's $490,000.00.

26.

Plaintiff continues to incur and suffer irreparable harm as Defendants
continue spending, dissipating and concealing the misappropriated funds
belonging to Plaintiff.

27.

Defendants used the United States mail, telephones, telecopiers,
facsimile machines and bank wire transfers, and other instrumentalities
of interstate commerce in furtherance of their fraudulent and illegal
scheme. Such acts constitute violations of 18 U.S.C. Sections 1341, 1343
and other criminal code sections.

28.

The actions herein set forth by Defendants constitute "racketeering
activity" within the meaning of the Georgia RICO statutes.

29.

In furtherance of their fraudulent and unlawful scheme, Defendants
conducted similar transactions with other parties using the same
fraudulent promises, confirmations and commitments to defraud such
parties, including the Los Angeles Times, TV Azetca, TV Bandeirantes and
other organizations and entities.

30.

The foregoing constitutes an "enterprise", a "pattern of racketeering
activity" and prohibited activities within the meaning of the Georgia
RICO statutes.


COUNT I. Common Law Fraud

31.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 30 above set forth.

32.

Defendants, and each of them, defrauded Plaintiff in numerous ways:


A. Defendants contracted with Plaintiff to provide specific
accommodations and services, and billed Plaintiff for security deposits,
rental fees and other charges for specific apartments, rental homes,
mobile phones and services. Plaintiff paid Defendants in full for the
specific accommodations and services for which it contracted and was
billed. Rather than utilizing Plaintiff's funds for the stated purpose,
Defendants converted, commingled, dissipated, misappropriated, concealed
and diverted Plaintiff's money. Defendants then knowingly, with the
intent to deceive, confirmed to Plaintiff that its funds had been
properly utilized as security deposits and rental fees on specific
apartments, rental cars and mobile phones;

B. Knowing that Plaintiff's funds had been misappropriated and
misapplied, Defendants continued to knowingly misrepresent and deceive
Plaintiff by repeatedly confirming, both orally and in writing, that
specific accommodations and services had been reserved for Plaintiff's
employees in Atlanta for the Centennial Olympic Games;

C. As the employees began arriving in Atlanta to cover the Olympic
Games, Defendants billed the Plaintiff $70,180.00 on June 25th and
$44,799.92 on June 28th, allegedly for rental car deposits, mobile phone
rentals, "ancillary service deposit fully refundable" and for other
services, but at the time those amounts were billed and collected by
Defendants from Plaintiff, Defendants had a present intention to
misappropriate and misapply those funds, and did, in fact, convert,
commingle, misapply and dissipate those monies, and;

D. As the final phase of Defendants' preplanned and calculated
fraudulent scheme, Defendants waited until they assumed that Plaintiff
must have made alternative accommodations for its numerous employees who
had arrived and others who were set to arrive in the Atlanta area, and
then Defendants contacted Plaintiff again claiming that they could now
provide the accommodations for which Plaintiff had already paid
Defendants. Defendants' statements were knowingly false and fraudulent.
Defendants had no apartments or accommodations for Plaintiff's employees
because they had misappropriated the funds needed to pay the apartment
complexes.. Defendants' statements were made with the intent to create
the illusion that Defendants could preform their obligations under their
contract with Plaintiff. As late as June 11th, Defendant Mills claimed
that she had accommodations for Plaintiff's employees, but investigation
revealed that allegation to be totally false.


33.

Defendants' misrepresentations and lies were made with the purpose and
intent of defrauding and deceiving Plaintiff. Plaintiffjustifiably
relied on such misrepresentation and lies, and sustained substantial
damages as a result thereof.

34.

Plaintiff is entitled to recover of Defendants, jointly and severally,
compensatory damages well in excess of One Million Dollars
($1,000,000.00), plus interest to the date of judgment and attorneys'
fees and expenses of litigation.

35.

Plaintiff is also entitled to an award of punitive damages to be
assessed against Defendants, jointly and severally, pursuant to OCGA
Section 51-12-5.1 in that Defendants' actions showed willful misconduct,
malice, fraud, wantonness, oppression, or that entire want of care which
would raise the presumption of conscious indifference to consequence.


COUNT II. Conspiracy To Defraud

36.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 30, and paragraphs 31 through 35
above.

37.

Defendants, and each of them, engaged in a conspiracy to defraud
Plaintiff and committed acts in furtherance of such conspiracy,
including the acts set forth above.

38.

As a proximate result of Defendants' conspiracy to defraud, Plaintiff
has been damaged in an amount in excess of One Million Dollars
($1,000,000.00) plus interest to the date of judgment, attorneys' fees
and expenses of litigation..

39.

Plaintiff is also entitled to an award of punitive damages to be
assessed against Defendants, jointly and severally, pursuant to OCGA
Section 51-12-5.1, in that Defendants' actions showed willful
misconduct, malice, fraud, wantonness, oppression, or that entire want
of care which would raise the presumption of conscious indifference to
the consequences.


COUNT III. Constructive Trust

40.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in - paragraphs I-39 above set forth.

41.

Plaintiff remains the owner of the funds misappropriated by Defendants
and Defendants hold such funds wherever they may be traced and located,
and any properties, real or personal, purchased therewith as
constructive trustees of Plaintiff.

42.

Plaintiff is entitled to have a constructive trust and equitable lien
impressed upon the misappropriated funds, wherever they may be traced
and located, and on any and all properties purchased in whole or in part
with such funds.


COUNT IV Equitable Accounting

43.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 42 set forth above.

44.

Plaintiff is entitled to an equitable accounting pursuant to OCGA
Section 23-2-70, in order to account for all the misappropriated funds,
wherever they may be traced or located, and to account for all such
properties, real or personal, purchased with such funds.

45.

Plaintiff has no adequate remedy at law because without such an
accounting, Plaintiff will not be able adequately to trace, locate and
recover all misappropriated funds and other monies to Plaintiff.


COUNT V. Appointment Of A Receiver

46.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 42 set forth above.

47.

Pursuant to the Georgia Civil Practice Act, the common law of Georgia,
and OCGA Sections 9-8-1, 9-8-2 and 9-8-3, Plaintiff is entitled to have
a Receiver appointed to take possession of, preserve and protect the
misappropriated funds, wherever they maybe traced and located, and any
properties or other assets purchased with such funds.

48.

Without the appointment of a Receiver, Plaintiff's rights in such funds
and property cannot be fully protected, and the misappropriated funds
and properties or other assets purchased with such funds are in danger
of being secreted and divested by Defendants.


COUNT VI Common Law Conversion

49.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 30 above set forth.

50.

The Defendants, and each of them, have wrongfully appropriated,
embezzled and converted Plaintiff's funds to their personal use and
gain.

51.

Defendants have no right, title or interest in Plaintiff's funds
misappropriated as set forth above.

52.

Plaintiff is entitled to recover such misappropriated and converted
funds, from each and every Defendant/Co-conspirator, jointly and
severally.

53.

Plaintiff is also entitled to an award of punitive damages to be
assessed against Defendants, jointly and severally, pursuant to OCGA
Section 51-12-5. 1 in that Defendants' actions showed willful
misconduct, malice, fraud, wantonness, oppression, or that entire want
of care which would raise the presumption of conscious indifference to
consequences.


COUNT VII Breach Of Contract

54.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 30 above set forth.

55.

Plaintiff is entitled to compensatory and consequential damages
forseeably incurred as a result of Defendants' breach of contract, plus
interest, attorneys' fees and expenses of litigation.


COUNT VIII. Georgia RICO

56.

Plaintiff realleges and incorporates herein by reference the allegations
contained in paragraphs 1 through 30 above set forth.

57.

The association of the Defendants herein is a "enterprise" within the
meaning of OCGA Section 16-14-3. This enterprise was and is an ongoing
activity which has continued for over eighteen (18) months.

58.

During the relevant period, the Defendants have, in violation of OCGA
Section 16-14-4, conducted and participated in the conduct of the
affairs of this enterprise through a pattern of racketeering activity
within the meaning of OCGA Section 16-14-3. Defendants devised the above
described scheme to defraud Plaintiff and others of substantial sums of
money as above set forth.

59.

In furtherance of the scheme to defraud, Defendants have committed
multiple indictable offenses constituting mail fraud and wire fraud
under 18 U.S.C. Sections 13-41 and 13-43, as set forth above in
paragraphs 1 through 32, which allegations are incorporated herein by
reference.

60.

Defendants have also committed numerous thefts by deception within the
meaning of OCGA Section 16-8-3, including, (a) by promising to perform
certain services when Defendants never intended to perform such services
or knew that such services would not be performed, and, ultimately, by
keeping Plaintiff's funds for their own use and benefit; (b) by
obtaining funds from Plaintiff by deceitful means or artful practice
with the intention of depriving it of its funds, (c) by creating or
confirming Plaintiff's impressions that specific accommodations and
services had been reserved and paid for on Plaintiff's behalf, which
existing facts were false and which Defendants knew or believed were
false, and (d) by billing Plaintiff on June 25th and June 28th for
assorted services and allegedly refundable deposits with the intention
of misappropriating and misapplying those funds to other uses.

61.

Defendants engaged in the conduct above set forth with the specific
intent of defrauding Plaintiff and in furtherance of their unlawful
schemes. Defendants participated in and conducted the affairs of the
enterprise through a pattern of racketeering activity by committing
multiple incidents of racketeering activity having the same or similar
intents, results, accomplices, methods of commission, and the same
victim, which incidents are not isolated, all in violation of OCGA
Section 16-14-4. Plaintiff has been injured by reason of Defendants'
pattern of racketeering activity and other fraudulent offences, in an
amount to be proved at trial, but expected to be in excess of One
Million Dollars ($1,000,000.00). Plaintiff is entitled to recover three
times its actual damages sustained, plus punitive damages, attorneys'
fees and reasonable costs of investigation and litigation, all as
provided by OCGA Section 16-14-6.

62.

Plaintiff is also entitled to injunctive relief, including a Temporary
Restraining Order and Preliminary Injunction, as provided in OCGA
Section 16-14-6.


Prayer For Relief

WHEREFORE, Plaintiff prays for the following relief:

A. Under Counts I, II, VI, and VII of the Complaint, that Judgment be
entered in favor of Plaintiff and against all Defendants, jointly and
severally in an amount in excess of One Million Dollars ($ 1,000,000.00)
which will be proved with specificity at the trial of this action, plus
interest and all costs, including reasonable attorney's fees and
expenses of litigation;

B. Under Counts I, II, VI, and VIII of the Complaint, that Plaintiff be
awarded Punitive Damages to be assessed against Defendants, jointly and
severally, pursuant to OCGA Section 5112-5.1, in the sum of Ten Million
Dollars ($ 10,000,000.00), or in an amount to be determined by the
enlightened conscience of the jury as the amount necessary both to
punish Defendants and to deter them from engaging in future such
wrongful acts;

C. Under Count III of the Complaint, that a constructive trust and
equitable lien be impressed in favor of Plaintiff on all funds
misappropriated from Plaintiff, wherever such funds may be traced and
located, and on all properties, both personal and real and all other
assets purchased with such funds;

D. Under Count VIII of the Complaint, that Judgment be entered in favor
of Plaintiff against all Defendants, jointly and severally, in an amount
equal to three-fold the damages and losses sustained by Plaintiff plus
costs and reasonable attorney's fees, pursuant to the Georgia Rico
Statute;

E. Under Count IV of the Complaint, that this Court enter an Order
directing Defendants to provide an equitable accounting of all
misappropriated funds, wherever they may be traced or located, and to
account for all properties or other assets purchased with such funds;

F. Under Count V of the Complaint, that this Court enter an Order
appointing a Receiver to take possession of, preserve and protect the
misappropriated funds of Plaintiff, wherever they may be traced or
located, and any properties or other assets purchased with such funds;

G. That the Court hold an immediate hearing on Plaintiff's Motion For
Temporary Restraining Order and grant the emergency equitable relief
requested, and schedule a hearing on Plaintiff's Motion For Preliminary
Injunction at the Court's earliest opportunity;

H. That all costs of this action be assessed against Defendants; and

I. That Plaintiff have such other and further relief as the Court deems
appropriate.

Jury Demand

Plaintiff hereby demands trial by jury on all

Respectfully submitted,

/s/ David N. Levine GA BAR, No. 448400

/s/ William W. Gardner GA BAR No. 284625

1050 Crown Pointe Parkway Suite 310 Atlanta, Georgia 30338 770/671-8500

</PRE>
