<blockquote>
<h2>Samarach's Disdain</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>

From: Suzanne Schiller -- Pepper Hamilton & Schee
<BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 13:17:00 1996
<BR>Subject: Samarach's Disdain<BR>
Last Append: Tue Aug  6 12:04:18 1996
<BR><BR>
I do not live in Atlanta, nor did I attend the games.  However, I still found it offensive that Samarach chose to criticize AOC even before the games were over, and failed to pronounce them "the best Olympics ever."  _Everyone_ I know who went to Atlanta said things were great there -- including many athletes (second and third hand, I admit).  That the biggest complaints were about IBM's computer not giving accurate stats to reporters, some athletic transportation problems, and the "commercialism" of the games seems indicative of the fact that Atlanta did a spectacular job.   
<BR><BR>
So, Samarach doesn't like the commercialism?  Bitch all you want at IBM . . . if they won't be able to get advertising milage out of it next time, there won't be *any* computers stats.   And where else does Samarach think the money will come from to fund an event that has become this large?  Certainly, smaller and poorer nations can't afford it at all; former Eastern block countries have enough problems as it is, and I can't imagine that people living in, say, Quebec (or even worse, Montreal), are going to agree to a tax increase so that games can be staged in Vancouver.  Samarach's idealism seems to be blinding him to reality on this one. 
<BR><BR>
Thoughts?
<BR><BR>
---Shosh    


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Maria Dennis -- Jones Day - Los Angeles <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 14:06:25 1996 <BR>Subject: Samarach's Disdain 
<BR><BR>
I happen to agree with you, Shosh.  Who does Samaranch think he's kidding?  The Olympic Games are a very expensive event to host--where does Samaranch expect the money to come from?  Billy Payne did such a good job for Atlanta that all of those Olympic facilities are PAID FOR.  Done deal. 
<BR><BR>
Samaranch's comment was rather an insult to Atlanta and, I believe, the United States.  Commercialism/private enterprise is how our country runs.  If Samaranch doesn't like it, he can try to persuade everyone not to keep voting for an American city to host the Games!  (Salt Lake City in 2002) 
<BR><BR>
-Maria Dennis



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Ted Curtis -- Univ. of So. Florida - Tampa <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 16:04:11 1996 <BR>Subject: Samarach's Disdain 
<BR><BR>
I'm with both of you. I appreciated the reference to the Munich disaster (as hidden of a reference as it was) but how can he not call the Atlanta games the best ever when he does the same thing for every other city? I seem to recall he called the Norway games the best ever and while they were fun, this was just as good. 
<BR><BR>
He doesn't like commercialism? Next time he can pay for the Games himself. 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: James Hirschhorn -- Sills Cummis - Newark <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 18:32:42 1996 <BR>Subject: Where the Money Comes From 
<BR><BR>
It will have to come from governments.  The NYT reported over the weekend that the IOC will require for all future Olympics i)a government financial guarantee and ii)that the local organizing committee be subordinate to the local municipal government, as was the case in Barcelona. 
<BR><BR>
I'm not surprised.  Many people, myself included, think that the visibility of the commercial sponsors was vulgar, and one would expect that feeling to be fairly strong in the kind of stuffy old school tie types who seem to gravitate to the top of the IOC.  But more is involved than taste.  These guys own a very valuable trademark, and the value consists of the emotional associations that the Olympic movement has for the audience -- competition, purity, glory, sportsmanship, &c.  As we know from the constant fan complaints about how money has come to dominate the sports news, the appeal of sport is chivalric, aristocratic, and pre-commercial.   The appearance of those values is the reason, paradoxically, why the mass audience will pay (indirectly) to watch sports they pay no attention to for the other 3 years and 50 weeks of an Olympic cycle.  The value of the Olympic symbol has been somewhat  eroded already by the disappearance of amateurism in the big money sports, by the power of television to shape the public perception of the games, and by the need to cater to private sponsors.  The IOC doesn't want things to get to the point where the sponsors are more visible than the show, or where it looks too much like the athletes are just an excuse for the commercials, any more than Louis Vuitton (to pull a random designer brand name out of the air) would want to see its goods sold at Wal-Mart.   
<BR><BR>
They're like some late 19th century duke marrying an heiress whose father, God forbid, is in "trade":  they want the money and need it to preserve their position, they're somewhat ashamed of wanting the money,  and they have to keep the source of the money somewhat out of sight to preserve their position.  Their father in law's money is more than welcome, but the old man has to stay a decent distance away. 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Jay Levine -- Winston & Strawn - Washington <BR>Date: Mon Aug  5 19:06:19 1996 <BR>Subject: Samarach's Disdain 
<BR><BR>
I have to go with the prevailing view.  Samarach's speech was the stereotypical "biting the hand that feeds you."  He likes to get as much money as he could but still lay back and complain about the vulgarity of the "Americans"?  Can't have it both ways my friend. 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


Appended by: Suzanne Schiller -- Pepper Hamilton & Scheetz - Philadelphia <BR>Date: Tue Aug  6 00:57:37 1996 <BR>Subject: Government Funding 
<BR><BR>
Samarach's desires are all well and good, but I can't see it happening . . . or at least, I can't see it happening and, at the same time, keeping the Olympics as a world-class, once in every four years event that will attract viewers and visitors from all over the world.   
<BR><BR>
Earlier in this seminar, there was a discussion of the Montreal financial disaster and whether it would dissuade cities from wanting to host an Olympics.  The responses were, "look at Los Angeles; with private funding there'll never be another Montreal." Well, I think the converse is also true -- take away the private funding, and any city that hosts an Olympics will be Montreal.  My guess is that the actual costs of putting on the games in Atlanta was more than the entire GNP for probably 175 of the 197 nations who participated.   Absent the sponsors, it seems to me pretty self-evident that hosting an Olympics is a fiscal losing proposition.   
<BR><BR>
Moreover, once you rely on governments to foot the entire bill, you're going to get Olympics on the cheap -- the few construction delays and safety concerns raised during the building of the new stadium in Atlanta will seem subatomic in proportion to what will happen if governments take over; you won't have to worry about bombs in Centennial Park-type places because there won't be such things, and the opening ceremonies will be reduced to the parade of nations and nothing more.  And when that happens, the tourists will stay away too; it is my impression that what brought most of the visitors to Atlanta (particularly the last minute visitors, which I think was a substantial number) was the desire to simply be "at" the site of the Oympics because everyone seemed to be having such a great time.   If Samarach has his way, then the games in Atlanta (or Sydney, depending on how they turn out) will be the last games which will truly be able to hold the distinction of the "best Olympics ever" (whether Samarach bestowed the magical words or not). 
<BR><BR>
---Shosh



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Ken Shropshire -- Wharton School - Philadelphia <BR>Date: Tue Aug  6 10:19:23 1996 <BR>Subject: Samaranch's Strategy 
<BR><BR>
Clearly what Samaranch wants to do is get things back to the way they used to be prior to L.A.  If he can get enough competition between cities he can pull it off.  some of the recent bids have incorporated this heav y governmental largesse.  Berlin, for example, offered to make all of the tickets for events free.  I guess the best face on this is that Juan chose the wrong moment to state the longstanding IOC preserence for less commercialism. 



<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: James Hirschhorn -- Sills Cummis - Newark <BR>Date: Tue Aug  6 12:04:18 1996 <BR>Subject: Government-Private 
<BR><BR>
Shosh, I think you are drawing too stark an antithesis between government and private funding.  The IOC objective isn't to push out private sponsors.  It is to draw as much private money is it can, consistent with the IOC image remaining in the foreground and the sponsors not, in the IOC's judgment, not overshadowing or controlling the show.   
<BR><BR>
In the short run, 4-12 years, I think this will work.  Olympic sponsorship on the IOC's terms still has commercial value.  Moreover, the big sponsors themselves would want a much more agressive policing of non-sponsor and small scale commercial activity.  (I gather that one of the objections to the Atlanta setup was the commercial clutter from the small time vendors whom the city licensed in order to pay for its expenses that ACOG didn't reimburse.)  In the long run, the glacial pressure of sponsor money will ultimately transform and take control of the event, as it has in American professional sports -- witness the tv time out and the disappearance of the daytime World Series game.  Moreover, in the long run mortality will change the membership of the IOC, and the next generation of stuffy old men may be more commercially minded than this one. 
<BR><BR>
I also think that it is a mistake to say "no more Montreals."  No North American or Western European government has the political support to spend huge sums on what is basically a prestige project, but the model of the Hitler Olympics is attractive elsewhere.  The Seoul games were a coming out party for South Korea, as were the Barcelona games for post-Franco Spain and for Catalonia.  Looking further back, the Rome, Tokyo and Munich games symbolized the rebuilding and new respectability of the former Axis powers, and the Moscow games were to have symbolized the parity of the USSR with the US.  The Chinese government would love the recognition implicit in being an Olympic host, and if all goes well the new South Africa would love to signal its successful arrival by holding the '08 games in Cape Town.   As Ken points out, the Germans seem to be willing to pay for a second Berlin games to celebrate the reunification of Germany.  After that, who knows what arriviste government will be willing and able to tax its people for this kind of display?  Political sponsorship is, I suspect, more palatable to the IOC than commercial sponsorship because more organized, more centralized, and less obtrusive, and because they're more at home with the idea of national glory than they are with the sale of goods. 
<BR><BR>
Finally, the ambiance surrounding the Olympic show is supposed to be a reflection of the local culture. Atlanta was.  The city, like much of this country, is run by its chamber of commerce types and considers nothing more important than the pursuit of the dollar as an end in itself.  It had to create Centennial Park as a place of  assembly because, like most American cities, everyone who can afford to do so has abandoned the center of the city, and no square, agora, promenade or other focus existed.  It created a good temporary approximation to the modern American place of public assembly -- the shopping mall.  Other sites will do it differently.  To me it is hypocritical for Samaranch et al to curl up their lip at Atlanta; they knew or should have known that they were coming to a place whose characteristic activity is marketing. 


<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>



Appended by: Greg Ross -- Poyner & Spruill - Charlotte <BR>Date: Tue Aug  6 18:29:46 1996 <BR>Subject: And another thing... 
<BR><BR>
Samaranch is also partly responsible for the shear size of this event.  As discussed elsewhere in this seminar, sports (and categories within sports) proliferate.  Downsizing seems in order. 
<BR><BR>
At the closing ceremonies, there was an interesting preview of the Sydney games.  Seems that they are building a complex 10 miles up from the harbor--Costas said the venues will be closer together than ever before.  What do you do with this sports collossus when the games are over?  Where will the Olympic village be, and what will it be used for afterwards? 

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

Appended by: Sanford J. Asman -- Hopkins & Thomas - Atlanta <BR>Date: Tue Aug  6 19:21:16 1996 <BR>Subject: Samarach's Disdain 
<BR><BR>
As I didn't see any replies from anyone else who actually attended the Olympics, let me be the first to say that first hand, it was fun to just be in the city during the games.  Aside from the tragic bombing, the Centennial Park was well done, and a very pleasant place to spend time with one's friends and families.  Notwithstanding the pre-games warnings about traffic, etc., Atlanta was truly a pleasure to get around in during the past few weeks, and only today did traffic return to normal levels, which are significantly higher than during the games. 
<BR><BR>
MARTA, notwithstanding the sporadic bad press, did a fabulous job of moving people all over -- and it operated for FREE, for anyone who was associated with the games, as a volunteer or ticket holder. 
<BR><BR>
The security forces, which increased significantly following the bombing did an exemplary job, and they all did what they had to do without being anything other than professional and polite. 
<BR><BR>
Commercialism??  I didn't watch much on TV, so I really can't address how that aspect looked.  On the other hand, things were available for sale, and people were buying them.  Otherwise, I guess the vendors would have packed up and gone home ... as some did.   
<BR><BR>
Samaranch??  I don't remember bumping into him on the street or in any of the venues.  If he was there, he would have seen the tens of thousands of locals who volunteered their time to assist in putting on the games, in getting people around the city, in being available for medical emergencies, assisting in parking, directing people at MARTA and the airport, in taking tickets and ushering at the venues, etc., etc., so if he thought it was too commercial and he didn't have a good time... Oh, well.... 
<BR><BR>
I could go on, but I guess you've got my opinion. 
<BR><BR>
Sandy

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>


