<blockquote>
<h2>Roy Jones Jr. Goes For Gold</h2>

<h3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Todd Drucker -- CC- Law Editor - New York<BR>
Date: Tue Aug  6 14:01:36 1996<BR>
Subject: Roy Jones Jr. Goes For Gold

<BR><BR>

At a press conference last Sunday, Jerry Dusenberry, president of USA Boxing, revealed that the IOC has appointed a commission to investigate a disputed decision from the 1988 Seoul Games that resulted in American Light Heavyweight boxer Roy Jones Jr. losing the gold medal to Park Si-Hun of South Korea.  Jones lost the gold medal fight on a 3-2 decision, although most observers believed he clearly dominated Park.  
<BR><BR>
Last month, Dusenberry sent a report to the USOC, alleging that several judges were bribed in favor of South Koreans and that certain International Boxing Association officials were aware of it.  IOC Director General Francios Carrard stated that the IOC will report its findings in its next executive board meeting in October, 1996.  
<BR><BR>
I remember the fight quite well, and was stunned by the decision.  As I recall, Park raised Jones' hand after the decision was announced.  If the IOC decides there was corruption involved, will Jones finally get his much deserved gold medal?        

<BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

