<H3>Seminar Library</H3>

<P><B>The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games sues an Atlanta travel agency
over the Olympic name</B> </P>

<P><FONT SIZE="-1"><B>by Jeffrey B. Gewirtz</B></FONT></P>

<P>In its aggressive effort to prevent ambush marketing in the Olympic Games
and the unauthorized use of the Olympic name and marks, the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games -- the official organizing organization for
the Games, commonly known as ACOG -- has filed suit in federal court
against a travel agency over the company's alleged unauthorized unofficial
use of the "Olympics" name. </P>

<P>The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games filed the suit in the federal
district court for the Northern District of Georgia on February 9, 1996
against the Event Group, an Atlanta-based travel and event planning
company.  Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games v. The Event Group,
L.C.C. (N.D. Ga., Atlanta Div., 2/9/96). </P>

<P>According to the complaint, in July 1995, The Event Group allegedly began
distributing materials that purported to offer the sale of transportation,
accommodations, and hospitality packages to the various 1996 Olympic
events.  The complaint further alleges, later that year, The Event Group
expanded its Olympic-related efforts by purporting to sell "1996 Summer
Olympic Games Ticket Packages" that allegedly included tickets to the
Olympic Opening and Closing Ceremonies and numerous Olympic sporting
events. </P>

<P>Contract Actions.  ACOG alleges The Event Group's activities were unlawful
because the Atlanta committee for the Olympic Games has been authorized to
act as the sole lawful source for the sale and distribution of all Olympic
tickets.  According to the complaint, all Olympic tickets include
provisions that tickets may not be resold or transferred, and that the
tickets particularly may not be resold to an entity that plans to offer the
tickets for resale--all activities ACOG alleged were conducted by The Event
Group.  While ACOG has licensed certain organizations to resell Olympic
tickets, it has not granted such rights to The Event Group. </P>

<P>The complaint, therefore, alleges that, upon purchasing the tickets from
ACOG, The Event Group was contractually bound not to resell the tickets to
third parties.  The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games alleges a claim
for breach of contract against The Event Group for allegedly reselling the
tickets as part of Olympic packages.  The sports organizing committee also
alleges a claim for tortious interference with contract.  In its complaint,
ACOG alleges this second legal claim is based on the Event Group's alleged
knowing interference with ACOG's existing contractual relations with third
parties, including official Olympic sponsors and those individuals who
received Olympic tickets through ACOG's official ticket distribution
process. </P>

<P>Trademark Actions.  Pursuant to the Amateur Sports Act, 36 U.S.C. 380, the
United States Olympic Committee (USOC) has the exclusive right to use, for
the purposes of trade, certain marks such as the international Olympic
Committee's five interlocking rings, the word "Olympic," and other marks
related to the Olympic Games--all rights assigned by the USOC to the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games.  However, according to the
complaint, neither ACOG nor the USOC have given the authority to The Event
Group for the use of these Olympic marks.  ACOG, therefore, also alleges
The Event Group violated federal trademark law in its use of the word
"Olympic" in its promotional materials. </P>

<P>Moreover, section 15. U.S.C. 1125(a), expressly prohibits an individual
from using a symbol that is likely to deceive consumers as to the
sponsorship of the individual's product.  That law prohibits an individual
from using "any false designation of origin, false or misleading
description of fact, or false or misleading representation of fact which .
. . is likely to cause confusion, or to cause mistake, or to deceive as to
the affiliation, connection, or association  of such person" with a
particular product. </P>

<P>In its complaint, ACOG alleges a cause of action for violation of this
section of the Lanham Act, claiming, The Event Group has violated federal
trademark law in making false and misleading representations of fact that
are likely to cause consumer confusion regarding the origin, sponsorship,
or approval of The Event Group's commercial activities.  The Olympic
organizing committee also alleges a cause of action for violation of state
law under the Georgia Uniform Descriptive Trade Practices Act, secs.
10-1-370. </P>

<P>In addition to monetary damages, the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic
Games demands a restraining order enjoining The Event Group from continuing
its sale of Olympic ticket packages. </P>

<P>ACOG also demands The Event Group disclose--to all entities to whom The
Event Group has sold unauthorized Olympic ticket packages--that its
activities violated ACOG's rights, and deliver to ACOG all letterhead,
advertising material, and other material that bear any Olympic trademarks. </P>

<P>-<I>Jeffrey B. Gerwitz is an attorney with the New York City law firm of
Dunnington, Bartholow & Miller.</I> </P>


