<html><head><title>Counsel Connect Seminar - Summer in Atlanta</title></head><BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" ALINK="#000080" VLINK="#FF0000">

 <a href="/inside/about.html"><img align=left border=0 width=400 height=60 src="/images/spotlight/gameshead.gif"></a>
<img align=right border=0 width=99 height=140 src="/images/spotlight/games2.gif">
<img align=right border=0 width=99 height=140 src="/images/spotlight/games.gif"> 
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
<H3>Seminar Library</H3>



<B>"On Eve of Games, Team of Arbitrators Is Standing By" </B>

<B><FONT SIZE="-1">By Lolita Browning, Staff Reporter</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1"><I>Fulton County Daily Report</I>, July 17,1996</FONT> </B>

<P>This year, for the first time, athletes in the Olympic Games must agree in
advance to take disputes with Olympic officials to binding arbitration. </P>

<P>The Games start this weekend, and arbitrators are standing by. </P>

<P>The athletes' agreement is a new section of the entry form that is
sometimes referred to as the "Butch Reynolds clause." It requires athletes
to submit any disputes with officials of the Games to a special arbitration
panel or be barred from the Olympics. </P>

<P>It was imposed after a long, costly court battle between Reynolds and the
International Amateur Athletic Federation over what the track federation
said was a positive drug test following a track meet in Monte Carlo,
Monaco. </P>

<P>The IAAF, the international body for track and field events, banned
Reynolds from competition for 28 months after the drug test in August 1990.
Reynolds will compete in the 400-meter race for the U.S. team. </P>

<P>Reynolds maintained he had not taken drugs and took the IAAF to court over
his suspension. A federal judge in Ohio awarded him $27.3 million in
damages and penalties in December 1992. But the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals threw out the award, saying U.S. courts have no jurisdiction over
the IAAF,  which is based in Monte Carlo, says Reynolds' current attorney,
James S. Albers Jr. of Albers & Albers in Columbus, Ohio. </P>

<P>Reynolds appealed the case to the U.S. Supreme Court, which refused to hear
it, Albers says. </P>

<P><H3>International Arbitration Court</H3></P>

<P>The International Olympic Committee, the International Sport Federation,
the National Olympic Committee and groups representing athletes have
created an arbitration courtthe Court of Arbitration for Sport, which is
under the supervision of the 20-member International Council of Arbitration
for Sport. </P>

<P>Reynolds says that although he signed the entry form for the Atlanta Games,
he considers arbitration clause  unconstitutional. </P>

<P>"If I want to represent my country, should I give up my rights?" Reynolds
asks. "I signed it under protest. Legally, they have no way of binding us
to that." </P>

<P>Albers, Reynolds' attorney, says the athlete had little choice. </P>

<P>"Common sense tells you that you have to be a member of this organization
if you want to participate in the Olympics," Albers says. "You have to play
by their rules." </P>

<P>Should a dispute reach arbitration, the parties are to choose from a list
of 150 arbitrators familiar with sports law, the Olympic arbitration court
says. Twelve of the 150 will be in Atlanta during the Games, says Geneva
lawyer Gabriella Kaufman, an official of the Geneva-based Court of
Arbitration and a professor of law at Geneva University. </P>

<P>In addition to the arbitrators for the IOC, the American Arbitration
Association maintains a roster of arbitrators to resolve disputes for the
U.S. Olympic Committee. </P>

<P>The latter group includes Atlanta lawyer William H. Schroder Jr., one of 16
Atlanta- area arbitrators who will be on call during the Games, says Toni
Griffin, director of public relations for the AAA in New York. </P>

<P>Schroder and the other arbitrators expect to settle disputes over such
matters as athletes' eligibility. </P>

<P>So far, 16 Olympics-related disputes have been decided by AAA arbitrators,
including four in Atlanta, Griffin says. </P>

<P>Each Atlanta case involved questions of eligibility, Griffin says. In one
case, arbitrators looked at a dispute involving the timeliness of the
filing of documents by an athlete to qualify. Another case involved the
eligibility of two coaches. The third dealt with a dispute over an
athlete's qualifying times. The fourth was over a conduct code matter,
Griffin says, declining to be more specific to protect the disputants'
confidentiality. </P>

<P>Schroder, of Schroder Partners, says switching to outside arbitration from
within the Olympics is a good idea. </P>

<P><H3>Assurance of Impartiality</H3></P>

<P>"I think that that's the way it ought to be," Schroder says. "That way you
can assure the athlete of impartiality." </P>

<P>The local arbitrators will be on call, serving in panels of three. </P>

<P>"We can be called any hour of the day or night" during the Games, Schroder
says. Notice could be as short as an hour, he says. </P>

<P>Decisions are binding, although appeals on certain grounds to the supreme
court of Switzerland are allowed, Kaufman says. </P>

<P>Meanwhile, Reynolds and Albers say they are considering filing a suit
against the attorneys who represented Reynolds in his case against the
IAAF. Lawyers with the Ohio firm Squires, Sanders and Dempsey made a
mistake, Albers says. </P>

<P>Had they filed the lawsuit in the correct court, Reynolds could have
received his award. But he did win on the facts, Albers says. </P>

<P>By press time, no one from Squires, Sanders and Dempsey had returned a
request for comment left with a secretary. </P>

<P>Reynolds, who in 1987 set the world record in the 400-meter runa record he
still ownssays mishandling caused the urine sample of a German female
athlete to be labeled as his. </P>

<P>According to the Medical Control Guide, Olympic athletes are tested for
various drugs immediately after winning an event. Tests are done for five
types of drugs: stimulants, narcotics, anabolic agents, diuretics and
peptide hormones and analogs.  </P>

<P><I>Lolita Browning's e-mail address is <a href="mailto:lbrowning@counsel.com">lbrowning@counsel.com</a></I>. </P>

