<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
<H3>Seminar Library</H3>



<P><B>"Suit by Homeless Seems in Trouble with U.S. Judge" </B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE="i1">By Emily Heller, Staff Reporter<BR>
<I>Fulton County Daily Report</I>, July 15,1996 </FONT></B></P>

<P>A federal judge says he will issue an order early this week on a federal
suit by seven homeless men trying to stop what they claim is an official
policy of sweeping them from the streets. </P>

<P>A partial bench ruling late last week by U.S. District Court Judge J. Owen
Forrester gave them little grounds to expect a victory, other than the
moral kind. </P>

<P>After a three-hour hearing on Thursday, Forrester denied the plaintiffs'
preliminary injunction of the city's aggressive-panhandling ordinance,
rejecting the claim that the law is unconstitutionally vague. </P>

<P>Forrester said he also had serious concerns about the plaintiffs' standing
in their attack on another ordinance, which outlaws behavior in parking
lots that police might perceive as a threat to people or property. </P>

<P>Forrester said he might be inclined to invalidate the ordinance. But he
said the plaintiffs had "major standing problems." The evidence showed that
the plaintiffs were arrested under numerous laws, but not that one, the
judge said. </P>

<P>Moreover, Forrester said, the plaintiffs had not showed "credible,
statistical evidence" to back their claim that the city systematically
clears its streets of beggars during major tourist events. The plaintiffs
are trying to stop the city from conducting another sweep for the Olympics.</P>


<P>Forrester did provide advocates for the homeless with what may have been
some consolation. He sharply criticized Atlanta officials for what he
called "indifference" to the problems of the homeless. The officials, he
said, ignore complaints about treatment of the homeless by the police and
give mainly lip service to the idea of teaching officers how to deal with
street people. </P>

<P>In particular, Forrester assailed Mayor Bill Campbell and Police Chief
Beverly Harvard, who gave depositions in the suit. </P>

<P>"Clearly they do nothing to investigate" complaints about police harassment
of homeless people, Forrester said. "It seems to the court that ... the
City of Atlanta is largely indifferent as to how its laws are enforced on
this group of people." </P>

<P>In response, Senior Assistant City Attorney Kendric E. Smith said the
criticism came from advocates for the homeless, not the homeless people
themselves. Thus city officials thought there was a "spin" on the
complaints and took them "with a grain of salt," Smith replied. </P>

<P>Speaking slowly and emphatically, Forrester said: "They didn't do a police
investigation. They didn't do anything. You don't have to be a rocket
scientist to see that it's an issue. Under the circumstances, it's
reasonable to do something." </P>

<P>The judge sarcastically took Harvard in particular to task for merely
asking line officers, "Is anybody violating the constitutional rights of
our citizens?" </P>

<P>Forrester also said the case contained unanswered evidence that the
plaintiffs had been arrested without probable cause. But the city's
indifference does not necessarily explain the unconstitutional arrests, he
said. </P>

<H3>What Constitutes a Crime?</H3>

<P>Forrester questioned Smith ironically about the 1996 city ordinance that
outlaws behavior in parking lots in "a manner not usual for law-abiding"
people and that would warrant a reasonable public safety concern. Last
month Forrester issued a temporary restraining order stopping the city from
enforcing the law passed in April. </P>

<P>At the hearing, he challenged Smith with a series of questions to establish
what he described as the law's vagueness. Might the following people be
arrested? he asked: </P>

<P>l Children playing marbles in a parking lot; </P>

<P>l An 18-year-old with a four-day beard, dirty hair and scruffy clothing,
holding a weapon while standing against a car waiting to meet buddies for a
hunting trip; </P>

<P>l Men playing football; or</P>

<P>l An epileptic having a seizure walking through a parking lot; </P>

<P>Smith replied that vulnerability to "clever hypotheticals" does not condemn
the law as overbroad. But how are the police supposed to enforce it?
Forrester asked, saying that he was not merely trying to think of clever
hypotheticals. </P>

<P>"The question is, what would the law allow [an officer] to do?" the judge
asked. Would the law give these people sufficient notice that what they
were doing would constitute a crime? he asked. </P>

<P>After the hearing Smith declined to comment, as did plaintiffs' attorneys
Kurt S. Kusiak and Matthew M. Burke, associates at the Boston firm of Ropes
& Gray. The attorneys said they had agreed with the judge not to discuss
the case with the media. Atchison v. City of Atlanta, No. 96-cv-1430
(N.D.Ga. filed June 10, 1996).  </P>

<P><I>Emily Heller's e-mail address is <a href="mailto:eheller@counsel.com">eheller@counsel.com</a>. </I></P>

