<html><head><title>Counsel Connect Seminar - Summer in Atlanta</title></head><BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" ALINK="#000080" VLINK="#FF0000">

 <a href="/inside/about.html"><img align=left border=0 width=400 height=60 src="/images/spotlight/gameshead.gif"></a>
<img align=right border=0 width=99 height=140 src="/images/spotlight/games2.gif">
<img align=right border=0 width=99 height=140 src="/images/spotlight/games.gif"> 
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
<H3>Seminar Library</H3>


<P>Editor's Note: Self-styled advocates for the involuntarily homeless moved
for a TRO to prevent the city of Atlanta from enforcing certain ordinances
that reportedly are being used to reduce the homeless presence on the
streets of Atlanta before the Summer Olympics. The advocates allege that
the homeless have been targeted by three unconstitutional city ordinances
covering aggressive panhandling, interference with parked vehicles, and
criminal trespass.</P>

</blockquote>


<B><P>IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR THE NORTHERN DISTRICT OF GEORGIA
ATLANTA DIVISION </P>

<P>ROBERT ATCHISON, CURTIS GATES, JOSEPH HORTON, ANTHONY JOHNSON,  DONALD J.
JOHNSON, DONALD V. PATTON, KENNETH WILSON (Plaintiffs) </P>

<P>The CITY OF ATLANTA, GEORGIA, a municipal corporation, and BEVERLY HARVARD
in her official capacity as CHIEF OF THE ATLANTA POLICE DEPARTMENT
(Defendants) </P></B>

<P>CIVIL ACTION
FILE NO. 1:96-CV-1430JOF</P>


<P>MOTION FOR A TEMPORARY RESTRAINING ORDER AND PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION </P>

<P>Come now Plaintiffs and, pursuant to Fed. R. Civ. P. 57 and 65 and 28
U.S.C. Sections  2201 and 2202, file this motion for a temporary
restraining order and preliminary injunction. As grounds therefor,
Plaintiffs show the Court as follows:  </P>

<P>1.  This is an action to redress deprivations of constitutional liberties
suffered by certain homeless residents of the City of Atlanta, Georgia,
solely because of their involuntary homelessness. Plaintiffs seek
declaratory, injunctive, and monetary relief from (a) arrests made pursuant
to city ordinances which are facially unconstitutional, (b) the persistent
enforcement of these ordinances and a state statute which continue to be
unconstitutionally applied against the homeless as part of a systematic
effort to purge them from the streets and other public places, and (c) the
unconstitutional policy, practice and custom of harassing, intimidating,
detaining and arresting homeless people for engaging in harmless,
inoffensive and lawful activities they, by reason of their homelessness,
are forced to perform in public.  </P>


<P>2.  Plaintiffs' complaint is cast in six counts, which allege the
following:  </P>

<P>(a) Count I: Defendants have relied upon Chapter 3, Section 17-3006 of the
Code of Ordinances -- the Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance (the
"Panhandling Ordinance"), as a basis for harassing, intimidating and
arresting one or more of Plaintiffs. On its face, and as applied to one or
more of Plaintiffs, the Panhandling Ordinance:  </P>

<P>(i) infringes upon constitutionally protected expression and thus violates
the right to free speech under the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
United States Constitution;  </P>

<P>(ii) irrationally, arbitrarily, capriciously and without sufficient
justification distinguishes between panhandling and all other forms of
solicitation in violation of one or more of Plaintiffs' right to equal
protection of the laws as guaranteed by the Fourteenth Amendment to the
United States Constitution; and  </P>

<P>(iii) prohibits conduct that is constitutionally protected and beyond the
City's police power and, thus, is unconstitutionally overbroad in violation
of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.  </P>

<P>As a proximate result of Defendants' unconstitutional actions, one or more
of Plaintiffs have suffered, and continue to suffer, substantial injuries
and damage.  </P>

<P>(b) Count II: Defendants have relied upon Chapter 106, Article II, Section
106-57 -- Unauthorized Interference or Attempted Interference With Parked
Vehicles (the "Parked Vehicle Ordinance"), as a basis for harassing,
intimidating and arresting one or more of Plaintiffs. Either on its face,
as applied to one or more of Plaintiffs, or both, the Parked Vehicle
Ordinance:  </P>

<P>(i) is unconstitutionally vague in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to
the United States Constitution;  </P>

<P>(ii) violates one or more of Plaintiffs' fundamental constitutional rights
to travel and to freedom of movement; and  </P>

<P>(iii) violates one or more of Plaintiffs' right to be free from arrest
without probable cause.  </P>

<P>As a proximate result of Defendants' unconstitutional actions, one or more
of Plaintiffs have suffered, and continue to suffer, substantial injuries
and damage.  </P>

<P>(c) Count III: Defendants have relied upon O.C.G.A. Section 16-7-21 (the
"Criminal Trespass Law") as a basis for harassing, intimidating and
arresting one or more of Plaintiffs. As applied to one or more of
Plaintiffs, the Criminal Trespass Law:  </P>

<P>(i) is unconstitutionally vague in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to
the United States Constitution; and  </P>

<P>(ii) violates one or more of Plaintiffs' fundamental constitutional rights
to travel and to freedom of movement.  </P>

<P>As a proximate result of Defendants' unconstitutional actions, one or more
of Plaintiffs have suffered, and continue to suffer, substantial injuries
and damage.  </P>

<P>(d) Count IV: Defendants, acting under color of state law, have violated 42
U.S.C. Section 1983 by engaging in a policy, practice and custom of
arresting, threatening to arrest, intimidating and otherwise harassing
Plaintiffs as part of the homeless population of Atlanta. As a proximate
result of this policy, practice and custom, Defendants have deprived
Plaintiffs of rights, privileges and immunities secured by the United
States Constitution. As a proximate result of Defendants' unconstitutional
actions, Plaintiffs have suffered, and continue to suffer, substantial
injuries and damage.  </P>

<P>(e) Count V: Defendants' policy, practice and custom of arresting,
harassing and otherwise interfering with the daily lives of Plaintiffs, as
part of the general homeless population of Atlanta, violates their
fundamental constitutional rights to travel and freedom of movement. As a
proximate result of Defendants' unconstitutional actions, Plaintiffs have
suffered, and continue to suffer, substantial injuries and damage.  </P>

<P>(f) Count VI: In detaining and arresting homeless persons for engaging in
conduct which constitutes the ordinary and essential activities of daily
life, Defendants are detaining and arresting Plaintiffs on a purely
pretextual basis. Defendants' policy, practice and custom of effecting
these purely pretextual detentions and arrests violates the rights of
Plaintiffs to be free from unreasonable search and seizure as protected by
the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments to the United States Constitution. As
a proximate result of Defendants' unconstitutional actions, Plaintiffs have
suffered, and continue to suffer, substantial injuries and damage.  </P>


<P>3.  In their complaint, Plaintiffs seek the following equitable and legal
relief:  </P>

<P>(a) A declaration that the Panhandling Ordinance is unconstitutional on its
face; (b) A declaration that the Panhandling Ordinance is unconstitutional
as applied to Plaintiffs;  </P>

<P>(c) A declaration that the Parked Vehicle Ordinance is unconstitutional on
its face;  </P>

<P>(d) A declaration that the Parked Vehicle Ordinance is unconstitutional as
applied to Plaintiffs;  </P>

<P>(e) A declaration that the Criminal Trespass Law is unconstitutional as
applied to Plaintiffs;  </P>

<P>(f) A declaration that Defendants' policy, practice and custom of
arresting, threatening to arrest, intimidating and otherwise harassing
Plaintiffs and the homeless population of Atlanta in general is violative
of 42 U.S.C. Section 1983;  </P>

<P>(g) The entry of a temporary and permanent injunction prohibiting
Defendants from effecting any arrests or otherwise stopping, detaining or
harassing any person under the authority of Chapter 3, Section 17-3006 of
the Code of Ordinances -- the Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance -- or
Chapter 106, Article II, Section 106-57 -- the Parked Vehicle Ordinance:  </P>

<P>(h) The entry of a temporary and permanent injunction prohibiting
Defendants from effecting arrests or otherwise stopping, detaining or
harassing any person by applying O.C.G.A. Section 16-7-21 -- the Criminal
Trespass Law -- in an unconstitutional manner;  </P>

<P>(i) The entry of a temporary and permanent injunction prohibiting
Defendants from engaging in their policy, practice and custom of arresting
or otherwise intimidating and harassing Plaintiffs as part of the general
homeless population of Atlanta for engaging in ordinary  and essential
activities of their lives on or about the public streets of Atlanta;  </P>

<P>(j) An award of compensatory damages for the pain and injury Plaintiffs
have suffered as  the proximate result of Defendants' actions;  </P>

<P>(k) An award of reasonable attorney's fees and costs pursuant to 42 U.S.C.
Section 1988; and  </P>

<P>(l) Any further relief as the Court may deem just and appropriate. </P>



<P>4.  As delineated more fully in their supporting memorandum, filed
contemporaneously herewith,  Plaintiffs show that they are entitled to the
relief requested for the following reasons:  </P>

<P>(a) Plaintiffs have established a substantial likelihood of success on the
merits of their claims that:  </P>

<P>(i) the challenged ordinances are unconstitutional on their face and as
applied;  </P>

<P>(ii) the challenged statute is unconstitutional as applied;  </P>

<P>(iii) Defendants' policy, practice and custom of arresting, threatening to
arrest,  intimidating and otherwise harassing homeless citizens such as
Plaintiffs violates 42 U.S.C. Section 1983;  </P>

<P>(iv) The policy, practice and custom of arresting, threatening to arrest,
intimidating  and otherwise harassing homeless citizens such as Plaintiffs
violates Plaintiffs' fundamental  constitutional rights to travel and
freedom of movement; and  </P>

<P>(v) The policy, practice and custom of arresting, threatening to arrest,
intimidating and otherwise harassing homeless citizens such as Plaintiffs
violates Plaintiffs' right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure
under the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments to the United States
Constitution.  </P>

<P>(b) Plaintiffs have established that their continuing constitutional
deprivations are irreparable in nature, and cannot be adequately
compensated by remedies at law. Likewise, the fear and loss of dignity
incident to repeated arrests and detention for honest activities can only
be sufficiently redressed by an order by this Court invalidating the
ordinances and the application of the state law at issue and enjoining
Defendants' harassment of homeless individuals.  </P>

<P>(c) Plaintiffs have established that the injury and threat of continued
injury to Plaintiffs outweighs any potential harm to Defendants from an
injunction. Defendants' interest in preventing crime in Atlanta is amply
served by the enforcement of other, unchallenged laws that are clearly
expressed and neutrally applied. Defendants will endure no harm in abiding
by the requirements of the Constitution.  </P>

<P>(d) Plaintiffs have established that an injunction would not disserve the
public interest. Defendants have numerous ordinances and statutes that are
clearly expressed and neutrally applied to ensure the public safety.  </P>


<P>5.
Pursuant to Local Rule 220-3, Plaintiffs seek an immediate hearing on their
request for a temporary restraining order. As discussed herein, Plaintiffs
are subjected to Defendants' policy, practice, and custom of arresting,
threatening to arrest, intimidating, and otherwise harassing homeless
citizens on a daily basis. In light of this grave and continuous
deprivation of Plaintiffs' constitutional rights, and the fact that the
only plausible relief for Plaintiffs is a temporary restraining order from
this Court, an immediate hearing on Plaintiffs' motion is a necessity.  </P>


<P>6.
Plaintiffs request that the Court enter an order:  </P>

<P>(1) Temporarily enjoining Defendants from effecting any arrests or
otherwise stopping, detaining or harassing any person under the authority
of Chapter 3, Section 17-30(16 of the Code of Ordinances -- the Aggressive
Panhandling Ordinance;  </P>

<P>(2) Temporarily enjoining Defendants from effecting any arrests or
otherwise stopping, detaining or harassing any person under the authority
of Chapter 106, Article II, Section 106-57 -- the Parked Vehicle Ordinance;
</P> 

<P>(3) Temporarily enjoining Defendants from effecting arrests or otherwise
stopping, detaining or harassing any person by applying O.C.G.A. Section
16-7-21 -- the Criminal Trespass Law -- in an unconstitutional manner;  </P>

<P>(4) Temporarily enjoining Defendants from engaging in any policy, practice
and custom of arresting, threatening to arrest, intimidating and otherwise
harassing Plaintiffs and the homeless population of Atlanta in general in
violation of 42 U.S.C. Section 1983; and  </P>

<P>(5) Temporarily enjoining Defendants from arresting or otherwise
intimidating and harassing Plaintiffs as part of the general homeless
population of Atlanta for engaging in ordinary and essential activities of
their lives on or about the public streets of Atlanta.  </P>


<P>7.</P>

<P>In support of their motion, Plaintiffs rely upon all pleadings, documents
and exhibits of record, in addition to the following exhibits attached to
their Memorandum in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion for a Temporary
Restraining Order and Preliminary Injunction:  </P>

<P>(1) Exhibit A -- Affidavit of Anita Beaty, discussing the number and
condition of the homeless in Atlanta;  </P>

<P>(2) Exhibit B -- Affidavits of Plaintiffs, describing their homelessness
and their treatment by the Atlanta Police;  </P>

<P>(3) Exhibit C -- Affidavit of Michael Grazio, summarizing and attaching the
declarations of 161 homeless residents of Atlanta describing their
treatment by the Atlanta Police;  </P>

<P>(4) Exhibit D -- Various newspaper articles, describing the homeless in
Atlanta;  </P>

<P>(5) Exhibit E -- Affidavit of Gregory Payne, describing his work with
Atlanta's homeless and observations of the treatment of the homeless by the
Atlanta Police;  </P>

<P>(6) Exhibit F -- Affidavit of Hollande Levinson, describing her
observations of the treatment of the homeless by the Atlanta Police;  </P>

<P>(7) Exhibit G -- Affidavit of Elizabeth Dede, describing her observations
of the treatment of the homeless by the Atlanta Police;  </P>

<P>(8) Exhibit H -- Affidavit of Ron Jackson, describing his observations of
the treatment of the homeless by the Atlanta Police;  </P>

<P>(9) Exhibit I -- Photograph of Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance Sign posted
in the City of Atlanta;  </P>

<P>(10) Exhibit J -- Affidavit of Robert Ferrell, describing the nature and
operation of Atlanta's labor pools;  </P>

<P>(11) Exhibit K -- Affidavit of Donna McKay-Randozzi, summarizing police
records of  arrests of homeless people in Atlanta; and  </P>

<P>(12) Exhibit L -- Patton v. Baltimore, No. S 93-2389, Mem. Order (D. Md.
Aug. 19, 1994).  </P>


<P>WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray that their motion for a temporary restraining
order and preliminary injunction be inquired into and sustained.  </P>


<P>Respectfully submitted,</P>

