<blockquote>
<H3>Seminar Library</H3>


<P>Editor's Note: U.S. District Judge Owen Forrester ruled that Atlanta's
Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance was unconstitutional in part. He found
specifically that prohibiting "continuing to request, beg or solicit alms
in close proximity to [an] individual" was unconstitutional. The court
denied plaintiffs' motion for a preliminary injunction. However, the court
noted that there was strong evidence of a pattern of police harassment of
the homeless that was "disconcerting." </P>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><P>IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR THE NORTHERN DISTRICT OF GEORGIA
ATLANTA DIVISION </P>

<P>ROBERT ATCHISON, et al., (Plaintiffs)</P>

<P>vs</P>

<P>THE CITY OF ATLANTA, GEORGIA, et al., (Defendants) </P></B>

<P>CIVIL ACTION NO.
1:96-CV-1430-JOF</P>


<P>ORDER</P>

<P>This matter is before the court on Plaintiffs' motion for a preliminary
injunction [5-1].  </P>

<P>I. STATEMENT OF THE CASE</P>

<P>Alleging that Defendants have instituted a systematic effort to purge the
streets of the homeless,1 Plaintiffs have challenged the facial and "as
applied" constitutionality of two city ordinances: (1) Section 106-85 of
the Code of Ordinances of the City of Atlanta, (the "Aggressive Panhandling
Ordinance"), and (2) Section 106-57 of the Code of Ordinances of the City
of Atlanta (the "Parked Vehicle Ordinance"). Plaintiffs also claim that
Defendants have a custom, practice, and policy of harassing, intimidating,
detaining and arresting the homeless engaged in lawful activity in
violation of the First, Fourth, Fifth and Fourteen Amendments.  </P>

<P>At a hearing conducted on June 19, 1995, this court issued a temporary
restraining order enjoining the City of Atlanta from charging or
prosecuting anyone based upon one provision, Section 106-57(a)(3) of the
Parked Vehicle Ordinance. After the parties conducted expedited discovery,
the court entertained further oral arguments from the parties in support
and opposition to this motion for a preliminary injunction on July 11,
1996. At the close of that hearing, the court deferred ruling on the
Section 1983 claims based upon alleged Fourth Amendment violations and
verbally indicated its intention to deny the motion for preliminary
injunction as to the Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance and grant in part the
motion as to the Parked Vehicle Ordinance if Plaintiffs proved that
Plaintiffs had standing to challenge the ordinance. After further
consideration of the issues and materials that the parties have submitted
in this matter, however, the court now GRANTS the motion for preliminary
injunction IN PART as to one provision of the Aggressive Panhandling
Ordinance, and DENIES the motion for a preliminary injunction on all
remaining matters, including the Parked Vehicle Ordinance and the matters
underlying Plaintiffs' Section 1983 claims.  </P>


<P>II. STATEMENT OF FACTS</P>

<P>The record developed before the court thus far reveals a disconcerting
pattern in which Atlanta police officers have arrested and detained
individuals engaged in lawful activity upon the streets of Atlanta for
alleged criminal violations. After the homeless Plaintiffs were kept in
custody for a number of days, charges for the crimes alleged were dismissed
either on the motion of the solicitor or based upon the failure of the
officer or the failure of an accused who had been released on bond to
appear in court. An initial review of the evidence from expedited discovery
and unrefuted affidavits now before the court suggests strongly that the
Plaintiffs may at trial be able to show that in the past eight months
Plaintiffs have been subjected to arrests in which the arresting officer
lacked probable cause to effect an arrest on at least ten occasions.
Although the materials submitted make a detailed reconstruction of the
events difficult, the circumstances of those arrests follow:  </P>


<P>*  On the night of November 21, 1995, Officer A.C. Huntley observed
Plaintiff Robert Atchison on foot holding his "Homeless - Please Help" sign
soliciting from cars at the intersection of Spring and Linden Streets.
Huntley Aff. at Paragraph 10. Officer Huntley warned Atchison that he would
arrest him if he continued to approach the cars soliciting money. Id. On
the following evening, however, Officer Huntley witnessed Atchison in the
same location soliciting money in the same manner. Id. at Paragraph 11.
Atchison did not frighten, block, or act in any manner to force people to
contribute, and respected the negative responses of persons who told him
that they would not help him. Atchison Aff. at Paragraph 5. Yet, Huntley
arrested Atchison for habitual begging and sent him to the Pretrial
Detention Center, where Atchison was held for three days until the charges
were dismissed on motion of the prosecution. Atchison Aff. at Paragraph 5;
Huntley Aff. at Paragraph 11; Defendants' Ex. A to Huntley Aff.  </P>

<P>*  In January 1996, Joseph Horton was talking with another homeless man at
the intersection of Whitehall and McDaniel Streets when a police car pulled
up and the officer frisked and arrested the men for panhandling. Horton
Aff. at Paragraphs 4-5. After Horton was held at the Pretrial Detention
Center for the weekend, the charges were dismissed on the motion of the
solicitor. Id.  </P>

<P>*  On February 22, 1996, Officer R. Thomas arrested Atchison at the corner
of Ellis and Piedmont for begging in violation of Section 106-85 as well as
for disorderly conduct based solely upon Atchison's display of his
"Homeless -Please Help" sign to oncoming traffic and pedestrians. Atchison
Aff. at Paragraph 7; see also Arrest Citation at Defendants' Ex. 19 of
Defendants' Memorandum in Opposition to Plaintiffs' Motion for Preliminary
Injunction. After Atchison served three days in the Pretrial Detention
Center, the charges were dismissed because the officer was not in court.
Id.  </P>

<P>*  In March 1996, the police discovered Curtis Gates as he was changing the
flat tire of a woman whose car was disabled in the vicinity of Interstate
20 and Ashby Street. Gates Aff. at Paragraph 6. Despite the woman's
proffered explanation, the police officer charged Gates with vending
without a permit and held Gates overnight at the Pretrial Detention Center
until the charges were dismissed. Id.  </P>

<P>*  On April 28, 1996, Gates asked a customer at the BP gas station on Lee
Street if he could clean his windows. Gates Aff. at Paragraph 8. Upon the
customer's refusal, Gates has alleged that he never repeated his request,
nor forced his presence or help upon the customer. Id. Officer T.J. Humes
subsequently arrested Gates for begging and soliciting; Humes has indicated
that Gates continued his solicitation after the customer gave a negative
response. See Arrest Citation at Defendants' Ex. 19 of Defendants'
Memorandum in Opposition to Plaintiffs' Motion for Preliminary Injunction.
Yet, after Gates was kept in custody at the Pretrial Detention Center, the
charges were dismissed. Gates Aff. at Paragraph 8.  </P>

<P>*  On May 23, 1996, Officer R. A. Bettis arrested Gates for criminal
trespass near the Exxon station at 500 Ashby Street. Gates Aff. at
Paragraph 9. At the time of his arrest, Gates was not on private property,
but rather was walking down Ashby Street assisting a man in looking on the
sidewalk for a gas container. Id. Bettis has indicated that Gates
previously had been warned to remain away from the location. See Arrest
Citation at Defendants' Ex. 19 of Defendants' Memorandum in Opposition to
Plaintiffs' Motion for Preliminary Injunction. After a two-day detention,
however, the charges were dismissed. Gates Aff. at Paragraph 10.  </P>

<P>*  On three separate dates in May 1996, officers arrested Atchison for
illegal pedestrian solicitation of rides or business for merely displaying
his "Homeless -- Please Help" sign to oncoming cars. Atchison Aff. at
Paragraphs 10-12; Huntley Aff. at Paragraph 12; see also Defendants' Ex. B
to Huntley Aff.  </P>

<P>*  On April 22, 1996, Anthony Johnson was cutting through a parking lot to
get dinner. A. Johnson Aff. at Paragraph 8. Without providing Johnson with
an opportunity to explain, Officer Daud Sheikh, who had previously warned
Johnson to stay away from that lot, arrested Johnson for being "an
unauthorized person in a parking lot" under the former ordinance found at
Section 106-57. Id. at Paragraphs 8-9; Sheikh Aff. at Paragraphs 4-5; Ex. A
to Sheikh's Aff. Id. Although the former ordinance was repealed on April 9,
1996, Officer Sheikh was unaware of the enactment of the new Parked Vehicle
Ordinance. Sheikh Aff. at Paragraph 5. The charges were subsequently
dismissed when Officer Sheikh could not appear in court. A. Johnson Aff. at
Paragraph 8-9; Sheikh Aff. at Paragraph 7; Ex. A. to Sheikh's Aff.  </P>


<P>Even in situations where an actual arrest or institution of charges was not
involved, it appears that police officers exceeded their authority in a
manner with constitutional implications while dealing with the homeless.
For example, Plaintiff Kenneth Wilson has averred that, at the end of 1995,
a number of Atlanta police arrived in the parking lot of TempCorps where he
was assembled with a group of homeless men seeking work. Wilson Aff. at
Paragraph 6. Without explanation, the police lined up the men against a
fence and frisked them. Id.  </P>

<P>In March of 1996, another police officer approached Kenneth Wilson when he
was crossing a police parking lot near the Jefferson Place Shelter; the
officer threatened and handcuffed Wilson before another officer intervened
and clarified that Wilson was not the same individual who had received
prior warnings about crossing the police parking lot. Horton Aff. at
Paragraphs 4-5. In a similar vein, Plaintiff Donald Johnson has averred
that in May 1996, a police officer apprehended Johnson and some friends who
were merely having a discussion at St. Luke's. D. Johnson Aff. at Paragraph
11. After spending the night in custody at the Pretrial Detention Center,
the group was released without charges being pressed. Id.  </P>

<P>The facts and allegations found within a number of the sworn declarations
submitted from one hundred sixty-one homeless men in Atlanta shed further
light upon the nature of the alleged Fourth Amendment violations and the
potential evidence available to demonstrate widespread violations of the
constitutional rights of persons living on the streets. See Ex. C to
Plaintiffs' Amended Memorandum in Support of Plaintiffs' Motion for A
Temporary Restraining Order and Preliminary Injunction. Although some of
the declarations appear to include valid stops and circumstances that
clearly warranted further police inquiry and action, dozens of the
declarations recount incidents in which officers randomly and without
apparent cause checked a person's identification, threatened arrest, or
ordered the men to "move along." Other declarants have described incidents
similar to those that the Plaintiffs have experienced in which officers
arrested and detained them at the Pretrial Detention Center for a number of
days before the charges were dismissed.  </P>

<P>The court recognizes that the City of Atlanta and its officials have shown
their concern for the plight of the homeless through, inter alia,
allocation of funds and social programs on behalf of the homeless. See
Campbell Dep. at 55. Yet, the limited discovery taken to date shows that
the mayor and police chief were on general notice that the homeless feared
police misconduct and sweeps, and have been largely indifferent to managing
the law enforcement response. Before the Super Bowl was held in Atlanta,
Mayor Bill Campbell met with a group of homeless who indicated that they
feared that the City would clear them from the streets. Campbell Dep. at
13-14. On another occasion, the Mayor also met with a homeless advocacy
group marching to City Hall in protest of alleged police harassment. Id. at
48. Although the Mayor still attributes the source of these allegations to
Anita Beatty, the Director of the Atlanta Task Force for the Homeless from
whom Campbell has received letters and heard complaints about the treatment
of the homeless, id. at 24, 34, 40-41, some of the homeless persons that
Campbell has met during his tenure as mayor as well as other homeless
advocacy groups have also expressed these same general concerns. Id. at
33-34. Further, it appears that at least two department heads within the
administration had some confirming data.2  Atlanta Police Department Chief
Beverly Harvard has also admitted to reading reports of alleged police
harassment and sweeps of the homeless in the newspaper. Harvard Dep. at
18-20.  </P>

<P>Little was done in response to these reports. The Mayor did meet with
Harvard and Crosslea to ensure that there was no harassment policy in place
and to issue oral instructions directing against such a policy. Campbell
Dep. at 35, 56-58; Harvard Dep. at 11-14. Aside from informal internal
inquiries among division commanders concerning policy directives, neither
the Mayor nor the Chief of Police initiated an investigation of the arrests
of the homeless. Harvard Dep. at 20-23, 27; Campbell Dep. at 18.  </P>

<P>Finally, the evidence arising from the limited discovery further reveals
that police officers responsible for patrolling the streets have not
received sufficient training in order to prepare them for regular
encounters with the homeless. New recruits to the Atlanta Police Department
receive 936 hours of classroom training and 240 hours of field training.
Johnson Dep. at 20-21. Officers appear to spend eighty hours of course work
focusing upon criminal procedure, which includes probable cause and
warrantless arrests. Nichols Aff. at Paragraphs 5, 7. Yet, only twenty
hours of the classroom training constitutes the instruction afforded for
all of the many city ordinances. Johnson Dep. at 46. As for any
subsequently enacted ordinance, the Atlanta Police Department relies
largely upon a brief discussion or a short handout summarizing the new
ordinance during roll call. Johnson Dep. at 9; McFarland Dep. at 13-14.
There is no verification procedure in place under which the Department
ensures that officers on the beat have either read the ordinance or the
summaries of the ordinance provided. McFarland Dep. at 13-14. In addition,
it does not appear that officers have received "any instruction of any kind
regarding how they should interact with homeless people." Weaver Dep. at
14, 60; McFarland Dep. at 19; Humes Dep. at 16, 45; Johnson Dep. at 24.  </P>

<P>It is apparent that officers on the beat have not been fully trained
regarding the scope and application of the Aggressive Panhandling
Ordinance, the Parked Vehicle Ordinance, or even these ordinances'
predecessors. See Johnson Dep. at 37-38. When the Aggressive Panhandling
Ordinance was originally enacted in 1991, the roll call training did not
exceed a fifteen minute lecture accompanied by a short hand-out. See Ex. N.
to Plaintiffs' Supplemental Brief in Support of Motion for Preliminary
Injunction; Johnson Dep. at 36. Although the officers deposed during
expedited discovery exhibited some common sense understanding about dealing
with the type of conduct prohibited under the ordinances at issue, they
were unable to describe or discern with any precision the legal parameters
of the laws they are charged with enforcing. See Johnson Dep. at 27-29;
Weaver Dep. at 27; McFarland Dep. at 49-53; Humes Dep. at 22-25, 35.
Furthermore, despite the fact that the current Parked Vehicle Ordinance
requires particularized conduct beyond merely loitering or prowling in a
parking lot, the evidence suggests that police officers have arrested nine
individuals for simply loitering under this ordinance in May and June 1996;
see Ex. L. Each of these nine citations, however, was subsequently
dismissed by the municipal court. Id.  </P>


<P>III. DISCUSSION</P>

<P>This matter is not before the court at this time for a final adjudication
on the merits. Neither side is yet prepared for that, and much may change
based on further investigation and because of what is said herein. The
court has only been asked to grant preliminary relief. In order to succeed
on their motion for preliminary injunction, Plaintiffs must show: (1) a
substantial likelihood of success on the merits; (2) that they will suffer
irreparable injury if the injunction is not granted; (3) that the injury
which would occur in the absence of the injunction outweighs the injury
caused to Defendants due to the injunction; and (4) that the injunction is
in the public interest. Church v. City of Huntsville, 30 F.3d 1332, 1342
(11th Cir. 1994). As to the issues for which the parties have standing, the
court believes that Plaintiffs have satisfied their burden of showing
irreparable injury in the absence of a preliminary injunction that
outweighs any burden that would be imposed upon Defendants, and that the
injunction serves the public interest. Accordingly, the court will focus
its analysis upon whether Plaintiffs have a substantial likelihood to
succeed on the merits of their claims to warrant a preliminary injunction  </P>


<P>A. THE AGGRESSIVE PANHANDLING ORDINANCE4  </P>

<P>In December 1995, the Atlanta City Council adopted and the Mayor approved
Chapter 106, Offenses and Misdemeanors, Section 106-85, which addresses
"begging and soliciting alms by accosting or forcing oneself upon the
company of another." In an attempt to prohibit aggressive panhandling, the
ordinance states:  </P>


<P>[i]t shall be unlawful for any person to ask, beg or solicit alms, which
include money or other things of value, or exhibit oneself for the purpose
of begging or soliciting alms by:  </P>

<P>(1) Accosting another; or
(2) Forcing oneself upon the company of another.  </P>

<P>Section 106-85(c). According to the definitional section of the ordinance,
"accosting" means "approaching or speaking to someone in such a manner as
would cause a reasonable person to fear imminent bodily harm or the
commission of a criminal act upon such person's person, or upon property in
such person's immediate possession." Section 106-85(a). "Forcing oneself
upon the company of another" is defined as "continuing to request, beg or
solicit alms in close proximity to the individual addressed after the
person to whom the request is directed has made a negative response,
blocking the passage of the individual addressed or otherwise engaging in
conduct which could reasonably be construed as intended to compel or force
a person to accede to demands." Section 106-85(a).  </P>

<P>Challenging the facial constitutionality of this ordinance, Plaintiffs
argue that the Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance prohibits protected speech
in a public forum in violation of the First Amendment and the Equal
Protection Clause. Defendants have asserted that the challenges are without
merit because the ordinance does not regulate protected speech, but rather
prohibits a particularized sort of conduct occurring in the context of
panhandling. Alternatively, if the court concludes that the ordinance does
regulate speech, Defendants argue that the ordinance presents a valid time,
place or manner regulation that passes constitutional muster.  </P>

<P>The parties have not contested whether begging or panhandling is a
recognized form of protected speech under the First Amendment.5 Assuming
arguendo that simple begging constitutes protected expression,6 the First
Amendment does allow reasonable regulations of the time, place, and manner
of protected speech for regulations necessary to further significant
governmental interests. See Perry Educ. Ass'n v. Perry Local Educators'
Ass'n, 460 U.S. 37, 45 (1983). Notwithstanding the possibility of untrained
or erroneous enforcement of this ordinance, the language of the Aggressive
Panhandling Ordinance does not establish an outright ban on begging.
Indeed, begging is expressly permitted under the ordinance. Rather, the
city ordinance merely prohibits begging or panhandling through two
particular means: (1) accosting another person or (2) forcing oneself upon
another's company. Accordingly, this court views the ordinance as a
means-oriented restriction aimed at the secondary effects of particular
conduct associated with overly aggressive solicitation for alms. See e.g.
City of Renton v. Playtime Theatres, Inc., 475 U.S. 41, 46 (1986).  </P>

<P>In Renton, 475 U.S. 41 (1986), the Supreme Court upheld a zoning ordinance
prohibiting adult movie theaters that displayed adult films within 1000
feet of residences, churches or schools. Although the ordinance made a
distinction based upon the subject matter of the films being shown, the
Court held that the ordinance was content-neutral because its purpose was
to prevent the secondary effects that adult theaters had on the community,
including retail trade, property values, and the quality of urban life,
rather than the suppression of speech found within adult films. Id. at 48
(citations omitted). See also R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul, 505 U.S. 377, 389
(1992)("since words can in some circumstances violate laws directed not
against speech but against conduct ..., a particular content-based
subcategory of proscribable class of speech can be swept up incidentally
within the reach of a statute directed at conduct rather than speech.") In
a similar vein, the court finds that the Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance
does not aim to prohibit any unwanted message of panhandlers, but rather to
address other significant secondary interests stemming from unruly conduct
that might accompany panhandling. See, e.g., Young v. New York City Transit
Auth., 903 F.2d 146, 158 (2d. Cir.), cert. denied, 498 U.S. 984 (1990)
(regulation of panhandling aimed at maintaining public safety and
preventing physical contact, harassment, intimidation, and threats that
persons associate with panhandling); see also Patton v. Baltimore City,
Civil No. S 93-2389 at 62-65 (D. Md. Aug. 19, 1994) (compelling state
interests including protection of citizens and visitors, promotion of
tourism and business, and preservation of the quality of urban life
supported aggressive panhandling ordinance). Furthermore, the Aggressive
Panhandling Ordinance by its terms only regulates panhandling to the extent
that the begging individual employs threatening or assault-like conduct to
force accession to his or her demands. Like many other valid statutes, this
ordinance is primarily directed at extortionate conduct. Thus, with one
exception discussed infra, the ordinance appears narrowly tailored to
address the significant interests while affording panhandlers ample
channels with which to communicate their message.  </P>

<P>As the parties discussed during the hearing before the undersigned, the
court finds troubling the definitional clause in Section 106-85(a) that
sets forth the proscribed conduct under the phrase "forcing oneself upon
the company of another." According to the ordinance, a person has violated
this provision by " continuing to request, beg or solicit alms in close
proximity to the individual addressed after the person to whom the request
is directed has made a negative response" or other actions that one might
reasonably construe as compelling accession to the requests. See Section
106-85(a) (emphasis added). According to Plaintiffs, this definition is
overbroad because it encompasses harmless solicitation. It restricts a
beggar from presenting his request to a new person in close proximity to
another who has refused him.  </P>

<P>As far as this court can ascertain, the sole interest or secondary effect
that this definitional phrase is designed to protect is the insulation of a
person who declines to give money from the act of begging. Begging is not a
"senseless act of beauty" and its message may be disquietening. Arguably,
one might contend that the City has also a substantial interest in
protecting whatever sense of peace and solitude its citizens can find in a
bustling city. Yet, it is well established that the public expression of
ideas may not be proscribed based upon the victimization, sensitivity or
other reactions of the listener. See, e.g., R.A. V. v. City of St. Paul,
505 U.S. 377, 394 (1992); Boos v. Barry, 485 U.S. 312, 318-21 (1988);
Street v. New York, 394 U.S. 576, 590-92 (1969).  </P>

<P>In Boos v. Barry, for example, the Court invalidated an ordinance that
prohibited the display of a sign that brought a foreign government into
"public disrepute" within 500 feet of a foreign embassy. Boos, 485 U.S. at
315. The Court rejected the need to shield foreign embassy officials from
speech that was critical of their government. Id. at 321. In that instance,
the ordinance was not a content-neutral regulation focusing upon the
"secondary effects" of speech, but rather targeted particular speech with
an emotive impact based upon its content. Id. Unlike the majority of the
Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance, which seeks to address harms independent
of the content of the panhandler's message, this definition based upon
continued requests in close proximity to a person indicating a negative
response bases its proscription upon the reaction of the listener to
content. While the court has no doubt that Defendants could reconstruct a
definition that would pass constitutional muster, this phrase as it now
stands, fails to survive constitutional scrutiny.  </P>

<P>Finally, Plaintiffs also raise an Equal Protection Clause challenge to the
Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance based upon the ordinance's
underinclusivity because the ordinance only regulates conduct based upon
solicitation for alms. The court finds this to be a distinction without
significance. In Renton, the respondents raised a similar contention that
the zoning ordinance at issue had not regulated other adult businesses that
were also likely to trigger the same secondary effects as those of the
regulated adult film theaters. See Renton, 475 U.S. at 52-53. The Supreme
Court rejected that argument on two fronts: (1) the record did not contain
any evidence regarding other adult businesses in the city, and (2) the
Court was unwilling to assume that the city would not amend its ordinance
to include other businesses with the same proscribed secondary effects. Id.
(citing Williamson v. Lee Optical, 348 U.S. 483, 488-89 (1955)). The record
before the court does not suggest the existence of problems with conduct
accompanying noncharitable solicitation. Thus, the fact that Defendants
have begun to regulate aggressive solicitation only in the context of
panhandling does not by itself suggest invidious discrimination against
panhandlers in violation of the Equal Protection Clause. See Williamson,
348 U.S. at 489.  </P>

<P>Pursuant to Section 1-10 of the Code of Ordinances of the City of Atlanta,
see Ex. 2 Attached to Defendants' Memorandum in Opposition to Plaintiffs'
Motion for Temporary Restraining Order and Preliminary Injunction, the
unconstitutionality of one phrase of the Code shall not affect the validity
of the remaining portion of the Code. Accordingly, the motion for a
preliminary injunction enjoining the enforcement of the Aggressive
Panhandling Ordinance is GRANTED IN PART. The court, however, limits its
ruling to find that only the definition of "forcing oneself upon the
company of another" that prohibits "continuing to request, beg or solicit
alms in close proximity to the individual addressed after the person to
whom the request is directed has made a negative response" is
unconstitutional.  </P>


<P>B. THE PARKED VEHICLE ORDINANCE</P>

<P>In December 1995, the Atlanta City Council reenacted and the Mayor approved
Chapter 106, Article II, Offenses and Misdemeanors, Section 106-57, which
addresses "unauthorized persons on [a] parking lot." That ordinance
prohibited "any person to remain on any property which is used primarily as
a parking lot for vehicles unless such person has a vehicle parked on the
property, or is employed by the owner or manager of the property, or has
other lawful business on such property ...." On April 1, 1996, however, the
Atlanta City Council adopted in its place an amended section of the same
number entitled "Unauthorized Interference or Attempted Interference with
Parked Vehicles Ordinance (hereinafter "the Parked Vehicle Ordinance"). The
mayor approved this ordinance on April 9, 1996. This newly enacted
ordinance provides as follows:  </P>

<P>(a) It shall be unlawful for any person to loiter or prowl on any property
which is used to park vehicles, including parking lots for vehicles as set
out in the City of Atlanta Code of Ordinances, Chapter 30, Article XVII,
Division 3, Section 30-1196, et seq., and public right-of-way, if said
person has been observed:  </P>

<P>(1) attempting entry into vehicles, or</P>

<P>(2) tampering with the vehicle of another, which shall mean any
unauthorized interference with a vehicle or any part or accessory thereof
or any contents therein, or  </P>

<P>(3) otherwise acting in a manner not usual for law-abiding individuals
under circumstances that warrant justifiable and reasonable alarm or
immediate concern for the safety of persons or property in the vicinity  </P>

<P>(b) Among the circumstances which may be considered in determining whether
alarm is warranted is the fact that the person opens or attempts to open
the doors, trunk windows or hood of the vehicle; takes flight upon the
appearance of a law enforcement officer; manifestly endeavors to conceal
himself or any object that may be utilized for entry into an automobile or
is otherwise prohibited by law; removes or attempts to remove anything of
value from the vehicle; or otherwise causes damage to the vehicle.  </P>

<P>(c) A law enforcement officer shall, prior to any arrest for an offense
under this code section, afford the person an opportunity to dispel any
alarm or immediate concern which would otherwise be warranted by requesting
the person to identify himself and explain his presence and conduct. No
person shall be convicted of an offense under this code section:  </P>

<P>(i) unless the law enforcement officer complies with the foregoing
procedure; and (ii) unless the trier of fact determines beyond a reasonable
doubt under all circumstances of the case that the explanation was not true
or would not, if believed by the officer at the time, have dispelled the
officer's alarm or immediate concern.  </P>

<P>(d) Upon conviction of violation of this section, a person shall be
sentenced to imprisonment or public work for six (6) months, with a minimum
of sixty (60) days to serve in the city jail or working on the public
streets or on the public works of the city, the remainder of the time to be
prohibited.  </P>

<P>Section 106-57.</P>

<P>Plaintiffs assert that the Parked Vehicle Ordinance is unconstitutionally
vague. Defendants argue that Plaintiffs do not have standing to challenge
the current embodiment of the ordinance since no Plaintiff has been
arrested under it. Plaintiffs contend, however, that the arrests they have
suffered under the older version and fear that they will endure under the
new one bestow this court with jurisdiction to entertain their claim.  </P>

<P>Article III of the Constitution provides that "[t]he judicial Power shall
extend to all Cases . . . [and] Controversies." U.S. Constit. art. III,
Section 2. The "case or controversy" requirement mandates that, "at an
irreducible minimum, . . . the party who invokes the court's jurisdiction ;
. . [must] 'show that he personally has suffered some actual or threatened
injury as a result of the putatively illegal conduct of the defendant."'
Valley Forge Christian College v. Americans United for Separation of Church
and State, 454 U.S. 464, 472 (1982) (quoting Gladstone, Realtors v. Village
of Bellwood, 441 U.S. 91, 99 (1979)). While standing does not require that
parties expose themselves to prosecution, Steffel v. Thompson, 415 U.S.
452, 459 (1974), there must be an announced intention to engage in
violative conduct as well as a "credible threat of prosecution." Babbitt v.
United Farm Workers Nat'l Union, 442 U.S. 289, 298 (1979); Athens Lumber
Co., Inc. v. Federal Election Comm'n, 689 F.2d 1006, 1012 (11th Cir. 1982),
vacated on other grounds, 718 F.2d 363 (11th Cir. 1983), cert. denied, 465
U.S. 1092 (1984). The court will not have jurisdiction in situations where
the threat of enforcement of the statute is only "imaginary or
speculative." Younger v. Harris, 401 U.S. 37, 42 (1971).  </P>

<P>What constitutes a "credible threat of prosecution" has been the subject of
much analysis. In Doe v. Bolton, 410 U.S. 179, 188 (1973), the Supreme
Court held that physicians who performed abortions could challenge the
validity of the Georgia abortion statutes even though none of them had been
prosecuted or threatened with prosecution since the doctors were the ones
"against whom these criminal statutes directly operate[d]." In Graham v.
Butterworth, 5 F.3d 496, 499 (11th Cir. 1993), cert. denied, _ U.S. _, 114
S. Ct. 2136 (1994), a county court judge had standing to contest a Florida
election statute regulating payments for sponsored advertisements even
though he had not been prosecuted under it. The judge had violated the
provision in the prior election and intended to engage in the same behavior
during the coming one. Id. In Planned Parenthood Ass'n v. City of
Cincinnati, 822 F.2d 1390, 1396 (6th Cir. 1987), the Sixth Circuit held
that an abortion clinic had standing to contest a statute regulating the
disposal of fetal tissue because, even though it had not suffered
prosecution for a violation, the organization had announced its intention
to engage in the prohibited conduct. In all of these cases, the plaintiffs
were engaged in a course of established behavior that, while otherwise
legitimate, had become regulated by criminal statutes or malum prohibitum.7
</P> 

<P>In City of Los Angeles v. Lyons, 461 U.S. 95 (1983), however, the Supreme
Court found that it would be improper to grant a preliminary injunction to
a plaintiff who was injured after being placed in a chokehold by a police
officer following a stop for a traffic or vehicle code violation. The Court
held that the plaintiff did not have the requisite standing because there
was no "real and immediate threat" that the plaintiff would again be
stopped for such an infraction, that the plaintiff would neither provoke
the officers nor resist, and that the police would apply the very dangerous
subduction technique. Id. at 105. It appears to this court that the Supreme
Court refused to assume that the recurrence of conduct that was malum in se
was inevitable. Accordingly, a "credible threat of prosecution" did not
exist.  </P>

<P>The illegal behavior at issue in the instant case -- attempting entry into
vehicles, tampering with vehicles, and "acting in a manner not usual for
law-abiding individuals under circumstances that warrant a justifiable and
reasonable alarm or immediate concern for the safety of persons or property
in the vicinity" -- is malum in se. Accordingly, this court finds that the
facts of the instant case are more closely analogous to those in Lyons and
will refuse to assume that future violations of the Parked Vehicle
Ordinance are inevitable. This conclusion is bolstered by the evidence in
the record that, of all of the arrests of the seven plaintiffs, none has
been for violations of the current version of the ordinance and only two
have occurred under the former embodiment. The dearth of prosecutions
demonstrates to this court that there in no great likihood[sic] that any of
the plaintiffs will be arrested for a violation of any portion of the
ordinance that, abstractly, might be troublesome.8 The court must conclude,
therefore, that Plaintiffs do not have standing to assert a constitutional
challenge to the Parked Vehicle Ordinance.9  </P>


<P>C. 42 U.S.C. Section 1983 VIOLATIONS BASED UPON THE CUSTOM, PRACTICE. OR
POLICY OF THE CITY OF ATLANTA  </P>

<P>Plaintiffs allege that Defendants are liable pursuant to 42 U.S.C. Section
1983 for depriving Plaintiffs of their constitutional rights based upon two
theories: (1) Defendants' persistent practice of violating the
constitutional rights of Plaintiffs and other homeless persons, and (2)
Defendants' inadequate training of police officers. To establish liability
under Section 1983, Plaintiffs must show that Defendants had a policy,
custom or widespread practice that is the "moving force" behind the
constitutional deprivations. Brooks v. Scheib, 813 F.2d 1191, 1193 (11th
Cir. 1987) (citing Monell v. Department of Social Servs., 436 U.S. 658,
690-94 (1978)); see also DePew v. City of St. Mary's, 787 F.2d 1496, 1499
(11th Cir. 1986). Although the official policy-makers of the municipality
need not formally approve the "custom" in order for liability to attach,
Church v. City of Huntsville, 30 F.3d 1332, 1342-43 (11th Cir. 1994),
"actual or constructive knowledge of such customs must be attributed to the
governing body of the municipality." Id. at 1345 (citing Depew, 787 F.2d at
1499).  </P>

<P>As for Plaintiffs' first theory of liability, this court is satisfied that
Plaintiffs have produced sufficient evidence at this stage of the
proceedings to demonstrate that a number of officers have effectuated
arrests of the homeless without probable cause in violation of Plaintiffs'
Fourth Amendment rights. Yet, as discussed below, this court cannot
determine that the City of Atlanta had knowledge of such a custom in order
to grant the relief now sought.  </P>

<P>In Depew v. City of St. Mary's, 787 F.2d 1496 (11th Cir. 1986), a civil
rights action based upon the use of excessive force, the plaintiffs
introduced evidence of two prior specific incidents in which citizens filed
complaints of police brutality. Id. at 1497-98. Although individual council
members admitted that they were aware of these incidents and that some
investigations had ensued, the evidence showed that the mayor and council
members largely discounted the alleged victims' complaints, denied
allegations of impropriety, and affirmed the actions of the officers
involved. Id. Thus, the Eleventh Circuit determined that the city had
knowledge of improper conduct in which police officers had used
unreasonable force, but did not take any remedial action. Id. at 1499.  </P>

<P>In contrast, the four homeless witnesses in the Church case provided
testimony concerning expulsion of the homeless from public parks, arrests
for public intoxication, and other alleged police harassment that had
occurred over several years. See Church, 30 F.3d at 1345-46. The plaintiffs
recounted few of the incidents with specific detail. Id. at 1345. The
plaintiffs also relied upon a two-year-old demographic study instituted
from within the police department that generally outlined "rousting" of the
homeless by the City of Huntsville police. Id. Amidst doubts that the
evidence supported a finding that the defendants had a custom of
constitutional violations, the Eleventh Circuit concluded that plaintiffs
had failed to present evidence that the City Council or Mayor had actual or
constructive specific knowledge of the incidents involving the homeless
witnesses. Id. at 1346.  </P>

<P>The evidence in the case at bar pales in comparison to the records
developed in Depew and Church. The limited discovery did reveal that a
number of leading city officials, including Mayor Campbell and Police Chief
Harvard, were on notice of general allegations of police harassment and
fear of the homeless regarding police misconduct and homeless sweeps. In
addition, Chief of the Department of Corrections Pocock was aware that the
arrest statistics for homeless persons had vastly increased in 1995. After
conducting his own inquiry, Pocock discussed his findings with Sue Ellen
Crosslea, the Director of the Bureau of Human Services. However, the record
is devoid of evidence that these officials had knowledge of specific
instances of present or past police misconduct that suggested police
officers were violating Fourth Amendment rights. Based upon this circuit's
authority, Plaintiffs cannot rest upon the fact that Defendants were aware
of generalized allegations of homeless sweeps or of police misconduct in
order to attribute constructive knowledge of the alleged constitutional
violations. See also Brooks v. Scheib, 813 F.2d 1191, 1193 (11th Cir. 1987)
(no evidence of knowledge of past police misconduct where plaintiff failed
to show numerous complaints lodged alleging police misconduct had merit).  </P>

<P>Plaintiffs also claim that Defendants are liable for failing to provide
adequate training to their police officers. To establish liability under
this theory, Plaintiffs must show that the City failed to train their
officers in the execution of their duties, and that this failure
constituted a city policy. Kerr v. City of West Palm Beach, 875 F.2d 1546,
1555 (11th Cir. 1989) (citing City of Canton v. Harris, 489 U.S. 378, 388
(1989)). In order to constitute a policy, the City's failure to provide
more or different training under the circumstances must demonstrate a
"deliberate indifference" to the rights of its citizens. Canton, 489 U. S.
at 388; Kerr, 875 F.2d at 1555. Although a review of the record clearly
supports a finding of negligence on the part of the City of Atlanta in the
level of training provided in regard to the treatment of the homeless and
the ordinances at issue, the court cannot determine that the City's failure
to train amounts to "deliberate indifference" based upon the record as
developed.  </P>

<P>"Deliberate indifference" exists when the need for additional or different
training becomes obvious based upon apparent unconstitutional actions or
abuses occurring in its absence. See Belcher v. City of Foley, 30 F.3d
1390, 1397 (11th Cir. 1994) (citing Canton, 489 U.S. at 390). For example,
in Kerr v. City of West Palm Beach, 875 F.2d 1546 (11th Cir. 1989), a case
involving the use of excessive force during the apprehension of suspects
with a canine unit, the evidence revealed that not only were suspects
frequently injured during apprehension, but also that officers filed
reports whenever a dog bite occurred which supervisory officials then
reviewed. Id. at 1556. Based upon this evidence, the Eleventh Circuit
vacated a judgment n.o.v. and determined that the whole of the evidence
demonstrated that "the unconstitutional character of many of the canine
unit's apprehensions was plainly obvious to City officials." Id.  </P>

<P>As indicated above, the facts and evidence in the instant case do not make
it clear that the need for training was readily apparent to City
Defendants. The essence of the allegation underlying this Section 1983
claim is that Defendants have a custom in which officers frisk, detain and
effectuate arrests of the homeless without probable cause or reasonable
suspicion in violation of the Fourth Amendment. Yet, at most, Defendants
were aware of only generalized reports of police misconduct or homeless
sweeps. There is no evidence in the record that any homeless person
including Plaintiffs or advocates on behalf of the homeless initiated a
formal or informal complaint or provided more specific information that
might have informed city officials that police officers had exceeded their
constitutional authority in violation of the Fourth Amendment. Had it been
shown that the Mayor had been faced with the Plaintiffs' affidavits or the
one hundred sixty-one declarations that were submitted to this court, the
court very likely would reach a different conclusion. In the absence of
evidence of particular allegations that officers had violated the Fourth
Amendment rights, however, the court cannot infer that the need for greater
training in this area of the law was obvious to city officials.  </P>

<P>Plaintiffs met their burden in producing uncontested evidence demonstrating
that a number of officers have effectuated arrests of the homeless without
probable cause in violation of Plaintiffs' Fourth Amendment rights. Based
upon the record developed, including over one hundred declarations of the
homeless and the unrebutted incidents outlined in Plaintiffs' affidavits,
it is clear that city officials have received sufficient notice of these
events in order to establish a custom in the future. However, because this
court cannot determine that the City of Atlanta had sufficient knowledge of
such a custom in order to grant the relief now sought, Plaintiffs' motion
for a preliminary injunction seeking to enjoin Defendants from encroaching
upon the Fourth Amendment rights of Plaintiffs is DENIED.  </P>


<P>IV. CONCLUSION</P>

<P>For the foregoing reasons, Plaintiffs' motion for a preliminary injunction
is GRANTED IN PART and DENIED IN PART.  </P>

<P>SO ORDERED this 17th day of July, 1996.</P>

<P>/s/<BR>
J. OWEN FORRESTER<BR>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT JUDGE</P>


<P><B>ENDNOTES</B></P>

<FONT SIZE="-1"><P>1. Throughout this order the court refers to the class of citizens as
"homeless," but the plaintiffs acknowledge that the group includes the
homeless, the poor, the shabbily dressed street person who may have
shelter, and even professional panhandlers.  </P>

<P>2. For example, the Chief of the Department of Corrections, Tom Pocock,
indicated that the reports "that an inordinate number" of homeless persons
were imprisoned caused him to track the record of homeless arrests that
occurred in 1995. Pocock Dep. at 36-37. Pocock shared the results of his
tracking with Sue Ellen Crosslea, the Director of the Bureau of Human
Services. Id. at 37; see also Memorandum to Sue Ellen Crosslea, Attached to
Pocock Dep. 10  </P>

<P>3. At the hearing on July 11, 1996, the court granted Defendants' request
to submit full copies of the original depositions, which the parties
conducted during the expedited discovery and upon which both parties relied
in their briefs in support of and opposition to this motion. Accordingly,
Defendants delivered these materials on the morning of Monday, July 15,
1996. Defendants, however, have also provided the court with other
materials that they represent as omitted from the record, discussed during
the depositions, or otherwise relevant to the matters now before the court.
As the court has indicated previously, the record was closed at the start
of the hearing on July 11, 1996. Thus, to the extent that Defendants are
seeking leave to submit additional material in opposition to this motion,
Defendants' request is DENIED.  </P>

<P>4. In their brief in support of their motion for a temporary restraining
order and preliminary injunction, Plaintiffs had cited to the Aggressive
Panhandling Ordinance as Chapter 3, Section 17-3006. See Ex. 22 to
Defendants' Memorandum in Opposition to Plaintiffs' Motion for Preliminary
Injunction. That ordinance also prohibited begging and soliciting alms by
accosting or forcing oneself upon the company of another. Id. During the
initial hearing on June 16, 1996, however, the parties clarified that
Section 17-3006, which the City Council and the Mayor adopted and approved
in July 1977, was the predecessor of the current ordinance. Thus, although
the substantive language of the ordinance at issue remains essentially
unaltered, the Aggressive Panhandling Ordinance currently in effect is
found at Chapter 106 Offenses and Misdemeanors, Section 106-85.  </P>

<P>5. See Young v. New York City Transit Auth., 903 F.2d 146, 153-54 (2d.
Cir.), cert. denied, 498 U.S. 984 (1990); but see, Loper v. New York City
Police Dept., 999 F.2d 699, 704 (2d Cir. 1993).  </P>

<P>6. See, e.g., Village of Schaumberg v. Citizens for a Better Environment,
444 U.S. 620, 644 (1980) (Rehnquist, J., dissenting)("I believe that a
simple request for money lies far from the core protections of the First
Amendment...."). If begging is protected, it is most likely that it is as
commercial speech.  </P>

<P>7. Courts have also applied this rationale when a police custom or
practice, rather than a criminal statute, is being challenged. In Church v.
City of Huntsville, 30 F.3d 1332, 1337-39 (11th Cir. 1994), the Eleventh
Circuit found that the plaintiffs had standing to seek injunctive relief
against the city for its alleged practice of arresting and harassing the
plaintiffs on the basis of their homeless status. The arrests were for
eating, sleeping, and bathing in public and, as such, were attempting to
regulate behavior that was, at most, malum prohibitum.  </P>

<P>8. At the hearing for the preliminary injunction, this court announced
that, if Plaintiffs were to establish standing to contest the Parked
Vehicle Ordinance, the court would hold Section 106-57(a)(3)
unconstitutionally vague due to its failure to provide adequate notice to
ordinary persons as to what behavior would result in a violation.
Additionally, the court would have followed the rationale of Fields v. City
of Omaha, 810 F.2d 830, 832-34 (8th Cir. 1987), wherein the Eighth Circuit
ruled that a statute with a provision similar to that contained in section
106-57(c) was void for vagueness due to its failure to provide standards to
guide the discretion of police officers and prevent "arbitrary and
discriminatory law enforcement."  </P>

<P>9. Plaintiffs' argument that the two arrests under the predecessor statute
confers standing does not alter this conclusion. Plaintiffs cited to
Leverett v. City of Pinellas Park, 775 F.2d 1536, 1539 (11th Cir. 1985),
wherein the Eleventh Circuit held that Plaintiffs who had been arrested and
prosecuted under the earlier versions of the criminal ordinance restricting
nude dancing in commercial establishments where food and alcohol were
served had standing to challenge the current statute. Leverett can be
distinguished from the instant case for the same reason discussed supra --
that standing exists when the parties intend to continue a course of
conduct that is malum prohibitum but not for violations that are malum in
se. In Leverett, the regulated activities were merely malum prohibitum
while those in the instant case are malum in se. Accordingly, Leverett is
inapposite to the standing inquiry before the court.  </P>
</FONT>
