<blockquote>
<H3>Seminar Library</H3>


<P><B>"City Assigns Times, Places to Demonstrate" </B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE="-1">By Lolita Browning, Staff Reporter</FONT></B><BR>
<I><B><FONT SIZE="-1">Fulton County Daily Report</I>, July 15, 1996</FONT> </B></P>

<P>Planning to stage a protest when the world visits Atlanta during the
Olympics? Please take a number. </P>

<P>As a security measure, the Atlanta Police Department is assigning sites and
times for protesters, who must submit permit applications to the police
department, says Police Chief Beverly Harvard. </P>

<P>"The city wants to accommodate the First Amendment needs of the people that
come into the city," says Robin J. Shahar, an assistant city attorney
working with law enforcement officials. </P>

<P>While people have the right to protest, says Senior Assistant City Attorney
Kendric E. Smith, the city has the right to regulate them as to the time,
manner and place. </P>

<P>"The idea was to get the sites at the places we thought people wanted to
be," he says. </P>

<P>If you want to watch a demonstration, here are the venues: </P>

<P>l Techwood Drive at 10th Street, west of Interstate 75/85, on the northeast
corner, west of the median (Olympic venue). </P>

<P>l Northside Drive and Marietta Street, on the grass where Northside and
Marietta intersect (aquatics venue site). </P>

<P>#l Rhodes Street at Northside Drive between Electric and Northside (Georgia
Dome). </P>

<P>#l Techwood Drive north of Marietta Street between Walton and International
(Centennial Park site). </P>

<P>l Greensferry and Lee Street, at the intersection away from MLK Chapel side
(Atlanta University Center). </P>

<P>l Martin Luther King Jr. Drive and Tatnell Street, on the Morris Brown
College side, away from the Phyllis Wheatley YWCA (Clark Atlanta
University). </P>

<P>l Capitol Avenue and the Interstate 20 east access road (stadium venue
sites and the pedestrian corridor). </P>

<P>So far a handful of organizations have submitted applications, says Atlanta
Police Sgt. Gerrick R. Roper, of the department's Olympic Planning Office.
In addition, the office has received five inquires about the procedures,
Roper says. </P>

<P>A similar plan was enforced during the Democratic National Convention in
1988. The city roped off a parking lot at Marietta Street and Techwood
Drive across from the CNN Center, notes Smith. A stage was set up with a
sound system, and water was provided, he recalls. </P>

<P>"The protesters had permits for specified time periods, and when their time
was up, the sound was cut off," he says, adding that the plan ran smoothly.</P>


<P>But with far more people coming, Smith says, more sites are needed. </P>

<P><H3>More People, More Problems?</H3></P>

<P>"The two events are very different," he says. "The scale of the Olympics
... is far greater than that of the Democratic Convention. The Olympics
brings huge volumes of people, making it more difficult to control." </P>

<P>In itself, the city's policy does not bother the attorney for at least one
advocacy group that defends First Amendment rights. Gerald R. Weber,
counsel for the American Civil Liberties Union of Georgia, says designating
specific sites "makes sense." </P>

<P>"Logistically, it's going to be easier for the demonstrators and the city,"
Weber says. </P>

<P>But Weber says the city has not given demonstrators enough room at the
sites. He says he is concerned that some demonstrators will not fit within
the designated boundaries. He says ACLU members will observe protests to
see that everything is done properly. And he says people should not be
prohibited from expressing opinions in parks or on streets as long as they
don't interfere with traffic. </P>

<P>The city has not indicated what it plans to do to groups protesting in
nondesignated areas. Smith says it depends on the incident. Anyone can
leaflet on the sidewalks, he says. </P>

<P>"This procedure is for someone who wants to hold a demonstration," he says.
"It's not intended to cover everything in the city of Atlanta as it relates
to the First Amendment." </P>

<P>Protesters will not be allowed to demonstrate in streets that are not
blocked off specifically for demonstrators, Smith says. </P>

<P>And whoever has the permit for a particular spot has to be there with the
permit representing the group, he adds. </P>

<P><H3>Limited Time Offer</H3></P>

<P>Officer Roper says the city will not let any group monopolize a site for
long. Interviews with the heads of two organizations provide illustrations.</P>


<P>Dr. Scott Noren of Kansas City, Mo., is one applicant. A resident in oral
and maxillofacial surgery, Noren plans to have 200 participants promoting
powerlifting as an Olympic sporting event on July 20, the first Saturday of
the Games. </P>

<P>At first he wanted the entire four hours from 2 p.m. to 6 p.m. At first the
city offered him an hour. They compromised on 3 p.m. to 4 p.m. and 5 p.m.
to 6 p.m. </P>

<P>Robert P. Kunst, president of Shalom International, a Jewish organization,
asked to protest from July 18 to 21 from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. in front of the
Georgia World Congress Center. </P>

<P>But Kunst, of Miami, Fla. has been assigned to July 18 and 19 from noon to
2 p.m., he says. </P>

<P>"They seem to be limiting it to certain times and certain people," he says.
"As a First Amendment issue, I don't think there should be a limitation. If
I have the strength to stand in the hot sun and dehydrate to protest, that
is my First Amendment right. </P>

<P>"People should be allowed to be there as long a they want to be there." </P>

<P>But he says he understands the security issues involved. </P>

<P>"I don't want to make life more complicated. I would prefer to have four
days, but I am satisfied with the two," he says. </P>

<P>Kunst's group will be demonstrating against two corporate sponsors of the
Olympics: BMW/Mercedes and McDonald's. He claims BMW used people as "slave
laborers" in its shops during World War II and now refuses to compensate
the survivors. And he claims that the 1995 opening of a McDonald's
restaurant across from the Dachau concentration camp in Germany is
insensitive. </P>

<P>In response to the claims against the German manufacturer, Thomas O.
McGurin, general manager of corporate relations for BMW, says, "BMW was
nationalized during the war. So the use of slave labor wasn't a corporate
decision. It was a decision made by the German government. </P>

<P>"I think BMW should be judged on what it has done during the postwar period
rather than during the war," McGurin says, noting the corporation's
investments in the former eastern zones. </P>

<P>No one from McDonald's returned a call for comment.   </P>

<P><I>Lolita Browning's e-mail address is <a href="mailto:lbrowning@counsel.com">lbrowning@counsel.com</a>. </I></P>


